<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Child-Zimbabwe     02-29 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child-Zimbabwe,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diplomat's Son Returned to Zimbabwe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 9-year-old son of a Zimbabwean diplomat
who had been accused of abusing the boy has been returned to his
native land, according to a published report.
   U.S. officials said Terence Karamba left New York for Zimbabwe
on Sunday, accompanied by a Zimbabwean social worker, but was not
to be returned to his father's custody, The Washington Post
reported in Tuesday's editions.
   The boy was to be placed in foster care under the auspices of
the courts and the Zimbabwean Ministry of Social Welfare, said
Robert J. McMahon, director of the social services agency that had
cared for the boy for the past two months.
   McMahon, executive director of St. Christopher-Ottile Services
for Children and Families, said the Karamba family would undergo
counseling in hopes of eventually being reunited with Terence.
   ``With any of these cases, there's always a lump at the bottom
of your stomach, but I think the level of risk is as low as you can
possibly get it,'' McMahon told the newspaper.
   A city agency had charged that the boy's father, Floyd, had
beaten the boy and the child in December was removed from his home
and placed in foster care.
   The father, who served for more than a year as a member of
Zimbabwe's delegation to the United Nations, was ordered to leave
the United States because of what State Department officials called
``clear evidence of child abuse.''
   In January, the Supreme Court refused to block the U.S.
government from sending the boy home after the Legal Aid Society's
Juvenile Rights Division had argued that the boy was afraid to go
home.
   McMahon said Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., interceded
and persuaded the State Department that the boy should not be
returned immediately.
   ``We received what we asked for, which was time to work with the
boy, said Gary Kipling, a St. Christopher-Ottilie official who
served as Terence's foster father part of the time.
   The State Department had a psychiatric consultant accompany the
boy on his trip home and also engaged a law firm in Zimbabwe to
monitor his case, the Post reported.
</TEXT>
