<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO-Shultz     02-29 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Shultz,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Denounces U.S. Mideast Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Shultz, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat met Monday with
five Western diplomats and delivered messages about the ``dangers''
of the U.S. plan for a Middle East peace settlement, the
Palestinian WAFA news agency reported.
   It said Arafat met with the ambassadors of France, Britain,
Greece, Spain and Turkey in Tunis, the headquarters of the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   WAFA said Arafat asked the diplomats to transmit to their
nations his concern about ``the dangers to the Palestinian people
of the new American demarche.''
   A two-day summit conference of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization is to open Wednesday in Brussels, Belgium, with
President Reagan among the leaders scheduled to attend.
   According to WAFA, Arafat's messages said the U.S. plan proposed
by Secretary of State George Shultz on his Mideast tour ``ignores
the national rights of the Palestinian people, notably their right
to self-determination and the creation of an independent state on
their own territory under the PLO, the sole, legitimate
representative.''
   Shultz has called for a Palestinian role in negotiations, but
not participation by the PLO.
</TEXT>
