<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0770 02-29 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0770,0376</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Turner; No separates moved for the AMs cycle.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>James Douglas</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James H. Douglas Jr., an Air Force
secretary under President Dwight D. Eisenhower who presided over
the planning and construction of the Air Force Academy in Colorado
Springs, Colo., died Wednesday. He was 88.
   Douglas graduated from Princeton University after serving as an
Army officer in World War I. He earned a law degree from Harvard in
1924.
   Douglas, an attorney and investment banker, also served for two
years as deputy secretary of defense beginning in 1959. He held a
high post in the Treasury Department under Presidents Herbert
Hoover and Franklin D. Roosevelt. Douglas was appointed
undersecretary of the Air Force in 1953 and secretary in 1957.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joseph Kiselewski</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONG PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph Kiselewski, an internationally
known sculptor, died Friday at the age of 87.
   Kiselewski work included the World War II Memorial in Holland's
Veterans Cemetery, the statue of Harold Vanderbilt in Nashville,
Tenn., and four plaques for the House chamber of the Capitol in
Washington, D.C.
   He received many awards for his work, including the Prix de Rome
and the Beaux Arts Prize and he's listed in Who's Who in America.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Beatrice Burns</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beatrice Major Van Fleet Burns, the wife of
former governor of Hawaii John Anthony Burns, died Sunday at age 82.
   Burns was elected governor of Hawaii in 1962. Mrs. Burns served
as Hawaii's first lady for 12 years. Her husband died in April
1975.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Leslie Turner</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leslie H. Turner, 88, the artist who wrote
and illustrated the ``Captain Easy'' adventure comic strip for 27
years, died Sunday.
   Turner graduated with an English degree in 1922 from Southern
Methodist University in Dallas. Considered one of the top magazine
illustrators of the 1920s and '30s, Turner was best remembered for
``Captain Easy,'' which at its peak appeared in more than 600 daily
newspapers.
   The strip addressed unpleasant subjects such as alcoholism as
early as 1949, and it won praise for being scientifically correct.
Turner wrote and illustrated ``Captain Easy'' until he retired in
1970.
</TEXT>
