<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0039EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BeyondHumphreyland     02-29 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beyond Humphreyland,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Simon's Skip-the-South Strategy Defies Arithmetic</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may be the most implausible gambit of the
year, or the most naive, or just the dumbest _ but there isn't any
doubt that Paul Simon's decision to skip the South on Super Tuesday
turns 1988 political theology on its head.
   ``We urged him to take a Midwestern industrial strategy,'' said
Illinois Democratic Chairman Vince Demuzio, perhaps with a straight
face.
   The accepted dogma is that no Democrat in this lifetime will
grace the White House without winning a fair share of states in the
South.
   It's simple arithmetic. The Republicans have had a lock on the
West; they've done whatever it takes to win California and they've
added support from the farm belt and the upper reaches of New
England.
   Democrats _ who won ``Hubert Humphreyland'' in 1984, but little
else _ generally can rely on some industrial states, the islands of
Hawaii and the four corners of the District of Columbia.
   Of course that doesn't add up to a Democratic victory in the
Electoral College and during a 20-year stretch, the Republicans
have lost the White House just once, to Georgia's Jimmy Carter.
   And so party leaders agree the Democrats must work the South;
the need for a Southern strategy was an underlying rationale for
creating next week's Super Tuesday primaries and is one explanation
for the tremendous effort being poured into the region this week by
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, Jesse Jackson, Rep. Richard
Gephardt of Missouri and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee.
   But not Paul Simon.
   Simon is the senator from Illinois whose campaign is
floundering, to be polite. After a second-place finish in Iowa,
third-place finishes in New Hampshire and Minnesota and a complete
collapse in South Dakota, he is out of money and out of the running.
   The book of campaign etiquette says this is where Simon thanks
his staff, thanks his supporters and gets out of the race _ perhaps
throwing his endorsement to a candidate who shares his values.
Maybe Dukakis, or maybe a dramatic, home-state boost for Jackson.
   Yes, that's the way it's generally done.
   Simon embraced the etiquette just after New Hampshire.
   ``If I don't win either Minnesota or South Dakota, I'm going to
drop out of the race,'' he said. ``I don't want to just continue
indefinitely running second or third.''
   He expressed high hopes for victory, declaring, ``The place
where my natural roots are is right here in Hubert Humphreyland.''
   The logic was unassailable but his resolve didn't last.
   Before 24 hours, Simon was hedging ``because of the reaction
we've been getting from around the country.'' (Whose reaction was
he talking about? Certainly not the reaction of the voters in
Hubert Humphreyland; he finished just behind uncommitted, just
behind Jackson and way behind Dukakis.)
   And so Simon announced that he's going to skip the South and
pick up in Illinois on March 15, in Michigan on March 26, and so
on. He says the Southern vote will be ``scattered'' and that,
``We're not going to have a first-ballot nominee. We're going to
have a very open convention.''
   Fair enough. But will the convention turn to Paul Simon?
   The dogma of 1988 says the last thing the Democrats will do is
nominate a candidate who bypassed the South. He could put Minnie
Pearl on his ticket and it wouldn't keep the Republicans from
rubbing their hands together in excitement.
   Not that Simon is talking about a Southerner for his ticket. No,
he's got a ``Midwestern industrial strategy.'' In Michigan the
other day he said he'd want to consider Lee Iacocca as a running
mate.
   It's possible that Simon, blinded by presidential ambition,
simply does not see this strategy as futile. But Simon didn't enter
the race until failing to draft Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas, so
blind ambition doesn't ring true. And naive, or stupid, he is not.
   Instead, this skip-the-South gambit is probably a reluctant
deference to local pols who want to ride his home-state coattails
into Atlanta.
   ``There are people in Illinois who want to go to the convention
and who are Simon delegates,'' Simon said last week.
   That's all well and good for them, but Simon himself stands to
become a quintessential spoiler, draining votes from compatible
liberal candidates without a prayer of winning himself. In return,
he might hope to amass the kind of good will in Illinois Democratic
clubrooms that provides an uncontested primary for re-election in
1990.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan Wolman is assistant bureau chief in
Washington for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
