<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0834,1245</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Celli and Douglas. AMs separates moved on Zhang, a0722,
and Hardin, a0814. An AMs separate on Kuenn also moved on sports
circuits.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Harvey Kuenn</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvey Kuenn, a former hard-hitting major
leaguer who managed the Milwaukee Brewers to their only World
Series appearance, died at home Sunday at age 57.
   Kuenn, the 1953 American League Rookie of the Year and the 1959
AL batting champion, had been the Brewers' major-league scouting
consultant since 1983.
   In 1982, after taking over the Brewers in June, he led Milwaukee
to the World Series. The Brewers lost to the St. Louis Cardinals in
seven games. He was fired after Milwaukee finished fifth in its
division the following season.
   Under Kuenn, the hard-hitting Brewers were known as Harvey's
Wallbangers, Kuenn had a lifetime batting average of .303 in 15
major-league seasons with Detroit, Cleveland, San Francisco, the
Chicago Cubs and Philadelphia. He retired as a player in 1966.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Amy Lynn Hardin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAHOKIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amy Lynn Hardin, who underwent a liver
transplant at 11 months thanks to vigorous community fund-raising,
died at home Saturday at the age of 5.
   Amy was born with biliary atresia, in which the bile ducts
malfunction and the liver becomes hard. She underwent surgery when
she was 6 weeks old and again at 3 months, but the operations were
unsuccessful.
   Doctors said her only chance for survival was a liver
transplant. Community residents rallied to raise more than $260,000
for the operation. The rock group Kiss gave a benefit concert, and
President Reagan sent a letter of support.
   The liver Amy received on May 10, 1983, began to fail around
Thanksgiving, and she returned to the hospital for a month, said
her mother, Robin Hardin.
   ``She couldn't stand it anymore,'' Mrs. Hardin said. ``We made a
promise that we wouldn't take her back to the hospital. We brought
her home and the family took turns being with her.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Louis Zhang Jiashu</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis Zhang Jiashu, bishop of Shanghai under
China's independent Catholic Church, died Thursday at age 96, the
official Xinhua News Agency reported.
   The ``Patriotic'' Catholic Church in China broke with the
Vatican in 1957 after accusing Rome of interfering in China's
internal affairs. The church claims more than 3 million followers
in China.
   Xinhua said Zhang studied in Britain and France for 10 years
before returning to China in 1924. In 1960, he was elected bishop
of the Shanghai diocese, which has an estimated 100,000
parishioners and about 20 churches.
   The report said he was vice chairman of the China Patriotic
Catholic Association.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Edward M. Knabusch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward M. Knabusch, who began making chairs
in a garage behind his father's home in the 1920s and founded the
La-Z-Boy Chair Co. with his cousin, died Thursday at age 88.
   Knabusch and cousin Edwin J. Shoemaker built novelty chairs such
as The Gossiper, a telephone stand with a built-in seat, before
modifying a wooden porch chair so its seat moved forward as its
back reclined.
   On the advice of dealers they made an upholstered version. In
1929, the La-Z-Boy recliner was patented, and in 1941 the La-Z-Boy
Chair Co. was incorporated. Sales topped $420 million in the
company's 1987 fiscal year.
   The company halted chair production during World War II to make
seats and backs for tanks, torpedo boats, turret guns and armored
cars.
   Knabusch resigned as chairman in 1985 but continued as a
director. Shoemaker, 81, continues as vice chairman, executive vice
president of engineering and a director.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Mary Dunhill</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mary Dunhill, the last surviving child of Alfred
Dunhill, founder of the tobacco and pipe-making company, died
Wednesday at age 81.
   The only daughter among Dunhill's four children, Ms. Dunhill
joined the board of Dunhill Holdings in 1944, explaining ``they
were rather short of men,'' and in 1961 became chairman, succeeding
her eldest brother, Alfred.
   ``Miss Mary,'' as she was known, became president when she
retired as chairman in 1975, and continued to work two days a week.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Emelyn Jewett</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emelyn Jewett, daughter of former Oakland
Tribune publisher Sen. William Knowland and a former president of
the newspaper, died of cancer Thursday. She was 59.
   Jewett had served on the Tribune board of directors since 1950
and was named president upon her father's death in 1974. She was
senior vice president of the Tribune Publishing Co. through three
other owners, resigning in 1985.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Marjorie Holwill Breffeilh</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marjorie Holwill Breffeilh, commander of
the Women's Army Volunteer Corps in the Hawaiian Islands during
World War II, died Thursday of complications following surgery. She
was 76.
   Breffeilh fled Shanghai, China, after the Japanese bombed the
International Settlement, where she had lived with her parents for
20 years.
   She was put in charge of volunteer women's services and given
the rank of major when the bombing of Pearl Harbor forced
evacuation of the regular Women's Army Corp.
   Her volunteers performed clerical and administrative chores for
the military during the war.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Gene Vincent de Paul</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Composer, pianist and musical arranger Gene
Vincent de Paul, whose collaboration with lyricist Don Raye on the
song ``Pigfoot Pete'' earned them an Oscar nomination, died
Saturday at age 68.
   De Paul worked with Johnny Mercer on music for the 1954 film
``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers'' and the Broadway play ``L'il
Abner.''
   He and Raye were nominated for an Academy Award in 1942 for
``Pigfoot Pete'' from the film ``Hellzapoppin.''
   Among his biggest hits were ``Cow Cow Boogie,'' ``Star Eyes,''
``Irresistible,'' ``When You're in Love'' and ``Mr. Five by Five.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>James H. Douglas Jr.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James H. Douglas Jr., who as Air Force
secretary under President Dwight D. Eisenhower presided over the
planning and construction of the Air Force Academy in Colorado
Springs, Colo., died Wednesday at age 88.
   Douglas, an attorney and investment banker, also served for two
years as deputy secretary of defense beginning in 1959.
   He held a high post in the Treasury Department under Presidents
Herbert Hoover and Franklin D. Roosevelt. He was appointed
undersecretary of the Air Force in 1953 and secretary in 1957.
   A native of Cedar Rapids, Iowa, Douglas graduated from Princeton
University after serving as an Army officer in World War I. He
earned a law degree from Harvard in 1924.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Vincenzo Celli</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vincenzo Celli, former principal dancer
and choreographer at La Scala Opera House in Milan and the last
pupil of ballet master Enrico Cecchetti, died Sunday at age 87.
   Born in Salerno, Italy, Celli immigrated to the United States
with his parents in 1904. Celli said he was inspired at age 14
when, as an usher in a Chicago theater, he saw Nijinsky dance with
the Diaghilev Company.
   Celli studied for six years with Cecchetti, the teacher of
Nijinsky and Pavlova. He debuted at La Scala in 1926 in
``Petrouchka'' and was named ballet master in 1929, a post he held
for 12 years.
   Later he opened a studio in New York and taught ballet for 40
years. His pupils included Alicia Markova, Jerome Robbins and Agnes
DeMille.
</TEXT>
