<1ST_LINE>r p PM-WyomingCaucuses     02-29 0789</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wyoming Caucuses,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Western Test This Week In Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyoming this week becomes the first state
in the West to allocate presidential delegates, but the contest has
gotten relatively little attention in the rush to the Super Tuesday
states.
   Still, state officials and Wyoming political leaders are touting
their caucuses this Saturday as the kickoff contest in the region,
saying results in the state will help set the stage for larger
contests to come.
   ``We have a real potential to influence the process, especially
since we're the first Western state'' to assign delegates, said
Muffy Moore, state Democratic Party chairman.
   ``It's not our numbers that are important. It's our position on
the calendar,'' she added.
   The Wyoming caucuses are three days before Super Tuesday, March
8, when 20 states, mainly Southern and border states, will hold
caucuses and primaries.
   Wyoming's caucus process, according to Republican and Democratic
campaign directors, calls for little in the way of media
advertising. Instead, campaign staffers spend most of their days on
the phones to individuals who will attend the county conventions.
   ``You make the calls. You make the personal contacts. This is a
retail state,'' said Mickey Munley, a co-director for Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s Wyoming campaign. ``Down South, there are so
many people all the candidates are buying TV. ... In Wyoming, it's
more personal. People want a phone call.''
   State GOP chairman Mark Hughes said he expected the Republican
race to come down to Sen. Bob Dole and Vice President George Bush,
who have spent more time and effort in Wyoming than Rep. Jack Kemp
and Pat Robertson.
   ``My opinion is that Bush and Dole are far more organized and
have been in the state a much longer period of time,'' said Hughes.
   ``I don't believe Jack Kemp has campaigned extensively here and
don't think his campaign has been that strong here,'' he said,
adding that Robertson also has been weak in Wyoming.
   On the Democratic side, leaders are reluctant to make
predictions. .
   ``It's hard to tell how people are going to vote at this
point,'' Moore said late last week. ``I still think we have a very
large portion of our Democrats who haven't made up their minds
yet.''
   Twenty-eight years ago it was Wyoming's position in the alphabet
that brought it glory as the state's Democratic delegation cast the
deciding vote in Los Angeles that gave John F. Kennedy the party's
presidential nomination.
   Some state and party officials believe that with that in mind,
it might be in Wyoming's best interest to send an uncommitted
delegation to the convention.
   Gov. Mike Sullivan holds that belief, at least for the time
being. One of Wyoming's five ``super delegates'' to the Democratic
national convention, Sullivan does not have to commit himself to
any candidate prior to the convention.
   So far he has remained uncommitted, although he's been lobbied
by the candidates to cast his support prior to Super Tuesday.
   Not all Democratic leaders are taking that tack, however.
   Former Gov. Ed Herschler, the state's chief executive officer
for 12 years before Sullivan took over in 1987, will get an idea
this Saturday of how much political clout he carries. He endorsed
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee last month.
   Mike Beson, deputy campaign director for Rep. Richard Gephardt,
said endorsements aren't the only thing that count.
   ``We're not going to let that hinder our campaign,'' he said.
``We have a grassroots, aggressive campaign.''
   On the Democratic side, each of the 23 counties will hold party
conventions Saturday at which a secret ballot will determine the
allocation of 13 delegates. Once the results are known, nominees
for delegates to the state party convention on May 7 in Sheridan
will campaign on behalf of a certain candidate, or perhaps as an
uncommitted delegate.
   Later in the day, delegates to the state convention will be
selected, and at the convention the 13 delegates to the national
convention will be chosen.
   On the Republican side, things are not so simple.
   Precinct caucuses started earlier this month at which delegates
to the county conventions were selected. At the county conventions,
which start Tuesday and end the following Saturday, there will be
no formal presidential preference poll taken to base delegate
selection, said Mary Ann Collins, state GOP executive director.
   Twelve counties are considered delegate counties and will send
12 presidential delegates to the state GOP convention on May 7 in
Cheyenne. The nominees for these positions must declare which
candidate they are supporting, according to party bylaws.
   The remaining counties, plus one, will send alternate delegates
to the state convention. At the state convention the remaining six
delegates will be selected.
</TEXT>
