<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PhoneFraud     02-29 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Phone Fraud,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phone Credit Cards Easy Prey for Crooks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone credit cards make it easier to
charge calls but they're also making it easier for thieves to steal
the numbers and run up huge long-distance bills.
   The thieves are not necessarily the users. They often sell the
stolen numbers to others who use them to dial around the world.
   Toll fraud costs the long-distance companies about half a
billion dollars a year, about 1 percent of the industry's revenues,
according to the industry-sponsored Communications Fraud Control
Association.
   Despite phone companies' security efforts, thieves are coming up
with bold new deceptions aimed at the unsuspecting.
   Officials at the Mexico (Mo.) Ledger fell into such a trap with
a Southwestern Bell calling card, which the newspaper used to make
long-distance calls on American Telephone & Telegraph Co.'s
network, according to Editor Robert M. White II.
   Southwestern Bell, using a computer to monitor calling-card use
by its customers, detected unusually high use by the newspaper one
weekend in January. After consulting the newspaper, it canceled the
card and issued a new one.
   Publisher Max Thomson says that on the same day the new code was
issued, he got a call from a man who said he was from AT&T and
needed to verify the new credit card number assigned to the
newspaper because someone was trying to use it. Unsuspecting,
Thomson gave the caller the new number.
   Within days, the card again was being used to charge calls
around the world, and by the time Southwestern Bell's computer sent
up another red flag, the newspaper's card had run up charges of
more than $4,500.
   The calls included one for $155.46 from a New York pay phone to
Mali and another costing $105.27 from the same phone to the same
number in Mali 12 hours later; a $144.15 call that lasted two and a
half hours between a Jersey City, N.J., phone booth and China.
Others calls went to Kuwait, Bangladesh, Gambia, Senegal, Spain,
Taiwan and the Dominican Republic, among other places.
   As is the practice of most phone companies, Southwestern Bell
didn't charge the newspaper for the unauthorized calls.
   But the Ledger has ensured that it won't happen again: ``We no
longer have credit cards,'' Thomson said.
   Southwestern Bell officials aren't sure how the newspaper's card
number was stolen initially. Some codes are obtained by computer
hackers who dial into a long-distance company's electronic files
and find secret billing codes.
   Long-distance companies are improving their network software to
help detect unauthorized access quickly, and they are phasing out
their shorter codes and adopting 14-digit replacements, which are
harder for hackers to crack.
   But thieves don't need a computer to get a code. Some hang
around phone booths where callers are dialing from cards and
``they'll use binoculars, mirrors, anything they possibly can'' to
read the numbers off the cards or even memorize the numbers as the
caller is punching them into the phone, said Everick Bowens,
president of the fraud control association.
   With codes in hand, hustlers and hackers then look for customers.
   At banks of pay phones in transit areas, the hustlers offer
domestic and international calls at deeply discounted rates, aware
that with frequent use the life of a code can be just a few hours.
   Bolder hustlers are passing themselves off as legitimate
resellers of long-distance service or even as a representative of a
long-distance company.
   US Sprint Communications Co., which lost $80 million to toll
fraud last year and is one of the most active long-distance
companies in going after code theft, recently uncovered a
``multi-level marketing operation'' that sold codes to about 200
people and businesses _ including insurance companies, accountants,
lawyers and retailers, said security director Robert F. Fox.
   ``A man walks in wearing a three-piece suit and says he's a
reseller with a contract with a major long-distance company and
that he can cut your long-distance phone bill,'' Fox said,
recounting the scam.
   ``He looks at a company's phone bill. Say it's $10,000 a month.
He says, `I can cut it to $5,000 a month,''' Fox said. ``He says
he'll give you authorization codes, and for your protection the
codes will be changed every few days.''
   Some of the buyers are caught unaware, Fox said, but ``some
people don't ask a lot of questions because they don't want a lot
of answers.''
   Sprint has been going after many of these buyers in civil court
actions and collecting restitution, he said.
   Fox advises: ``It may sound legitimate, but if it sounds too
good to be true, it probably is.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
