<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MutualFundTaxes     02-29 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mutual Fund Taxes,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Says Mutual Fund Expenses Won't Count as Income</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has put out the
definitive word on a confusing new law affecting taxation of
investors in mutual funds.
   Investors will not have to report certain operating expenses of
their publicly offered mutual funds as 1987 income because the
funds will not pass along those expenses to shareholders, said IRS
spokesman Rod Young.
   ``People don't have to be concerned at all about those expenses
on the returns they are filing now,'' said Mike Delaney of the
Investment Company Institute, which represents most of the nation's
2,400 mutual funds.
   This means investors will have to do nothing on their 1987
returns to get a one-year reprieve from a new tax.
   However, unless Congress intervenes, about 20 million
shareholders will have to count such expenses as income on future
tax returns and then attempt to write them off as a miscellaneous
itemized deduction.
   The taxation of these expenses has been surrounded by confusion
because of the wording of a new provision affecting them that was
signed into law by President Reagan only last Dec. 22. That
provision delayed for one year implementation of a section of the
big tax overhaul enacted in 1986.
   Because of the December change, publicly offered mutual funds
will not allocate their 1987 operating expenses among shareholders.
Thus, shareholders will not have to mention such amounts on their
tax returns at all.
   But all that changes for 1988. Mutual funds will be required to
pass on operating expenses to shareholders. In turn, shareholders
will list that amount as income and hope they can deduct it as a
miscellaneous expense.
   That is, unless Congress intervenes again.
   Under the 1986 tax overhaul, the deduction for all kinds of
miscellaneous expenses is limited to those that exceed 2 percent of
adjusted gross income. A mutual-fund shareholder whose
miscellaneous expenses did not reach that threshold would have no
way of deducting the fund's expenses and, as a result, would be
taxed on income never received. The same would be true for a
taxpayer who did not itemize deductions.
   Reagan has asked Congress to grant shareholders permanent relief
from taxation on that ``phantom income'' at a cost of $400 million
a year.
   The lion's share of money invested in mutual funds is in those
that are regularly traded on securities markets. But there are
numerous non-public funds that are traded privately.
   The IRS notes those that are not publicly offered or owned by at
least 500 persons may have to allocate expenses among shareholders
for 1987. Any fund that is so affected should be advising
shareholders to report as income the expenses that are designated
in ``Box 2'' on Form 1099-DIV.
   ``If you are not sure that your fund qualifies as publicly
offered, you should contact your fund,'' advises Young of the IRS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nazi-Debate Bjt   02-29 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nazi-Debate, Bjt,0889</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate About the Nazi Past Stirs West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN FISCHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bitter, open debate marked by
charges that some prominent historians are trying to tone down the
horror of Nazi atrocities is capturing the attention of West
Germans.
   The controversy has been the topic of a best-selling book,
numerous newspaper articles and TV reports. It is known as the
``Historians' Dispute'' and has split prominent professors into
feuding camps.
   One group, represented chiefly by prominent Berlin historian
Ernst Nolte, is calling for a new perspective on the Third Reich
and German identity 43 years after World War II.
   Six million Jews were killed in Europe between 1933 and 1945 as
part of Adolf Hitler's ``Final Solution.''
   Nolte and his supporters tend to compare what happened under
Hitler to atrocities carried out by other governments, such as the
deaths of millions in the Soviet Union under Stalin.
   But their opponents, led by Frankfurt University philosophy
professor Juergen Habermas, say the conservative historians are
trying to lessen the magnitude of Nazi crimes through such
comparisons. Habermas, one of West Germany's best known
intellectuals, also says his opponents are paving the way for
nationalistic impulses.
   In December more than 300 historians, sociologists, and
philosophers met in Frankfurt to discuss the dispute's impact. No
resolutions were passed there, but lectures held at the meeting
will be published in a book scheduled for release in March.
   The debate, however, has moved far beyond academic circles.
   A book documenting the dispute made the best-seller list in the
news magazine Stern last year, and new arguments regularly make
headlines in leading newspapers. As recently as Jan. 20, regional
television in the state of Bavaria devoted a book-review show to
new history books associated with the dispute.
   Nolte told The Associated Press in a telephone interview
Wednesday that he stands by his arguments.
   ``Those who want to make the Nazis' mass murder stand alone by
forbidding every comparison with other events are guilty of having
an incredibly unhistorical attitude,'' Nolte said.
   Nolte sparked the historians' dispute with an essay called ``The
Past That Won't Go Away,'' published in the conservative
Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung newspaper in June 1986.
   He suggested that Stalin's infamous forced labor camps and the
Communists' murder of millions of peasants were in a sense a
forerunner of the Nazi death camp Auschwitz and Hitler's genocide
program.
   ``Wasn't the Bolsheviks' `class murder' the logical and actual
precursor of the National Socialists' `racial murder'?'' Nolte
asked in the essay.
   Nolte's opponents have frequently called his phrasing unclear
and open to many interpretations.
   His critics also say he tries to justify Hitler's motives for
attacking the Soviet Union in World War II by arguing that the
dictator was mainly responding to the Soviets' goal of spreading
communism.
   ``To Nolte, Hitler is a European citizen who was historically in
the right in that he unwillingly went to war for democracy,'' the
Bayerischen Rundfunk television show ``Lesezeichen'' said in
reviewing Nolte's new book.
   Nolte and his supporters, however, say their arguments raise
valid questions in historical interpretation.
   Other Nolte arguments include comparing Nazi atrocities with
those of Cambodia's Pol Pot regime in the 1970s.
   Nolte says that he does not adhere to any one political party,
but many historians call him a conservative.
   ``I would say Nolte is a conservative,'' historian Christian
Meier of the University of Munich told the AP. ``Conservatives in
this dispute are those who see the horrible events of World War II
and the Holocaust as an instance of fascism, which also took hold
in other European countries, and not as a failure of German society
and values.''
   Habermas, in a newspaper essay, charged several conservative
historians with reinterpreting history to justify and minimize the
Nazi regime's crimes. The article appeared in the Hamburg-based
weekly newspaper, Die Zeit, in July 1986.
   The Nazi crimes ``lose their singularity'' in Nolte's arguments,
Habermas wrote in the article.
   Many historians hold that the Nazis' genocide cannot validly be
compared with other atrocities.
   ``Never before had a state, with the authority of its
responsible leader, decided and announced it would completely kill
off a specific group of people'' and put the plan into aciton,
historian Eberhard Jaeckel of Stuttgart University wrote about the
Nazi genocide in a 1986 essay as a response to conservative
arguments.
   Some historians say that too much dwelling on the Nazi past
could cause West Germans today, particularly younger ones, to
resent what they may see as a steady stream of accusation.
   ``Many (West) Germans today are at least one generation removed
from the Nazi period,'' Meier said. ``But the (West) Germans are
constantly being reminded of past actions. If it goes too far, it
could even provoke a counter-reaction.''
   Some liberal historians attribute the airing of conservative
views to a new, conservative ``political climate'' in West Germany.
In 1982, Chancellor Helmut Kohl's conservative Christian Democrats
toppled the leftist Social Democrats.
   ``Ten years ago they (the conservative historians) wouldn't have
risked advancing such notions,'' historian Hans-Ulrich Wehler told
the AP. ``The conservative historians' arguments fit into today's
political climate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0144EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FDA-Aspirin     02-29 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FDA-Aspirin,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Asks For Meeting With Aspirin Makers on Heart Attack Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration says it is
concerned about possibly misleading advertisements that describe
regular aspirin use as a way to prevent heart attacks.
   The agency has summoned the nation's aspirin makers to a meeting
this week to discuss to what degree they can make that claim in
their ads, an FDA official said Sunday.
   The meeting is scheduled for Wednesday at the agency's
headquarters in Rockville, Md. It comes a month after The New
England Journal of Medicine published preliminary results of a
study showing that aspirin taken every other day could reduce the
risk of heart attacks in middle-aged men.
   ``We do have some concerns about this,'' said FDA spokesman
Donald McLearn. ``Even the study itself was accompanied by an
editorial saying, `Don't jump to conclusions, folks.'''
   Some aspirin makers have launched advertising campaigns
featuring young men who have suffered heart attacks.
   The study was conducted on physicians aged 40 to 65 years old.
   ``It was clear from the preliminary results that it could be
helpful for heart attacks for men between 40 and 65,'' McLearn
said. ``Our concern is people will read about the study and say,
`I'm a 20-year-old female, maybe I should take aspirin every day.'
That's not what the study was all about.''
   McLearn said that because the study's results are still
preliminary, doctors still may need to know more before prescribing
regular aspirin dosages to patients. One possible side effect is an
increased risk of strokes, he said.
   Also asked to participate in the meeting were associations
representing the prescription and over-the-counter drug industries.
Also likely to attend are officials of the Federal Trade
Commission, which oversees advertising of over-the-counter drugs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
