<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 2ndLd-Writethru a0889 02-29 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0889,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Share Prices Weaker, Dollar Stable</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with with closing levels. Pickup
4th graf pvs ``Dealers said...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined moderately in quiet trading
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today, ending 13 consecutive days of
gains in the market's key index, while the dollar remained steady
after opening lower against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which rose 119.69 points
during Saturday's half-day session, closed at 25,242.81, down 42.06
points or 0.2 percent.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at 128.08 yen,
down 0.27 yen from Friday's close of 128.35 yen. After declining at
one point in morning trading to 127.95 yen, its first trip below
the 128-yen level in about three weeks, the dollar ended the day at
128.12 yen, down 0.23 yen.
   Dealers said many stock market participants were staying on the
sidelines in anticipation of a slight correction in prices
following the recent gains.
   During the 13 previous trading days, the Nikkei index rose a
total of 1,622.60 points or 7 percent.
   ``The market is taking a respite, which many participants had
expected for some time,'' said an analyst at Nomura Securities,
Japan's largest brokerage, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A record 14 consecutive days of gains in the Nikkei average was
set in early 1961.
   Foreign exchange dealers said sentiment toward the dollar was
relatively weak, with the market still searching for the currency's
bottom level. But they said the dollar's decline was being tempered
by fears of possible market intervention by Japan's central bank
below the 128-yen level, profit-taking by speculators and light
activity by commercial dollar-sellers.
   Despite the fears of dollar-buying by the Bank of Japan, a
senior trader at a commercial bank, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the central bank was unlikely to intervene unless
the dollar began falling at a faster pace below the 127.5-yen level.
</TEXT>
