<1ST_LINE>r p PM-MaineCaucuses Bjt   02-29 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Maine Caucuses, Bjt,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Do the Expected in Maine; Jackson Surprises with
Strong Second</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Englanders Michael Dukakis and George
Bush claimed victories in the Maine caucuses, but Jesse Jackson's
unexpectedly strong second-place showing was the surprise of the
evening.
   ``Our message is winning,'' declared Jackson, who finished with
1 percent of the Democratic vote in Maine's caucuses four years ago
but gained 28 percent on Sunday.
   Anything but first place would have been a major setback for
Dukakis, the Massachusetts governor who was winning 42 percent of
the delegates to the state Democratic convention in Maine.
Twenty-one percent were uncommitted.
   The also-rans were Paul Simon with 4 percent, Richard Gephardt
with 3 percent, and Albert Gore and Gary Hart with 1 percent each.
   ```Today our message shone through again ... (and that) gives
our national campaign another push towards success on Super
Tuesday,'' Dukakis said Sunday from Cleveland.
   Bush too needed the ``overwhelming victory'' he claimed Sunday.
With no official tally, the Bush campaign cited its own reports
from 259 caucuses and said the vice president had the non-binding
support of 65 percent of the GOP state convention delegates chosen
over the weekend.
   That added up to a huge lead for Bush in the state where he has
a vacation home. Robertson garnered 147 delegates, or 14 percent;
Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole 88, or 8 percent; and Rep. Jack
Kemp 14, or 1 percent, the Bush campaign said, adding that 123
delegates, or 12 percent, were uncommitted.
   ``I am delighted with what appears to be an overwhelming victory
in the Maine caucuses, assuring my campaign of all 22 national
delegates,'' Bush said from Washington.
   If the Democratic results held up at the state convention,
Dukakis would win 10 of the state's 23 pledged delegates to the
Democratic national convention. Jackson is in line for 8 delegates
and the uncommitted group 5.
   The numbers were unquestionably on the side of Dukakis, but the
runner-up emerged with a victory no less sweet.
   ``Maine has sent a message to America that we can win, that
America wants bold leadership and a new director with sound
ideas,'' Jackson said from the campaign trail in Texas.
   ``If it hadn't been for the strong grassroots organization that
we had, we would have been in trouble,'' acknowledged David
Villarino, manager of Dukakis' Maine campaign. Villarino asserted
that Jackson's victories in two of Maine's largest cities, Portland
and Bangor, reflected defections from the recently scaled-back
campaign of Illinois Sen. Paul Simon.
   Whatever the reason for their success, the Jackson forces were
ecstatic.
   ``What we're doing in Maine is building an electoral victory,
from the grass roots to the top of the blades,'' said Scott Nova of
the Jackson national campaign staff.
   Bush aides had worried earlier in the week that Robertson's
``invisible army'' of supporters would flood the caucuses here as
they did in Michigan, Iowa and other states. But Robertson's
supporters did not total the numbers feared by Bush aides, and
deals with Dole supporters diluted Robertson's impact.
   With the state party planning no count of results, the various
campaigns agreed in general that Bush was running well ahead.
   Jeff Nelson, a spokesman for Robertson in the state, said of the
Bush supporters: ``I don't think there's any question that they are
going to be able to claim victory.''
   A top Dole organizer, state Sen. Pamela Cahill, also conceded.
   ``This is Bush country up in New England, up in Maine and New
Hampshire,'' she said.
   In assessing the results in Maine, Dukakis and Jackson both
dutifully invoked Super Tuesday, the mega-primary next week in
which 20 states and one territory will hold primaries or caucuses.
At stake in the March 8 contests are 1,307 delegates to the
national convention.
   ``We're right where we want to be, and we're heading into the
final turn,'' said Villarino.
   Jackson spokesman Mel King said, ``People across the country,
when they find he came in second in Maine, are going to dispel the
notion that a person who is black can't do well.''
   Bush supporters acknowledged that they needed a big margin over
Robertson before the contests in the South, where the former
television evangelist has a strong core of support.
   ``We couldn't afford to have the national story out of Maine be
that Robertson comes in a close second,'' said Gov. John R.
McKernan Jr., one of Bush's strongest backers in the state.
   Maine's conservative GOP wing and fundamentalist churches were
fertile recruiting grounds for Robertson, and his forces mounted an
energetic challenge. But outmaneuvered, if not outmuscled, by Bush
backers in caucus brokering, Robertson's followers were unable to
turn their raw numbers into a matching proportion of delegates.
   ``The party and the procedures'' favored Bush over Robertson,
said Jeff Nelson, state spokesman for the Robertson campaign.
</TEXT>
