<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brite-LeapBirthdays     02-29 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brite-Leap Birthdays,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How Many Candles?</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Kaschalk has had fewer birthdays than any
of his seven children.
   ``My youngest boy is 19, and I'm just going to celebrate my 14th
birthday,'' says the East Detroit milkman, who was born on Leap Day
in 1932.
   Like other folks born on Feb. 29, Kaschalk's actual birthday
rolls around only once every four years. It's a studder step in
time that compensates for the 365\ days it takes the Earth to orbit
the sun.
   The U.S. Census Bureau estimates about 9,600 babies were born in
the United States on Feb. 29, 1984, and a similar number of infants
should be born today.
   ``It's truly delightful,'' said Ypsilanti businessman Peter
Fletcher, who was born the same day as Kaschalk. ``The common
reaction is one of sympathy and lament because you don't have a
frequent natal commemoration.
   ``But that very streak of sympathy provokes people to make it
even more memorable. When I was in my callow youth, people would
try to compensate for it by having a veritable spate of shivarees
and celebrations for me.''
   Jason Weiner, who's celebrating birthday No. 3 though he turned
12 today, takes it all in stride.
   ``It's OK, I guess,'' said the sixth-grader at Maple Elementary
School in Walled Lake.
   ``This is his third birthday,'' said Jason's mom, Joyce Weiner.
``We used to celebrate it on the 28th (of February), but the last
few years he's said he wants to celebrate it on March 1.''
   The traditional observance of leap year began in 46 B.C. when
Julius Caesar adopted the Egyptian calendar and the Western world
began counting years with 365\ days each.
   The added day every fourth year keeps the Earth's calendar in
line with the sun's rotation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham-Hometown     02-29 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham-Hometown,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hometown Residents Stand By Arizona Governor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Uintah Basin and Uinta Mountains cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALTAMONT, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the rural valley where
Arizona Gov. Evan Mecham grew up find it hard to believe he has
done anything wrong, no matter that he has been indicted and
impeached.
   The dairy farmer's son who left the Uintah Basin when he joined
the Army Air Corps in 1943 was industrious and studious, kind of
quiet and a model citizen, neighbors and relatives recall.
   ``We can't believe he isn't a good man and see no reason for
impeachment. I've not found anybody who couldn't praise Evan and
his integrity,'' said Birdie Swasey, a retired teacher who has
known the Mecham family since the Great Depression.
   Beverly Fieldsted, who was one year behind Evan in school and
whose brother-in-law lives in the former Mecham residence down the
road in Mount Emmons, agrees.
   ``They were not a crooked family. Evan didn't steal money,'' she
said. ``He worked hard on the farm, he went to school, he minded
his own business, he wasn't a smart-alecky, showy kid.''
   While defending Mecham's integrity, Mrs. Swasey acknowledged
that the governor, whose impeachment trial was scheduled to begin
today, may have spoken carelessly at times.
   ``I suppose he's not a politician. He may have spoken quickly.
You have to learn the rules of society, be sophisticated ... you
can't be naive like a child and say everything that pops into your
head,'' she said.
   Mecham and his family occasionally return to this expansive
valley along the south slope of the Uinta Mountains to visit
relatives, who remain supportive.
   ``I hate to see them treat him so badly,'' said Edith Burton,
Mecham's aunt. ``I just stopped listening to the news because it
made me feel bad. I knew much of it wasn't true.''
   Mecham said recently that his home country was ``the greatest
place to grow up. I always apologize to my children that I raised
them in the city and not in a place like that.''
   Mecham's father, Adelbert, settled in Mountain Home in 1908 and
married Ina Hanberg there in 1916. Evan, the fifth of six children,
was born May 12, 1924.
   When Evan was 12, the family moved to Mount Emmons, where they
had a ``humble home,'' a dairy, ran a store and raised a few crops,
the governor said. ``We didn't have much, but we weren't poor. I've
never felt poor in my life.''
   Being a dairy farmer's son during the Depression and early war
years forged Evan's character, including those traits responsible
for his current problems, friends said.
   ``He's never been a quitter,'' said his cousin, Ona Rust.
``That's why he's hanging in there now to clear his name.''
   In 1942, 18-year-old Evan took over most farm duties when his
father became incapacitated by rheumatoid arthritis. Evan was
forced to cut back on schoolwork, but kept up his grades and earned
an agricultural scholarship to Utah State University.
   He had a reputation of someone who always worked hard to get
what he got, said former neighbor Harry Fieldsted, adding, ``I
don't know if he was any smarter, but he seemed to apply himself
more.''
   Mecham sang and danced at Mormon Church functions and was
elected student body president his junior year at Altamont High
School, though he was kidded about his shyness in the 1941 yearbook.
   Mecham's date at the Altamont junior prom, Florence Lambert,
became his wife, and they later had seven children. The couple
settled in Arizona after World War II, when Mecham studied business
at Arizona State University and became an auto dealer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
