<DOCNO> AP880229-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     02-29 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Stocks Close Lower In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index ended 13
consecutive days of gains today, edging down in moderate trading,
while the dollar stayed within a narrow range after opening lower
against the Japanese yen.
   Dealers said many participants stayed away from the stock
exchange in anticipation of a market correction following the
string of gains. After rising 119.69 points during Saturday's
half-day session, the 225-share Nikkei Stock Average closed at
25,242.81, down 42.06 points or 0.2 percent.
   ``Such a small decline has almost no meaning,'' said Kunihiro
Ono of Nomura Securities, Japan's largest brokerage. ``It was just
a reaction to 13 straight days of increases.''
   ``The market is taking a respite which many participants had
expected for some time,'' said another analyst who spoke on
condtion of anonymity.
   During the previous 13 trading days, the Nikkei index had risen
a total of 1,622.60 points or 7 percent. It just missed matching a
record 14 consecutive days of gains set in early 1961.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar opened at
128.08 yen, down 0.27 yen from Friday's close of 128.35 yen. It
edged down briefly to 127.95 yen, its first trip below the 128-yen
level in about three weeks, before ending the day at 128.12, down
0.23 yen. Spot volume was a light $4.1 billion.
   ``Sentiment toward the dollar is bearish, and the market is
still searching for its (the dollar's) down side,'' said a trader
who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said speculators had tried
to sell the U.S. currency lower, but had bought back some dollars
in the afternoon to cover dollar-short positions.
   Traders said the dollar's decline was being slowed by fears of
possible market intervention by the Bank of Japan below the 128-yen
level, profit-taking by speculators, and light activity by
commercial dollar-sellers.
   But a senior trader at a commercial bank, who also spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the Bank of Japan was unlikely to
intervene unless the dollar began falling at a faster pace below
the 127.5-yen level.
   Satoshi Sumita, Bank of Japan governor, said today the central
bank would continue to move ``flexibly'' in money markets.
   In a speech to businessmen, he cautioned against a further
decline in the dollar, which he said would have negative effects on
the U.S. economy, including possible inflation, stock market
instability and a slowdown in foreign money flowing to the United
States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0418EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DeathFumes     02-29 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death Fumes,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carbon Monoxide Kill Four Children, Baby Sitter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN COVE SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carbon monoxide fumes apparently
from a gas heater killed four children ranging from ages 6 to 12
and their teen-age baby sitter, police said.
   ``It's absolutely the worst multiple death case in one family
that we've had in Clay County,'' said Sheriff's Lt. Tim Martin.
   ``Ultimately, what has happened was, we feel, a faulty exhaust
on a gas furnace became clogged and the carbon monoxide fumes were
allowed to back up and disperse through the house,'' he said
Saturday.
   Ola Weerts and a friend had left the children with a baby sitter
and went to dinner. When they returned about midnight Friday, the
baby sitter and three of the children were dead, Martin said.
   The only survivor was Tanya Weerts, 12, who was taken
unconscious to Shands Hospital in nearby Gainesville. She died
Saturday evening.
   Pronounced dead at Mrs. Weerts' home here were two other
children, 10-year-old James and 6-year-old Sherri. Mrs. Weerts'
friend's granddaughter, Julie Meador, 10, and baby sitter Jennifer
Bias, 17, were also dead, Martin said.
   ``They were all in their beds, apparently sleeping except for
one 10-year-old on the kitchen floor,'' he said. Ms. Bias was found
on a living room sofa.
   Autopsies on the others showed they died of acute carbon
monoxide poisoning, according to the medical examiner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
