<2ND_LINE>PM-Highway Slaying,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Headed To Celebration Party Murdered While Driving On Busy
Highway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law school graduate out to celebrate
after taking the Florida Bar examination was shot to death as he
drove along Interstate 95, police said.
   Friends following Irv Ribler's sports car told police the single
shot was fired from a van whose occupants had just thrown a small
object at the car, but that was unconfirmed, Broward County
Sheriff's spokesman Jim Leljedal said Sunday.
   ``Right now, we're just hoping someone will come forward who saw
what happened. Somebody had to. There was a lot of traffic out
there,'' Leljedal said of the shooting at dusk Saturday in
unincorporated Broward County.
   After Ribler, 26, was shot just below his left shoulder, his car
sped across the median, three lanes of oncoming traffic and then
plowed into a gully. He was pronounced dead within the hour at
Broward Medical Center.
   No other cars hit his and no other injuries were reported.
   Zaida Ribler, who cleaned houses and worked as a tailor seven
days a week to put her only child through Florida State University
and the University of Miami Law School, said her son was going to a
party in nearby Delray Beach.
   ``He left me a note before he left Saturday,'' she said Sunday
from her home here, about 15 miles north of Miami. ``It says, `Mom,
see you in the morning. I love you. Irv.'
   ``He was a good son. He studied so hard. He worked in the yard.
He cleaned the house. He didn't drink,'' his mother said. ``Now my
life has ended. Everything is over.''
   Ribler graduated from law school last May and had since failed
the bar exam. Since then, he had studied constantly. After taking
the test in Tampa on Wednesday, he was elated _ certain he had
passed, friends said.
   ``His whole life was centered on passing the bar and working as
a public defender,'' said classmate Manny Fernandez, 24. ``He had
some offers. He was almost there.''
</TEXT>
