<HEAD>Six, including Jimmy Breslin, Given 1988 ASNE Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer-Prize winning columnist Jimmy Breslin
was cited for stories of ordinary New Yorkers trying to live decent
lives amid drugs and poverty as the American Society of Newspaper
Editors announced six recipients of its 1988 Distinguished Writing
Awards.
   The New York Daily News columnist was honored for outstanding
commentary, which also included columns he wrote on the Howard
Beach racial attack.
   Other recipients announced by the ASNE Sunday are:
   _ Breslin's colleague at the Daily News, columnist Bob Herbert.
He was cited for deadline writing based on his account of the
violence in the 1987 presidential elections in Haiti.
   _ Blaine Harden, Washington Post Africa correspondent, for
non-deadline writing. He was chosen for a ``vivid account of a
river journey through Zaire'' and other stories.
   _ James M. Klurfeld, associate editor of Newsday, for editorial
writing. Klurfeld won for writing about President Reagan and the
Iran-Contra affair.
   _ Carl Schoettler, Baltimore Evening Sun reporter, for obituary
writing. His entries included accounts of the lives of three
Baltimore residents: a news dealer, a former mayor and a newspaper
publisher.
   _ Tom Shales, chief television critic and TV editor of The
Washington Post, for obituary writing. The committee noted his
appreciations of Ray Bolger, David Susskind, Danny Kaye and Rita
Hayworth.
   Winners of the national awards receive a $1,000 cash prize from
the ASNE Foundation at its annual convention in Washington April 15.
   Runners-up in the 1988 competition are Henry Allen, The
Washington Post; Graham S. Dower, Cleveland Plain Dealer; David
Finkel, St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times; Michael Pakenham, New York
Daily News; and Elizabeth Rau, Providence (R.I) Journal-Bulletin.
   The work of the national winners will be published in a book,
``Best Newspaper Writing 1988,'' produced by the Poynter Institute
for Media Studies in St. Petersburg, Fla.
