<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-LeapYear     02-29 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Leap Year,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Today Is A Four-Year Special</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Take note of today, Monday _ there won't be
another like it until 1992.
   It's leap year, when a day which seems to come from nowhere is
added to February and the year is 366 days long instead of 365.
   The astronomers of Julius Caesar in 46 B.C. decided it.
   They said that as the solar year was 365 days and 6 hours, the
hours made an extra day every four years.
   Why leap?
   The Oxford English Dictionary says _ and you may have to read
this twice _ that the year probably got its name because any fixed
festival after February in such a year ``falls on the next weekday
but one to that on which it fell in the preceding year, not on the
next weekday as usual.''
   A leaping over day, you see.
   According to popular tradition in Britain, a woman on this day
has the right to ask a man to marry her, instead of the other way
round.
   English folklore has it that any woman having her Feb. 29
proposal rebuffed can claim a silk dress from the man.
   In 1288 a law was enacted in Scotland to give women the right to
propose on Feb. 29. It said any maiden lady ``shall hae liberte to
bespeke ye man she likes.''
   If the man refused, he had to pay the lady a pound _ a lot of
money in those days _ unless he could claim he was already
betrothed.
   A few years later, France passed a simliar law and it was also
legalized in the 15th century in the Italian cities of Genoa and
Florence.
   A British romantic fiction publisher named Silhouette, seeking
to find out modern manners of proposing, asked the Gallup Poll to
include a leap year question in its survey.
   The poll found that women who propose to the man of their dreams
on Feb. 29 have a 92 percent chance of success.
   But only 12 percent of the women questioned for the survey _ it
didn't say how many _ responded that they would seriously consider
popping the question on this day.
   Jane Ellison, a columnist on a London daily, The Independent,
asked today: ``How many men are worth waiting four years to propose
to these days?''
   Ms. Ellison suggested using leap year ``sensibly'' by relocating
those ``annual events you dread'' to Feb. 29.
   Among her choices: the University Boat Race, the next Andrew
Lloyd Webber musical and Christmas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0504EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GacyLetters     02-29 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gacy Letters,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Prints Portions Of Letters Sent From Gacy To Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To the state, John Gacy is a sex murderer many
times over who deserves to die. To Sue Terry, he's ``a real nice
person'' she'd like to marry.
   Ms. Terry came to this feeling by exchanging letters during the
last 16 months and through repeated visits to Gacy at Menard
Correctional Center, where he's on death row for murdering 33 young
men and boys.
   Most of the victims were buried in the crawl space under his
home northwest of Chicago.
   Excerpts of some of Gacy's 41 letters to the 43-year-old
Centralia woman from Oct. 5, 1986, to Feb. 16 were published Sunday
and today in the Chicago Sun-Times.
   She said Gacy, 45, expects to be paroled and she believes he's
innocent of the sex killings.
   Gacy is under 12 separate death sentences and 21 terms of
natural life in prison with no hope of parole.
   ``We're real close,'' she said. ``I like John, and he trusts me.
I guess I love him. Yes.''
   Ms. Terry, a divorced mother of eight children who is also
helping to raise two grandchildren, said Gacy has asked her to
marry him. She said she would.
   ``I was gullible and trusted others. That's how I got where I am
today,'' Gacy wrote in one letter published today. ``I could lay
back and say it's not my fault I am here, because I know I never
killed anyone. The facts will back me up. But I am guilty of being
gullible and trusting others, so I belong here for letting myself
down.''
   Gacy also wrote of how he cried watching the Olympics and the
devotion of the athletes; he scolded Ms. Terry for not selling any
of his oil paintings; and he told of how he was going to run a
strict household for Ms. Terry's children when he gets out of
prison and they all live together.
   However, attorney Terry Sullivan, who prosecuted Gacy, said he
``is more likely to be executed than paroled.''
   Ms. Terry said she first met Gacy at Menard in August 1986,
seven months after she first wrote him a brief note.
   ``I decided to go back because, well, he's real nice. ... He's a
real nice person and he seems to be really concerned about me and
my kids.''
</TEXT>
