<2ND_LINE>PM-Black Catholics,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Says Catholic Church Has Been Racist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Bernard F. Law says the Roman Catholic
church has been guilty of racism and has put `horrendous
obstacles'' in the way of black Catholics.
   At a special Mass Sunday where more than 1,000 black Catholics
celebrated the past and future of blacks in the Boston Archdiocese,
the Boston archbishop said the ``faith of black Catholics has been
tremendously tested by the church, which put such horrendous
obstacles in their way. But the faith endured even under the most
extraordinarily difficult circumstances.''
   Following the Mass, which also marked Black History Month, Law
said, ``Racism is not conquered, not here or anywhere else. But
what we're seeing is a very positive sign.
   ``Racism is a sin. It offends God. The church is made up of
sinners, not saints, and one of the church's sins has been racism.
For that we are repentant.''
   There are an estimated 25,000 blacks among the 1.9 million
Catholics in the Boston Archdiocese.
   The Mass at the Cathedral of the Holy Cross featured the singing
of hymns by soloists Meyer Chambers, Philiss Baker and Denise
Graves.
   ``We're so accustomed to holding back in the Catholic church,
but today was a chance to live our own heritage, to open up,''
Chambers said. ``It's been a long time coming.''
</TEXT>
