<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthwestAirlines 1stLd-Writethru a0486 02-29 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Airlines, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0486,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Attendants Remain ``In Strike Position''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS 1st graf to CORRECT that strike deadline rather than
contract expiration occurred late Friday, ADDS two grafs of
background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines' 6,700 flight
attendants continued to keep the carrier guessing today on whether
they will strike, three days after a union deadline for reaching a
new contract.
   Both sides in the labor talks said just one issue divided them.
But William Genoese, international director of the Teamsters
union's airline division, said late Sunday that no further
negotiations were scheduled.
   ``At this moment we're in strike position. It can happen two
minutes from now or any other time. Under the law, we have that
right,'' Genoese said.
   He said absenteeism had increased among flight attendants.
   ``They are calling in sick. It's on the increase,'' Genoese
said. But he declined to categorize the absences as a negotiating
tactic, saying, ``I'm not going to say that.''
   Representatives of the airline and the union met with a federal
mediator for four hours Sunday and agreed on all but one contract
issue, said Northwest spokesman William Wren. Wren and Genoese said
the issue is Northwest's proposal to increase from five to nine
years the period that newly hired workers stay on a lower pay scale.
   Genoese said he sent a telegram to Steven G. Rothmeier, chairman
and chief executive officer of NWA Inc., the parent company of
Northwest, requesting a meeting. Wren said late Sunday he did not
know if Rothmeier knew of the request.
   Northwest officials said Sunday the airline continued to operate
a normal flight schedule. No delays were reported at airports
served by the carrier.
   If flight attendants do strike, the airline said it will keep
flying, using about 2,000 managers trained as flight attendants
were and 200 newly hired replacements.
   Genoese said he planned to meet today with representatives of
the pilots and machinists on whether they would honor flight
attendant picket lines.
   A strike deadline late Friday was extended as the two sides
continued negotiations that began Wednesday. Genoese said Saturday
night that a request by the federal mediator to delay a strike
helped avert a walkout earlier in the day.
   Former Republic Airlines flight attendants have been working
under their old contract since Northwest acquired Republic in 1986,
and many of them are paid less than their Northwest counterparts.
   The company, the nation's fifth-largest airline, is trying to
bring the workers under one contract and offered to bring former
Republic employees up to the salary levels of Northwest employees.
But the union claimed the airline wanted too much in exchange,
including cuts in vacation pay and retirement benefits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0535EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0880 02-29 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0880,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lee Blessing's `A Walk in the Woods' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with other reviews; No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a sun-dappled forest on the outskirts of
Geneva, a Soviet negotiator and his American counterpart meet to
discuss, among other things, the nuclear arms race and the fate of
the world.
   They are a diplomatic odd couple. The Russian, Andrey Botvinnik,
is gregarious, impulsive and almost childlike in his enthusiasm for
the frivolous. The American, John Honeyman, is officious,
humorless, a bit priggish and irritatingly sincere about his new
job as the U.S. representative to the arms control talks.
   Their one-on-one marathon conversations make up Lee Blessing's
``A Walk in the Woods,'' a wise and witty evening of theater that
arrived Sunday at Broadway's Booth Theater.
   The Russian wants to discuss country music, Italian suits and
making love to red-haired women. He wants a pal, not protocol.
``Formality is simply anger with its hair combed,'' he coos.
   The earnest American wants to steer the talk back to the
negotiations. He wants results. ``Friendship,'' he says, ``takes
you away from commitment to solving problems.''
   The two-character play was inspired by a true incident in 1982
involving American arms adviser Paul Nitze and a Soviet negotiator.
Blessing takes their real-life rustic ramble and embellishes on it,
transforming their meeting into a theatrical situation laced with
humor, grace and intelligence.
   Some two-person plays are like tennis matches. They are made up
of relentless back-and-forth banter that exhausts the audience
without leading anywhere. ``A Walk in the Woods'' has its share of
volleys and it dallies a bit, particularly in the second act.
Still, it manages to make its point about the need to keep trying
for peace, with a minimum of preaching.
   In part, the play succeeds because Blessing refrains from
overloading the evening with technical jargon and anti-war sermons.
There may be references to MX missiles, megadeaths, Star Wars,
bargaining chips, lasers and Afghanistan, but the emphasis is on
the men, not specific ways of averting nuclear destruction.
   By the time the two diplomats have walked through these woods
during four different seasons, they have grown to understand and
even like each other. That knowledge comes at the same time they
realize their two countries, while proclaiming interest in peace,
have little desire to slow down the arms race.
   If that makes the play sound unusually somber, it isn't. ``A
Walk in the Woods'' has its share of belly laughs, most of them
supplied by Robert Prosky, best known as Sgt. Jablonski on
television's ``Hill Street Blues.'' He's a big, beefy actor who
inhabits the very soul of the Soviet diplomat and who even
negotiates a convincing Russian accent. But the character's
joviality masks a cynicism fed by too many years at the bargaining
table. ``If mankind hated war, there would be millions of us and
only two soldiers,'' he says.
   Sam Waterston, as the somber American, plays straight man to
Prosky, except for one wonderful comic monologue in the second act
when he explains what happened after he threw a gum wrapper on
Switzerland's spotless soil. But for much of the time, this
reliable actor is left to deliver conventional, present-day
attitudes on the horrors of the arms race. It's to Waterston's
credit that he makes them seem part of his character's idealistic
beliefs rather than soapbox oratory.
   The play has been directed by Des McAnuff in an understated
manner with movement kept to a minimum. For a good deal of the
evening, the two actors just sit on a park bench set squarely in
the center of a woodsy glade designed by Bill Clarke and washed in
a delicate light by Richard Riddell.
   Rich-looking earth nearly spills into the first few rows of the
theater and a forest of trees soars to the top of the proscenium
arch. It's an inviting, tranquil setting, the perfect place to
ruminate on what would be lost if the two superpowers didn't
continue their walks in the woods.
   In other reviews:
   The New York Times' Frank Rich offered guarded praise for the
actors' work and called the set _ with the trees changing with the
seasons _ ``pretentious.'' Rich said the play ``fudges the
distinctions of actual international politics and arms negotiation,
choosing instead to telescope the messy, life-or-death conflict
into a sentimental relationship between two likable envoys.''
   In the Daily News, Howard Kissel roundly praised Waterston and
Prosky. ``It is Waterston's most moving work in years,'' he wrote.
``It is hard to imagine a more perfect actor to play the wily
Soviet.''
   Said Kissel, ``A few times the play seems coy or tendentious,
but the two are so powerful we never forget it's about frail men
fighting quixotically against their awareness of futility.''
</TEXT>
