<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     02-29 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Curly's skin-pated look-alike mingled with
the crowd while Three Stooges devotees watched old films and ducked
flying pies.
   From as far as California, at least 1,000 fans of the celebrated
knuckleheads came to Maine for a weekend of _ nyuk, nyuk _
Stoogemania, Ron Eugley, one of the convention's organizers, said
Sunday.
   A Stooge trivia contest was in progress when the pie fight _ a
highlight of the event _ broke out.
   ``I was emcee and I didn't even get a chance to close my eyes,''
said Joe Jerrier, 37, a firefighter from Gardiner, Maine. ``I got
four of 'em.''
   ``I've loved Larry, Moe and Curly ever since I was 5 years
old,'' said Virginia Riviera, 30, who came with two friends from
Salem, Mass.
   They and others swapped memorabilia and watched such films as
``Three Little Pigskins,'' ``All the World's a Stooge,'' ``Dizzy
Doctors'' and ``Disorder in the Court.''
   Curly impersonator David Knight, an iron worker from Palmyra,
N.Y., tweaked ears but generally restrained himself from
head-knocking, eye-poking and face-slapping. Those were some of the
slapstick hallmarks of the trio that made more than 190 short films
and about 50 feature-length films until the '60s.
   Morris ``Moe'' Horowitz, who later changed his last name to
Howard, died in 1975; his brother Samuel ``Shemp,'' and Larry
Fineberg died earlier, as did Jerome ``Curly,'' another Horowitz
brother who replaced Shemp as a result of a pay dispute.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Why is there a three-story, $8,000 stained
glass window 10 yards from the odor control tank at a sewage
pumping station near Fisherman's Wharf?
   The window is part of the $200,000 worth of art commissioned to
decorate the city's sewage treatment plants.
   Under a 1969 ordinance, San Francisco requires contractors to
set aside up to 2 percent of every public works construction dollar
for art that is selected by the Arts Commission.
   ``Just as we need air and water, we need art and culture in our
lives. It doesn't cost any extra ... (and) it makes a facility more
enjoyable and respected,'' Jill Manton, curator of San Francisco's
public art program, said recently.
   Concrete totems, a colored geometric roof gravel design and
mosaic tile walls are other completed sewer art projects.
   The Sunnydale Pump Station near Candlestick Park is in line for
a special design to help hide the station's rooftop air ducts while
featuring a habitat for an endangered butterfly species.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
