<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-29 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Both Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in light European trading
early today. Gold prices also fell.
   Market sentiment for the dollar turned bearish last week when it
became clear that the currency could not hold the 1.70-level
against the West German mark, said a trader in Frankfurt.
   But overall the market lacked direction, and the dollar was
fluctuating within a narrow range, traders said.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe compared with rates late
Friday:
   _ 1.6869 West German marks, down from 1.6895
   _ 1.3888 Swiss francs, down from 1.3897
   _ 5.7095 French francs, down from 5.7175
   _ 1.8941 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8965
   _ 1,243.20 Italian lire, down from 1,245.45
   _ 1.2639 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2838
   The British pound edged up to $1.7740 from $1.7715.
   The dollar closed in Tokyo at 128.12 Japanese yen, down from
128.35 yen on Friday. In later London trading today, the dollar was
quoted at 128.28 yen.
   London's major bullion houses fixed a recommended gold price at
midmorning of $423.75 a troy ounce, down from an opening bid of
$428 and Friday's closing rate of $431.50. A trader said gold came
under heavy selling pressure, but he was unsure why.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $424.20, down from $431.50.
   Earlier, the metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $430.19, down
from $430.34 on Saturday.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $6.10 a troy
ounce, down from $6.20 late Friday.
</TEXT>
