<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     02-29 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Soldiers Killed, Amnesty For Rebels Set To Expire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 20 government soldiers were
killed in clashes with communist rebels, and an aide to President
Corazon Aquino said she will not extend an amnesty for communist
and Moslem rebels.
   Mrs. Aquino first made the controversial amnesty offer in
February 1987 following the breakdown of peace talks with the
communist-dominated National Democratic Front. She extended it for
another six months the following August.
   An official at the presidential palace, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the program administered by the National Economic
Development Authority would expire on schedule tonight at midnight.
   ``Rebels who will come down from the hills starting tomorrow
will be charged in court for crimes they committed,'' he said.
   The official added that rebels who had already surrendered will
continue to receive government assistance.
   The military had been unenthusiastic about the program because
senior officers complained it enabled rebels to avoid prosecution
for killing soldiers. Military dissidents arrested after previous
coup attempts also complained that they should be granted the same
amnesty as the rebels.
   Officials at the National Economic Development Authority claim
nearly 60,000 people, mostly communist rebels or their supporters,
surrendered under the amnesty program. But the authority admitted
that only 6,252 were regulars of the 23,000-strong communist New
People's Army.
   Critics of the program believe those figures are inflated.
Journalists who attended several mass surrender ceremonies found
that many of those claiming to be rebels or their supporters were
simply impoverished peasants seeking government handouts or trying
to avoid military attacks on their villages.
   As the deadline approached, it appeared the communists were
gearing up for a new round of fighting. At least 20 soldiers were
killed in scattered battles with the rebels over the weekend.
   The rebels on Sunday stormed a Philippine Constabulary
headquarters on Negros island, killing six government troopers and
looting the garrison of its weapons, the military said today.
   On Saturday, 12 elite Scout Rangers died when their truck ran
over a land mine between Guinobatan and Jovellar towns in Albay
province, 200 miles southeast of Manila.
   Troops killed four ebels in the ensuing gun battle, the military
said.
   Elsewhere, rebels killed two Philippine Constabulary sergeants
in Leyte province Saturday and soldiers killed two rebels in Bohol
province, according to military reports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
