<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0809EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PalimonyPrizes     02-29 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palimony Prizes,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lotto Winner Must Share Prize With Former Housemate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed a Michigan Lotto jackpot
must share the $1.8 million prize with his former live-in
girlfriend, an county judge has ruled.
   Carolyn Eeles of Westland filed the suit, claiming she and her
former boyfriend, James W. Renfro, had an oral agreement to share
any winnings from Lotto tickets they bought for a December 1985
drawing.
   Ingham County Circuit Judge Peter Houk upheld the claim Friday.
   Eeles's lawyer, Karl Nickolai of Highland, argued that Eeles
paid $5 to buy 10 lottery tickets Dec. 18, 1985. One of those
tickets turned out to be a jackpot winner, which Nickolai said
Renfro redeemed two days before returning to his estranged wife and
moving to Tennessee.
   Renfro testified that he bought the Lotto tickets himself, but
17 other witnesses contradicted Renfro's testimony, including some
who vouched for Eeles' claim that she and Renfro each paid $5 for
the 10 tickets and that Eeles herself picked the winning numbers.
   Renfro has collected first two installments, worth about $74,000
each after taxes, and Houk ordered him to pay Eeles half of that
sum.
   Houk also ordered that Eeles receive half of the remaining 18
payments and interest on the first two installments and that Renfro
pay her lawyer's fees.
   ``I'm thrilled, there is justice in this land,'' Eeles, 43, said
afterward. Renfro, 48, said the witnesses ``weren't telling the
truth.''
</TEXT>
