<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Marcos     02-29 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Marcos,0431</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino's Relatives Went To Hawaii To Meet With Marcos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said today
she sent two relatives to meet Ferdinand Marcos in Hawaii, and her
ousted predecessor said he wanted to negotiate his return.
   Mrs. Aquino said she was not ready to let Marcos come back, but
a senator hinted Marcos may be allowed to come home if he swears
allegiance to the government and meets other terms.
   Presidential spokesman Teodoro Benigno told reporters Mrs.
Aquino recently sent her uncle, Rep. Francisco Sumulong, and
cousin, Rep. Egmidio Tanjuatco, to meet with Marcos at his home in
Honolulu.
   Marcos fled the Philippines in February 1986 after a
military-civilian uprising that followed fraud-tainted presidential
elections in which both he and Mrs. Aquino claimed victory.
   ``Go there and listen. If we can listen to other people, why
can't we listen to Mr. Marcos, who said that he had an important
message to send,'' Benigno quoted Mrs. Aquino as telling her
relatives.
   Tanjuatco told The Associated Press, ``I saw Mr. Marcos in
Honolulu starting at 2 p.m. on Jan. 26. We met only once. The
meeting was between him and myself only. During the meeting, Mr.
Marcos reiterated to me his desire to return to the Philippines at
the earliest opportunity.''
   In Honolulu, where Marcos lives in exile, Marcos issued a
statement saying:
   ``We are ready to appoint our representatives to negotiate the
details and conditions under which my family and I shall return to
the Philippines for the salvation of the country from the bloody
takeover by communist insurgents.''
   The statement commended the Aquino government for inviting ``all
political factions to organize one united political structure'' and
congratulated the Aquino government for existing as long as it has.
   The Aquino government had no immediate response to the statement
from Marcos.
   Mrs. Aquino has banned Marcos and his immediate family from
returning to the Philippines. Asked by reporters today whether she
would let Marcos return, Mrs. Aquino replied ``not yet.'' She
refused to elaborate.
   But Sen. Neptali Gonzales, a former justice minister in the
Aquino government, told reporters Marcos might be allowed to return
if he swears allegiance to the administration and settles claims
that he stole billions of dollars from the treasury during his
20-year rule.
   In another development, officials said they found the name
``Imelda Marcos'' on the passenger list of a flight that arrived in
Manila Saturday from Australia.
   A Marcos family spokesman said Mrs. Marcos was still in Hawaii.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
