<DOCNO> AP880229-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 0823EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlaneFlap     02-29 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plane Flap,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbors Up In Air Over Plane Restoration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Look, down on the ground! It's a bird!
It's a plane! It's an eyesore!
   It's a Stinson Reliant spotter plane, strange visitor from
another era, that now looms behind William Surgi's home.
   ``If we had really wanted to look at airplanes, we would've
moved next door to an airport,'' said Barbara Reeks. ``See how
you'd like it, day after day, out there where you have no choice
but to look at it.''
   Said her next-door neighbor, Anne Sullivan, ``What's he think
he's going to do, fly that thing out of here?''
   The single engine is missing from the plane, built in 1943 for
the Royal Canadian Air Force. The original fabric covering its
wings has been reduced to ragged strips of cloth fluttering from
the rusty steel frame.
   Surgi, 64, a retired Navy mechanic and World War II veteran,
said he is restoring the aircraft as a hobby. Until it is
airworthy, he wants to work on it behind his home.
   City officials say there's no law against that, though some
neighbors are complaining that the industrial flavor of Surgi's
yard may drive down property values.
   Surgi, who concedes that his hobby is an eyesore at the moment,
has been cited by the city for running a junkyard and for storing
so much debris that it attracted rats.
   However, he said his project has the support of most of his
neighbors, and displayed a petition he said was signed in his
behalf by 98 neighbors.
   The city has set a March 21 public hearing on the issue. A
proposed amendment to the city code would prohibit the storage or
repair of an airplane in residential areas, unless it is inside a
building.
   If he makes the plane flight-worthy, he'll have to dismantle it
and take it to an airfield to fly it, Surgi said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
