<HEAD>About 1,500 Armenians Rally in Support of Soviet Comrades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,500 Armenians marched through
Hollywood to call for re-establishment of their nation and show
support of protests in Soviet Armenia.
   Chanting in Armenian and waving signs with slogans such as ``one
nation, one people, one country,'' the demonstrators ended their
mile-long march Sunday at Los Angeles City College, where they
listened to speeches and sang Armenian songs.
   Police Sgt. Tom Knopp said the crowd was orderly and no problems
reported.
   The rally was organized by the Armenian Apostolic Church to
express solidarity with Armenians it says have been persecuted in
the Soviet Union, said spokeswoman Sona Tenkerian.
   About 200,000 of the up to 500,000 Armenians in California live
in Los Angeles County, she said.
   The recent protests in the Soviet republic of Armenia have
involved the region of Nagorno-Karabakh, in the Caucasus Mountains.
The region is part of the neighboring republic of Azerbaidzhan, but
Armenians want it to be annexed to their republic. More than 80
percent of Nagorno-Karabakh's 157,000 residents are Armenian.
</TEXT>
