<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Senegal-Elections     02-29 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senegal-Elections,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Violence Erupts After Reported Landslide For Incumbent President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY JAMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Abdou Diouf declared a state of
emergency to quell violent demonstrations that began today
following radio reports that he was winning re-election by a
landslide.
   Witnesses said truncheon-swinging riot police battled students
in the northern section of the capital and rock-throwing protesters
destroyed several buses in the southern section.
   A broadcast on national radio said all public meetings were
banned and that the emergency declaration was being made ``in
response to grave troubles this morning.''
   The radio said Diouf, who polled 83.5 percent in the 1983
election, received 77 percent of the vote in early returns. It said
early returns showed the leading opposition candidate, Abdoulaye
Wade of the Senegalese Democratic Party, got 21 percent of the
vote. Two other candidates split the rest.
   Diouf had been expected to easily win re-election to a second
five-year term in Sunday's voting. But opposition candidates
charged Sunday that Diouf's Socialist Party was handing out
fraudulent voting cards to his supporters.
   Reporters saw riot police break up a meeting today of the
opposition Senegalese Democratic Party outside party headquarters.
A photographer for The Associated Press was arrested and his camera
and film confiscated.
   The opposition party earlier had threatened demonstrations if
the government announced election returns before they had been
certified by the country's Supreme Court, which hears challenges to
results.
   Armored personnel carriers mounted with machine guns blocked
major entrances near the opposition party headquarters and to the
University of Dakar, where dozens of people were arrested today
during clashes with police.
   Witnesses said police moved in to break up a group of students
who had gathered on campus, and that police broke into the
students' residences, knocking down doors and throwing tear gas
grenades into the rooms.
   A group of Moroccan students told reporters they had been taken
out of their beds by police, dragged outside on the lawn and beaten
with rubber truncheons.
   Those who had been singled out for beatings also had their heads
shaved by police, students said.
   Although the election campaign had been marred by battles
between police and opposition supporters, the only reported trouble
on election day was in the northern town of Kebemer. A Radio France
International reporter said police fired on a group of young
Senegalese Democratic Party supporters who were throwing rocks at
them.
   The Kebemer hospital said four people were treated and released
and two others were hospitalized after surgery. No other details
were available.
   Diouf was appointed to succeed President Leopold Senghor who
retired in 1981.
   His party was expected to maintain its majority in the National
Assembly, although it appeared likely it would lose some of the 111
seats won in the 1983 elections.
   Candidates from four parties were contesting the presidency
while six parties had candidates running for seats in the
legislature.
   The opposition parties have called for changes in the electoral
process.
   Wade has repeatedly claimed there was widespread fraud in the
1983 voting and threatened to turn his party into a national
liberation movement if Sunday's voting was rigged.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
