<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ConsumerRatings     02-29 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Consumer Ratings,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Federation of America Rates Members of Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Consumer Federation of America says its
annual ratings of the voting records of Senate and House members
show 48 ``heroes'' and 23 ``zeroes'' for consumers.
   The ratings released Sunday were based on a dozen votes in the
Senate and 14 in the House of Representatives. Members were given
credit for some obvious consumer issues, such as support for
appliance energy efficiency standards, and for some that were not
so obvious, such as a vote against Supreme Court nominee Robert
Bork.
   The heroes included nine senators and 39 House members, the
group said, and it gave the Senate its best rating ever.
   For the first time since the federation started rating Congress
in 1971, it said, the Senate supported consumer interests in more
than half of the votes counted.
   Overall, senators sided with consumers 59 percent of the time,
it said, up from 45 percent a year earlier. Members of both parties
were credited with significant improvement.
   In the House, consumer issues were supported 53 percent of the
time, up from 51 percent the year before.
   Senate votes listed as favoring consumer interests, in addition
to the appliance and Bork votes, included retaining the broadcast
fairness doctrine, giving communities notice of large plant
closings, supporting clean water funds, cutting tobacco export
subsidies and opposing raising the speed limit to 65 miles per hour.
   House votes favoring consumers also included clean water, the
fairness doctrine and low speed limits plus limits on credit card
interest rates, requiring banks to make deposited funds available
to customers, encouraging use of generic drugs, restricting smoking
on airplanes and funding legal services.
   Senate heroes voted correctly, according to the federation,
every time, while House heroes managed at least 13 out of 14 votes
correctly, the study said.
   Senate heroes are Brock Adams, D-Wash.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.;
Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio; Barbara Mikulski, D-Md.; George J.
Mitchell, D-Maine; Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.; Claiborne Pell,
D-R.I.; Paul S. Sarbanes, D-Md., and Robert T. Stafford, R-Vt.
   House heroes, all Democrats, are Ronald V. Dellums, California;
Brian J. Donnelly, Massachusetts; Dennis M. Hertel, Michigan; Dale
E. Kildee, Michigan; Joe Moakley, Massachusetts; Ted Weiss, New
York; Sidney R. Yates, Illinois; Anthony C. Beilenson, California;
Thomas J. Downey, New York;Richard J. Durkin, Illinois;
   Also Dennis E. Eckart, Ohio; Don Edwards, California; Lane
Evans, Illinois; James J. Florio, New Jersey; Sam Gejdenson,
Connecticut; Frank J. Guarini, New Jersey; Charles A. Hayes,
Illinois; George J. Hochbrueckner, New York; Steny H. Hoyer,
Maryland;
   Plus Gerald D. Kleczka, Wisconsin; John J. LaFalce, New York;
Mickey Leland, Texas; Sander M. Levin, Michigan; Edward J. Markey,
Massachusetts; Robert T. Matsui, California; Nicholas Mavroules,
Massachusetts; Matthew F. McHugh, New York; Kweisi Mfume, Maryland;
   And George Miller, California; Henry J. Nowak, New York; Donald
J. Pease, Ohio; Claude Pepper, Florida; Charles B. Rangel, New
York; Peter W. Rodino, New Jersey; James H. Scheuer, New York;
Stephen H. Solarz, New York; Pete Stark, California; Gerry E.
Studds, Massachusetts, and Henry A. Waxman, California.
   On the other side of the coin, zeroes were listed as those in
the House and Senate who voted as the federation thought correct
either once, or not at all.
   Senate zeroes, all Republicans, were James A. McClure, Idaho;
Steven D. Symms, Idaho; Malcolm Wallop, Wyoming; Phil Gramm, Texas;
Jesse Helms, North Carolina, and Don Nickles, Oklahoma.
   House zeroes, also all Republicans, were Connie M. Mack III,
Florida; Robert E. Badham, California; Dan Burton, Indiana; Daniel
Coats, Indiana; Howard Coble, North Carolina; Larry Combest, Texas;
Tom D. DeLay, Texas; James M. Inhofe, Oklahoma;
   Also Jack F. Kemp, New York; Jon Kyl, Arizona; Bill Lowery,
California; Edward R. Madigan, Illinois; Bob McEwen, Ohio; Michael
G. Oxley, Ohio; Bob Stump, Arizona; Robert S. Walker, Pennsylvania,
and David O'B. Martin, New York.
