<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru   02-29 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0513,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settler Freed Pending Probe Of Palestinian Deaths; Death Toll
Rises</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with settler free on bail, two
more Arab fatalities; picks up 4th graf pvs: The army ...; DELETES
last five grafs pvs to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers killed one Palestinian during
a protest in the occupied West Bank today, hospital officials said,
and the army said a second Arab died of wounds suffered in an
earlier clash with soldiers.
   Meanwhile, a Jewish settler suspected of killing two
Palestinians was freed on bail, and an Israeli officer trying to
teach his men restraint made them watch TV footage of soldiers
beating captured Arabs.
   Yasser Daoud Eid, 18, died after he was shot in the neck during
a clash with soldiers in Burin, about 3 miles south of the West
Bank city of Nablus, the Arab-owned Palestinian Press Service and
officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad Hospital said. The army said it was
checking the report.
   A second Palestinian, 30-year-old Mahmoud Batwi, died of wounds
suffered four days ago when he was shot in the head in a protest in
the West Bank town of Jenin, the army said.
   Police freed on bond Hananiya Schneider, a Jewish settler
detained on suspicion of involvement in the shooting death of two
Arabs in the West Bank. Police said an investigation into the
slayings would continue.
   Schneider, of Neve Tzuf, is suspected of killing two
Palestinians on Saturday night from the neighboring village of Abud
after villagers blocked the main road.
   The army today charged three soldiers, including a
sergeant-major, with aggravated assault and brutality for allegedly
burying alive four Palestinians in the West Bank village of Kfar
Salem, an army spokesman said.
   The incident occurred Feb. 5 after troops broke up a
stone-throwing demonstration in the village. The Arabs escaped with
the help of relatives.
   The soldiers' names were not released. It was the first known
case of a soldier facing serious criminal charges related to the
unrest in the occupied lands, although other soldiers have been
disciplined for using excessive force there.
   The army also confirmed it was investigating charges that a
soldier shot and killed a Palestinian demonstrator in cold blood
after seizing him during a demonstration. The spokesman said the
incident occurred in the Gaza Strip last month but gave no other
details.
   In another development, an Israeli senior commander on Sunday
made his officers watch CBS television footage showing four
soldiers beat two Palestinians for nearly 40 minutes last week.
   Excerpts of the footage showed the soldiers bent over the Arabs,
who were lying on the ground with their hands tied behind their
backs. The soldiers kicked the Arabs in the head and chest, then
picked up fist-sized rocks and smashed them on the Arabs' arms and
legs, trying to break bones.
   ``We have to make sure that we don't become an army of rabble,''
Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, commander of Israeli troops in the West
Bank, told army radio.
   The four soldiers accused in the beatings near Nablus were
released from custody today, army radio said. Their case went to
the military prosecutors' office, where it will be decided what
steps to take against them, it said.
   In Jerusalem, police today safely detonated a bomb planted at
the entrance to a large supermarket in Ramat Eshkol, one of the
city's northern Jewish neighborhoods, police spokesman Rafi Levi
said. Levy said the bomb was discovered by a passerby who alerted
police.
   The latest fatalities came as U.S. Secretary of State George
Shultz pursued his Middle East shuttle. Since unrest began in the
occupied territories on Dec. 8, 74 Arabs have died, according to
U.N. count.
   Shultz visited Cairo on Sunday, where his peace plan received
support from President Hosni Mubarak. Shultz then returned to
Israel for more meetings with Israeli officials Sunday night and
this morning before flying to Jordan.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres told reporters after meeting
Shultz today that he believed Jordan was taking the shuttle ``very
seriously'' even though King Hussein flew to London for dental
treatment before the mission began.
   During a debate of Israel's 24-member Cabinet on Sunday,
Transportation Minister Chaim Corfu and Labor and Social Affairs
Minister Moshe Katzav proposed barring reporters from the West Bank
and Gaza. No decision was made.
   ``I've reached a conclusion that media presence creates riots. .
.. so in order to subdue the riots or stop them completely it's
better that the media would not be present,'' Katzav told army
radio.
</TEXT>
