<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SweepstakesLoser     02-29 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweepstakes Loser,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sweepstakes Victory Celebration Proves Premature</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEARL, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who thought she won enough in a
million-dollar sweepstakes to pay off her debts is deeper in debt
now after taking a celebratory trip and finding out she didn't win
after all.
   But officials of United States Purchasing Exchange, the
contest's sponsor, say Debra Long probably is the victim of a
mixup, a misunderstanding or a bad joke. She won't be getting any
money.
   Long quit her $2.25-an-hour waitress job, took a trip to Las
Vegas with her boyfriend and made plans to buy a house and pay off
debts after thinking she won $1.7 million in a sweepstakes.
   ``They were convinced I was a winner. I got phone calls saying
that,'' Long said after learning last week that she wouldn't
receive the money.
   A spokeswoman for the California-based mail-order company
disputes Long's story on several points. Among other things, she
says, no winner has been named because the sweepstakes is still in
progress.
   Long ordered a $9.98 canister set from USPE in November and
entered its sweepstakes.
   In early February, she said, she received a letter from USPE
saying she would receive a ``multimillion-dollar cash letter.''
Another USPE letter arrived Feb. 13 by certified mail, and Long
said she took it to mean she had won.
   USPE officials said the second letter was a promotion advising
customers they're in the running for the prize.
   Long said she called the company Feb. 15 to confirm her windfall
and was asked to read the letter over the phone.
   A secretary said ``if I heard two beeps, it meant I wasn't a
winner,'' Long said. ``I was sitting on the edge of my chair,
waiting, but I didn't hear any beeps.
   ``And then she connected me with the manager. He said, `Miss
Long, I pronounce you the grand prize winner of the USPE
sweepstakes. You're $1,731,852.21 richer than you were 24 hours
ago.'''
   She said she was told the money would be deposited in her bank
account within 60 days.
   USPE officials got word of Long's claim last Thursday, and
Cheryl McGeary, the company's customer service supervisor, called
Long with the bad news.
   Besides not confirming information via telephone, McGeary said,
USPE doesn't notify winners by certified mail and doesn't ask for
bank account numbers.
   And while Long said she called USPE on Feb. 15 to verify her
claim, McGeary said company offices were closed that day for
Presidents' Day.
</TEXT>
