<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Bombs     02-29 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Bombs,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Hanged in Public for Bomb Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran hanged two men sentenced to death
for bombing a Tehran square, Iran's official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported today.
   The executions Sunday raised to seven the number of people
hanged in public in the Iranian capital during the weekend for
bombings. IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said five men were hanged
Saturday.
   A senior commander of Tehran's Revolutionary Committees, which
have largely taken over security from civilian police, announced
Saturday that 30 people responsible for recent bombings in Tehran
and western Iran had been arrested.
   He said the suspects, described as ``paid Iraqi agents,'' would
be handed over to the Revolutionary Courts for trial.
   IRNA did not specify whether the seven men executed were part of
the group of 30 reported arrested.
   IRNA identified the two men hanged Sunday as Mohammed Kazimzadeh
and Rasoul Rahmani. It said the Islamic Revolutionary Court
convicted them of planting bombs, spying for Iraq and transporting
explosives to Tehran from Iraq.
   They received ``a large amount of money'' from Iraq for the
bombings, the agency said.
   The two men were sentenced to death for bombings last year in a
Tehran square and were hanged ``at the scene of their crime,'' IRNA
said.
   The latest reported bombing in Tehran was Feb. 18, when a car
bomb exploded on a Tehran expressway, wounding two people.
   Another 10 people were wounded three days earlier by a blast in
north Tehran's Martyr Bahonar Avenue, only a few hundred yards from
the residence of Iranian revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980. Members of
Iranian resistance groups fighting against Khomeini's fundamentist
Islamic regime are invariably branded Iraqi agents by the Iranian
authorities.
</TEXT>
