<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Broce     02-29 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Broce,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justices Will Review Kansas Man's Sentence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to review a
decision halving the fines and prison terms given to a Dodge City,
Kan., business and its president for rigging highway-construction
bids.
   The justices said they will hear federal prosecutors' arguments
aimed at reinstating the original sentences received by Broce
Construction Co. Inc. and Ray C. Broce.
   Broce and the business pleaded guilty in 1982 to charges
contained in two indictments, respectively alleging bid-rigging in
highway-construction projects in Meade and Barton counties.
   Broce was sentenced on March 15, 1982, to concurrent two-year
prison terms and fined $101,000. The corporation he headed was
fined $1.5 million.
   More than a year after the sentencing, Broce and the corporation
sought to set aside the judgment and sentence from the second
indictment. They contended that the separate sentences meted out
under the second indictment amounted to multiple punishment for the
same crime.
   A federal trial judge threw out the appeal but the 10th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals reversed that ruling.
   The appeals court said that the Constitution's protection
against double jeopardy had been violated by the sentencing, and
that Broce and the corporation had not waived their double-jeopardy
protections when agreeing to plead guilty.
   The appeals court set aside the sentences issued under the
second indictment _ $750,000 in fines for the corporation and
$50,000 in fines and a two-year prison term for Broce.
   In seeking Supreme Court review, government lawyers noted that
the two defendants pleaded guilty to two indictments alleging two
different criminal conspiracies under a plea bargain in which the
government agreed not to prosecute on other charges.
   Under such circumstances, the government's appeal said,
defendants should not be able later to attack the sentences on
grounds that the two alleged conspiracies were actually a single
conspiracy.
   The case is U.S. vs. Broce, 87-1190.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
