<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-RacetrackSearches     02-29 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Racetrack Searches,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Officials Wanting to Conduct Warrantless Racetrack
Searches Lose Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois officials wanting to conduct
warrantless searches of racetrack employees' on-grounds living
quarters as one way of protecting the sport's integrity lost a
Supreme Court appeal today.
   The justices, without comment, let stand rulings that such
searches violate constitutionally protected privacy rights if
conducted without first obtaining a court warrant.
   The Illinois Racing Board for years had authorized state law
enforcement officers to search, without warrants, the rooms of
``backstretchers'' _ those employees who feed, groom, exercise and
generally take care of racehorses.
   The searches were aimed at discovering drugs or mechanical
devices that could affect a race's outcome.
   While employed by horse trainers, many backstretchers live in
small rooms located in the area where horses are stabled, the
backstretch.
   The board also authorized warrantless searches of the employees
themselves.
   At one time, backstretchers were required to consent to such
searches as a condition to receiving their licenses.
   Three backstretchers working at Arlington Park Racetrack
challenged the state board's policy and rules in 1982.
   Don Serpas, Raymond Johnson and Carl Waters sued the racing
board in behalf of all backstretchers working at Illinois tracks.
The three had been subjected to searches that turned up no evidence
of any crime.
   U.S. District Judge Charles P. Kocoras ordered that the
warrantless searches be halted temporarily in 1983, and then banned
them permanently in 1985.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the ban last July
17 after finding no explicit authority for the searches in Illinois
law.
   The appeals court said the backstretchers' living quarters,
though temporary and humble, must be treated as their homes.
   The Constitution's Fourth Amendment generally prohibits searches
of someone's home unless a court warrant is obtained. Courts
generally will not issue a search warrant unless authorities show a
likelihood that evidence of criminal conduct will be found as a
result.
   ``There is no reason to doubt that drugs and mechanical devices
pose major threats to the integrity of the horseracing industry,''
the appeals court said. But it added that the Illinois racetrack
searches ``without the safeguard of a warrant are unreasonable and
violate the Fourth Amendment.''
   In seeking Supreme Court review, Illinois Attorney General Neil
F. Hartigan relied on past rulings by the justices that have
allowed warrantless searches of heavily regulated industries.
   The case is Schmidt vs. Serpas, 87-644.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
