<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-AtomicTests     02-29 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Atomic Tests,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Won't Review Atomic Test Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to revive
lawsuits charging the government and federal contractors with
negligently causing deaths and disease among people exposed to
open-air atomic tests.
   The court, without comment, let stand a federal law that
effectively spared the government from having to defend itself
against claims seeking billions of dollars.
   The atmospheric nuclear tests that gave rise to the case took
place between the closing days of World War II and the adoption of
a treaty between the United States and the Soviet Union in 1963
banning open-air testing.
   Suits were filed on behalf of 29 people _ civilians and members
of the military _ including 26 who died from cancer or
cancer-related causes. The suits alleged that the health problems
were caused by radioactive fallout from the explosions.
   Charged with negligence were the University of California, which
operated the Los Alamos, N.M., project; Lawrence Livermore
laboratories, which helped develop the atomic bomb; Sandia Corp.,
which provided engineering for the weapons program; and Reynolds
Electric Engineering Co., which helped build and operate a test
site in Nevada.
   The suits accused the private contractors of failing to take
adequate safety precautions at the test sites, and also said the
government was responsible for failing to enforce its own safety
standards.
   If the suits were successful, the government ultimately would
pay the claims because it had insured the private contractors for
any losses.
   But in 1984 Congress passed a law supported by the Reagan
administration that says only the U.S. government may be sued for
negligence allegedly caused by a private contractor in the atomic
weapons testing program.
   The result was to bar the claims since the government is immune
from such suits unless it surrenders immunity under the existing
Federal Tort Claims Act.
   Those who sued the companies said the 1984 law
unconstitutionally deprived them of a remedy for the deaths and
disease caused by the atomic explosions.
   ``The petitioners had a remedy against the original defendants.
They have none against the United States,'' they said.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the law last June.
It rejected arguments that the law violates the Constitution's
required separation of powers by retroactively preventing the
courts from considering pending claims.
   The administration, in urging the Supreme Court not to disturb
the appeals court decision, said more than 3,000 people are seeking
damages totalling more than $4.9 billion in all cases stemming from
the weapons tests.
   The high court on Jan. 11 refused to hear a related appeal by
some 1,200 people in Nevada, Arizona and Utah who sought to hold
the government financially responsible for deaths and diseases
allegedly caused by the tests in Nevada.
   The case acted on today is Konizeski vs. Livermore Labs, 87-953.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Bingo     02-29 0370</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Bingo,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Asked About Taxing Indian Bingo Games in Oklahoma
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court asked the Reagan
administration today whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run
by Indian tribes are subject to state sales taxes.
   The court said it wants to hear from Justice Department lawyers
before it says whether it will review an attempt by Oklahoma
officials to tax revenue from a bingo game in Tulsa run by the
Muscogee Creek Nation.
   The Justice Department's brief may not be filed for months.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in September that
the state could not force the tribe to collect and remit the
state's 2.5 percent sales tax on the bingo operations.
   The appeals court said the state's interest in collecting the
tax is minimal in this case.
   ``Patrons do not travel onto Creek lands to play bingo in order
to avoid sales taxes,'' the appeals court said. ``Creek Nation
bingo does not undermine the state economy or tax base. The state
is not losing tax revenues it would otherwise obtain from sales
made outside of tribal boundaries.''
   The appeals court also based its ruling in part on a Supreme
Court decision last year that said state and local governments may
not regulate Indian-run gambling unless Congress gives them
permission.
   The Muscogee Creek bingo game is conducted in Tulsa on a
100-acre area known as the Mackey site along the Arkansas River.
   The 10th Circuit court said the land is Indian territory in the
same way any reservation belongs to native Americans.
   The appeals court also said the fact that the bingo game is
managed by a non-tribal entity _ Indian Country, USA Inc. _ hired
by the tribe does not alter the exempt status of the gambling
operation.
   Forcing the tribe to collect and remit the sales tax would place
a heavy burden on the Indians even if the tax did not affect
revenue for the Creeks, the appeals court added.
   It said the tribe would be subject to fines and liens on its
property if it were held responsible for collecting the tax and
then failed to do so.
   The case is Oklahoma Tax Commission vs. Muscogee Creek Nation,
87-1068.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
