<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Israel-TVBanPetition     02-29 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-TV Ban Petition,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jewish Leaders Present Petition To Ban Television Coverage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jewish leaders have presented a
5,180-signature petition to the Israeli consul general recommending
a ban on television coverage of Israeli-Arab conflicts in the
occupied territories.
   Israeli Consul General Rahamim Timor accepted the petition
Sunday at Temple Emeth near Delray Beach.
   ``Good friends can give us advice,'' Timor told the audience of
400. ``Any recommendations, suggestions and advice will be studied
and considered.''
   Rabbi Leon Fink and Cantor David Leon led the petition drive
that blamed television coverage for sparking more violence on the
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Graphic television footage of recent Palestinian demonstrations
against Israeli rule has been shown around the world. The footage
has shown stone-throwing by Palestinians and Israeli retaliation,
including tear gas attacks, gunfire and brutal beatings.
   Seventy-four Palestianians have died in the protests since Dec.
8, according to United Nations figures.
   ``We're not against the press, but there's a major difference
between the camera and the press,'' said Leon, adding that
television footage gives a distorted view of the entire conflict.
``You get a completely different picture from the print.''
   ``If you think that stoning and firebombing in the Middle East
is a new thing, you are wrong,'' he said. ``We are concerned, we
should not be excited.''
   Timor said that occasionally, excessive force is used, ``but
this is war.''
   ``We shall not commit suicide,'' he said. ``If the public
relations is not nice, then they are not nice, but we shall
survive.''
</TEXT>
