<2ND_LINE>PM-Balcony Fall,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tourist Injured in Fall From Hotel Balcony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tourist was in intensive care today
after falling from a third-floor hotel balcony in the first such
incident in the college spring-break season.
   David Irwin and several friends stepped out onto the balcony
after hearing a firecracker go off Sunday night. Irwin, 23, reached
for a railing but missed, his friends told police. He fell to the
pool deck.
   It was not known whether Irwin was a college student. Manager
Neal Hughes of the Hawaiian Inn in Daytona Beach Shores Irwin had
traveled alone from Ontario.
   About 500,000 students are expected to visit area beaches this
March and April for spring vacations. Thirty people have fallen
from Daytona Beach-area hotel and motel balconies in the past four
years, mostly during spring break. Six have died.
   Heavy drinking has usually been the reason for the accidents,
officials say.
   The Hawaiian does not allow students on hotel balconies after 11
p.m.
   ``We have had students here for three weeks'' so far this year,
said Hughes. ``They have been real good. They have been real
cooperative about keeping the curfew hours.''
