<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SouthCarolinaGOP 1stLd-Writethru a0429 02-29 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Carolina GOP, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0429,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Carolina: Bellwether For Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 15th graf bgng ``A recent'' with new poll results</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every Saturday morning at Gene's Cafe, over
coffee, grits and country ham biscuits, elders of this small
piedmont town discuss the weather, how to solve the nation's
problems and lately, who should be nominated for president.
   Unlike previous races, they've had plenty of firsthand looks at
the candidates. And their Republican primary votes on Saturday,
along with the rest of South Carolina, will carry unprecedented
weight.
   As George Bush pointed out last week during one of many days
spent in the state:
   ``This state is going to be on the leading edge of the most
significant political event in terms of selecting a president that
we've had in this country in modern times,'' he said, in only a
slight overstatement of the importance of the Super Tuesday
collection of 20 primaries and caucuses three days after South
Carolina votes.
   ``You're going to see the darndest invasion of people who want
to be president that you've ever seen.''
   The Republican candidates are blanketing the state ahead of
Saturday's balloting with an eye toward the state's 37 GOP
delegates, yes, but more importantly, with hopes of a boost going
into Super Tuesday.
   South Carolina's primary falls three days before 20 states,
mostly in the South, choose more than one-third of the delegates to
the national convention in New Orleans.
   ``By going ahead of that, South Carolina has a special place in
the sun. You're going to send a signal, you see, all across the
region. And that signal will reverberate across the country,'' Bush
said.
   Heavy stuff for the boys at Gene's.
   But Claude Crocker said no topic is too big for his crowd.
   ``We talk about international trade policy, the Panama Canal,
the deficit. ... We handle all those high-level things,'' the vice
president of Clinton Mills deadpanned.
   Crocker thinks Bush is the man to beat in his area and in the
state. But Charles ``Buddy'' Oakley said former television
evangelist Pat Robertson can't be counted out.
   ``I think Robertson appeals to a large group of religious-type
people in South Carolina,'' he said.
   Their observations mirror more objective measurements.
   A survey published Sunday by The State newspaper said Bush was
the choice of 48 percent of the voters likely to cast GOP ballots,
Dole 25 percent, Robertson 19 percent and Jack Kemp 3 percent. The
poll, conducted last Monday through Wednesday, surveyed 319 likely
GOP voters.
   But Lee Atwater, a South Carolina native and Bush's national
campaign manager, said Robertson's strength has to be at least
doubled because of the strong turnout of his supporters and the
difficulty in measuring them. Robertson has attracted new voters to
the rolls, and many conservative Democrats are expected to vote in
the GOP primary for him.
   University of South Carolina political professor Earl Black said
``there is an enormous potential for a heavy cross-over vote''
because South Carolina voters don't register by party and because,
this being the second primary ever, there is no historical gauge.
   Robertson has said for months that he is seeking a first-place
finish in South Carolina, where he has a large and fervent
following of fundamentalist Christians. One Robertson stronghold is
PTL's Heritage USA, where more than 1,500 people live.
   South Carolina is a do-or-die state for Kemp, who has yet to
finish better than third in any contest. The New York congressman
is portraying himself here as the conservative alternative, saying
Robertson has no chance of winning the nomination.
   ``South Carolina is George Bush's to lose,'' said Blease Graham,
an associate professor in governmental studies at the University of
South Carolina.
   One issue that could cost Bush votes, Graham said, is his
opposition to legislation that would restrict the growth of textile
imports, which the industry says is causing job losses.
   The industry is running advertisements across the state every
day urging people indirectly to vote for candidates who back the
legislation. Robertson and Dole announced last week that they
support the bill now in the Senate.
   Bush's main strategy in South Carolina has been to promote his
close ties with President Reagan, who remains popular here.
   Turnout in 1980 was 145,000, and party officials estimate that
between 175,000 and 200,000 people will vote Saturday.
</TEXT>
