<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Andrews     02-29 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Andrews,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced to Death in Utah Hi-Fi Killings Loses Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sentenced to death in Utah for his role
in the 1974 killings of three people forced to swallow drain
cleaner before they were shot lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The justices let stand William Andrews' conviction and death
sentence for the three murders committed during an Aril 22, 1974
robbery of an Ogden store.
   Police said Andrews and Pierre Dale Selby, both stationed at
Hill Air Force Base in Utah, robbed the Hi-Fi Shop. Killed were
Stanley Walker, the store's assistant manager; Michelle Ansley, a
cashier; and Carol Naisbitt, a relative of the store's owner.
   Andrews' lawyers said he was a ``non-triggerman'' participant in
the crime, and that Selby actually murdered the three.
   Selby, from Brooklyn, N.Y., was executed last Aug. 28.
   Andrews, a former resident of Jonesboro, La, contended that he
was denied a fair trial because blacks were excluded from the trial
jury. His appeal also challenged the validity of Utah's death
penalty law on several grounds.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals previously had rejected
those arguments.
   The case is Andrews vs. Shulsen, 87-5449.
</TEXT>
