<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-ReversePaternity     02-29 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Reverse Paternity,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Decide Paternity Issue in California Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether states may block a man from trying to prove he fathered the
child of a woman married to someone else.
   The court said it will study a challenge by a man identified in
court records only as Michael H., to a state evidentiary rule
creating a conclusive presumption of fatherhood to a wife's husband.
   Michael H. contends he is the father of a 6-year-old girl,
Victoria, born to a woman identified as Carol D. at a time when
Carol D. was married to Gerald D.
   Michael H. filed in a state court in Los Angeles a ``reverse
paternity'' lawsuit in 1982, seeking to have himself declared
Victoria's father.
   His lawsuit was thrown out because California law, as do laws in
many other states, creates a conclusive presumption of paternity in
favor of a woman's husband if a child is conceived and born during
their marriage.
   In upholding the dismissal of Michael H.'s lawsuit, a state
appeals court said the conclusive presumption is based ``upon a
determination by the Legislature as a matter of overriding social
policy that given a certain relationship between the husband and
wife, the husband is to be held responsible for the child and the
integrity of the family unit should not be impugned.''
   The California Supreme Court had refused to hear Michael H.'s
appeal last July 30.
   The nation's highest court two years ago rejected, without
comment, a similar appeal from a Massachusetts man seeking to prove
he fathered the child of another man's wife.
   In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for Michael H. said he
enjoyed ``an ongoing father-child relationship'' with Victoria and
that blood tests show a better than 98 percent chance that Victoria
is his biological daughter.
   The appeal said Victoria was born as a result of an affair
Michael H. and Carol D. had while she was married to Gerald D.
   The appeal also said that Carol D. and Victoria moved to the
Virgin Islands to live with Michael H. for several months in 1982
when she and her husband were estranged.
   Court records indicate that Carol and Gerald D. later resumed
living together.
   The case is Michael H. vs. Gerald D., 87-746.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
