<HEAD>Envoy Reiterates He Won't Vacate Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's ambassador to the United States said
today that efforts by the newly installed government in Panama to
replace him will not succeed.
   Following the ouster last Friday of President Eric Arturo
Delvalle, the successor government appointed the second ranking
official at Panama's U.N. Embassy, Leonardo Kam, to succeed
Ambassador Juan B. Sosa.
   The U.N. Embassy said that Kam was in Washington today but Sosa
said he had heard nothing from the envoy.
   Sosa said in a telephone interview that the ouster of Delvalle
by the National Assembly, dominated by forces loyal to military
strongman Manuel Noriega, was unconstitutional. Sosa said he
continues to regard Delvalle as Panama's president.
   ``I hope not to hear from Mr. Kam,'' Sosa said. ``It would be a
very embarrassing situation. He would be representing an
unconstitutional government. He would be wasting his time.''
   Asked about the status of other embassy diplomats, Sosa said,
``The Panamanian Embassy is loyal to its ambassador and the
ambassador is loyal to President Delvalle.''
   He said the representative of Panama's Defense Forces at the
embassy, Capt. Jose S. Motta, continues to serve at his post. He
added that Motta reports to the Defense Forces and not to the
ambassador.
