<HEAD>Three Arrested In Officer's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALT SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three men arrested on capital murder
warrants in the shooting death of an off-duty police officer had
previously pleaded guilty to an assault on another police officer
and was on parole, authorities said.
   Another of the men arrested was on parole after a robbery
conviction.
   ``This is rather indicative of how the criminal justice system
is working,'' Capt. John Holt said Sunday.
   The officer's death was the seventh in six shootings involving
police this year. In addition to three dead police officers, four
civilians have been killed by police this year.
   Vincent Edward Cooks, 23, was arrested Sunday in Houston, and
Tony Ray Harvey, 23, and Tracy Dewayne Stallworth, 27, were
arrested Saturday, Holt said at a news conference Sunday.
   Holt and Lt. Ron Waldrop told reporters that other details of
the arrests were not available because the investigation into the
death of officer Gary D. McCarthy was continuing.
   Cooks began serving a five-year sentence in December 1986 and
was paroled on Aug. 4, 1987. He initially was charged with
attempted capital murder of a police officer, but Houston police
Sgt. V.W. West said Cooks pleaded no contest in September 1985 to a
reduced charge of aggravated assault.
   Harvey was paroled Jan. 18 after serving 18 months of a six-year
sentence for aggravated robbery and unauthorized use of a motor
vehicle, Holt said.
   Harvey was being held in lieu of $500,000 bond while bond was
set at $300,000 for Stallworth. Cooks was to be returned to Dallas
from Houston, said an officer who refused to give his name.
</TEXT>
