<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     02-29 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matt and Ben Kearney did more homework, read
more books and spent more time with their parents while facing the
ultimate challenge, an entire year without television.
   It came to a festive end at a family party when their father,
lawyer Mike Kearney, handed each boy a packet of 10 $50 bills tied
up in a red ribbon and then turned the television set back on at
7:30 p.m. Thursday.
   ``It feels real weird,'' said 9-year-old Matt, flipping channels
quickly between the Olympics, ``Jeopardy'' and ``Magnum P.I.'' ``It
feels like I'm not supposed to be doing it.''
   Kearney got the idea about the year without television when he
read about a New Jersey boy whose mother offered him $500 to turn
off the set for a year.
   ``Every day they'd get up in the morning and watch TV until they
went to school,'' Kearney said. ``Then they'd come home and watch
it the rest of the day. On weekends they'd watch it until their ...
eyes bugged out.''
   It took the two brothers about ``two seconds'' to take their
father up on the challenge, Ben, 11, said.
   The first days were the hardest. ``The first night we sort of
played more and then went to bed,'' Ben said. ``And then the next
morning we got up and thought, `What are we going to watch?' And
then we remembered we couldn't.''
   Their mother, Shannon Kearney, saw the project as an exercise in
self control. The rest of the family, including 5-year-old Patrick,
had continued watching television.
   The boys plan to spend part of their money on a home video game
and save the rest.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WINNIE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A graduate of Texas A&M, whose alumni are
dubbed Aggies and are the butt of some farming jokes in Texas, has
some of his fields under water and dumps hay on them, leading some
anonymous wag to proclaim it an ``Aggie Hay Farm.''
   But John Gaulding, 41, is not trying to grow hay. He's feeding
crawfish.
   Gaulding farms about 1,200 acres about 60 miles east of Houston
and leases about 300 acres to people who raise the freshwater
crustaceans, especially popular in Cajun cuisine.
   He said he didn't appreciate it when a sign with the message
``Aggie Hay Farm'' mysteriously appeared in front of his land in
October.
   ``At first, it seemed like a harmless prank,'' Gaulding said
Sunday. ``I had no idea who did it. I don't know if they really
even knew that it was a crawfish farm.''
   ``We left it up for a couple of days. People were asking us to
leave it up, and there was so much talk, finally we decided we
would,'' he said. ``I figured if A&M could win the Cotton Bowl, I
could put up with a little kidding about it.''
</TEXT>
