<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PuertoRico-Dominicans 1stLd-Writethru a0584 02-29 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Puerto Rico-Dominicans, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0584,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boat Sinks Off Puerto Rico Carrying More Than 40 People</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead to raise reference to Dominican Republic.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANK GAUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AGUADA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities said today that a small
wooden boat carrying illegal aliens from the Dominican Republic
sank in rough seas off the west coast of Puerto Rico. A survivor
was quoted as saying more than 40 people were aboard.
   Elmer Hasker, deputy district director for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in San Juan, said one illegal alien was in
INS custody, another hospitalized, two bodies had been recovered
and another had been spotted but washed away before it could be
retrieved.
   One of the two known survivors ``has stated that there were
approximately 40 people on the boat,'' Hasker said in a telephone
interview in San Juan. ``We don't know anything about their
situation ... whether they drowned or made it to shore is unknown
at this point.''
   The boat sank during the weekend off Aguada, about 85 miles west
of the capital San Juan. At the time, the seas were very rough and
it was very windy.
   In a telephone interview from Aguada, police spokeswoman Evelyn
Crespo said a survivor told authorities there were 45 people on the
boat, including 37 men and eight women.
   Police said the two bodies were of two girls, one 14, the other
16.
   Ms. Crespo said one of the survivors reported the group left
from the province of Higuey, on the southeastern tip of the
Dominican Republic, early Saturday. The survivors were rescued
around 10 p.m. Sunday, she said.
   There was no information available on why the boat sank. Hasker
said the boat apparently sank Sunday night.
   ``The boat has washed ashore so it was close enough that it
didn't disintegrate,'' Hasker said.
   Estimates on the length of the boat ranged from 20 to 30 feet.
   This morning a vessel from the Commonwealth Maritime Police
searched the waters off Aguada for survivors and bodies, and INS
and local officials searched the land, INS Border Patrol Agent Luis
Garcia in a telephone interview from Aguadilla, about five miles
from Aguada.
   Garcia said some clothes had been found along the beach in
Aguada but there was no way of knowing whether they belonged to
those aboard the boat that sank.
   In October, as many as 100 Dominicans are believed to have died
when their boat sank about three miles off the north east coast of
the Dominican Republic as they started their journey to Puerto Rico.
   Hundreds of Dominicans leave their country each year in wooden
boats to make the dangerous crossing to Puerto Rico, where they
hope to find jobs and a better life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
