<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Security     02-29 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Security,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Take Up Case of Fired NSC Worker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today agreed to decide
whether employees of a Pentagon intelligence agency are entitled to
administrative hearings when they are fired as security risks.
   The justices said they will hear Reagan administration arguments
that those who work for the National Security Agency are not
entitled to such procedural protection.
   The case raises issues similar to those in a case decided
Tuesday by the high court.
   In that ruling, the court said the Merit Systems Protection
Board _ which provides job protection to federal workers _ lacks
authority to reinstate an employee fired for lacking a security
clearance. The court upheld the firing of a laborer at a Navy
installation.
   In the case acted on today, the justices will review a ruling
that granted an administrative hearing to an unidentified NSA
employee who said he was fired because he engaged in homosexual
activities.
   The employee, identified only as John Doe, works with secret
codes for the spy agency.
   He told his superiors in 1982 that he had homosexual relations
with several foreigners during vacation travels abroad.
   After a psychiatric evaluation, the NSA _in a decision upheld by
the defense secretary _ ordered him fired on grounds his
``indiscriminate'' sexual activities posed a security risk since he
had access in his job to the most secret type of classified
information. The agency said the fact the acts were homosexual was
not the determining factor.
   Doe then filed a federal court suit, claiming the Department of
Defense violated a federal civil service law entitling him to an
administrative hearing.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with him in a ruling
last June.
   The appeals court said, ``As the government acknowledges, in
this case the (defense) secretary has not found that a hearing
would itself contravene national security. Accordingly, (Doe) is
entitled by law to that hearing.''
   Caspar Weinberger was secretary of defense at the time of Doe's
firing. Since then, he has been succeeded by Frank Carlucci.
   The case is Carlucci vs. Doe, 87-751.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
