<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Flag     02-29 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Flag,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha: Government May Agree to Remove Union Jack From Flag</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha suggested
Monday that his government might comply with a demand by some
British lawmakers that the Union Jack be removed from the South
African flag.
   Members of all three main parties in Britain's Parliament,
citing Botha's latest crackdown on black oppositon, urged their
government on Saturday to request that a replica of the British
flag be removed from the South African flag.
   The Union Jack and the flags of two South African provinces are
displayed in the center of South Africa's flag as symbols of the
country's past.
   ``The flag of South Africa not only relates to our history but
is indeed a symbol of national unity and nationhood,'' Botha said.
``It is surprising that the agitation against the South African
flag from Britain is not taking into consideration the feelings of
the English-speaking South Africans.''
   ``But if the British government wishes to interfere with the
composition of a South Africa symbol on this basis, the question
may be asked whether the South African Parliament should not give
this matter its serious attention.''
   Designed 60 years ago, the South African flag was intended to
show how the country was formed by a merger of British-controlled
territory and the former Afrikaner republics of Transvaal and the
Orange Free State. The mainly Dutch-descended Afrikaners make up
about 60 percent of the 5 million whites, while most of the others
have British ancestry.
   The British and Afrikaners battled each in the Boer War that
ended in 1902, and strains between the two still surface.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
