<HEAD>Business As Usual For Acting Governor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Gov. Rose Mofford held to a regular
schedule Monday as the Senate began its impeachment trial of Evan
Mecham.
   Mrs. Mofford held a routine 9 a.m. staff meeting, said her press
secretary, Athia Hardt.
   ``The only TV we have is in my office, and I don't expect it to
be on most of the day,'' Ms. Hardt said. ``We'll probably just
catch it like everybody else when we go home at night.''
   Mrs. Mofford has told department heads not to watch the trial
and her Department of Administration director has instructed state
employees not to watch it during work hours, Ms. Hardt said.
   Mrs. Mofford, a Democrat elected as secretary of state, became
acting governor when the House impeached Mecham, the elected
Republican governor, on charges he illegally concealed a $350,000
campaign loan, misused $80,000 in state money and obstructed
justice.
   Mecham, who says he is innocent, also faces a recall election in
May and a criminal trial next month on six felony charges stemming
from the campaign loan.
   Mrs. Mofford would become governor should Mecham be convicted at
either trial. Should Mecham lose the recall, the opponent who
received the most votes would become governor.
</TEXT>
