<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Iran-Iraq 3rdLd-Writethru a0562 02-29 0774</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0562,0792</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranian Missiles Hit Baghdad, Many Casualties Reported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs, IRNA says 16 killed at the hospital.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs ``Tehran Radio..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said it fired three missiles into
the Iraqi capital of Baghdad before dawn today and Iraq said two
missiles crashed into residential areas, killing many civilians.
   Twelve hours later, Iran's official media reported Iraqi
warplanes bombed residential districts of Tehran and hit a
hospital. Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, said 16 people were killed at the hospital and ``dozens
wounded, including newborn babies.''
   Tehran Radio, also monitored in Nicosia, urged Iranians to take
refuge in recently built bomb shelters. It was the second time the
Iraqis have bombed Tehran in three days.
   The Turkish Anatolia news agency said one bomb exploded 300
yards from a downtown hotel where State Minister Yusuf Ozal of
Turkey was staying with an official delegation led by Prime
Minister Turgut Ozal, his brother.
   There were no reports of Turkish casualties.
   Earlier today, Baghdad's official Iraqi News Agency, monitored
in Nicosia, quoted a military spokesman as saying Iranian artillery
also shelled residential areas of the embattled southern port of
Basra and the border town of Khanaqin, 80 miles northeast of
Baghdad during the night. He made no mention of casualties.
   It was the third straight day of attacks on cities and
industrial centers by the two Persian Gulf war foes, beginning when
Iraqi warplanes bombed Tehran on Saturday for the first time in
months.
   The attacks heightened fears that the two nations had begun
another round of the so-called ``war of the cities'' that started
in March 1985.
   In other action, Iran claimed Kurdish guerrillas and
Revolutionary Guards killed or wounded 350 Iraqis on Sunday in
fighting in northeast Iraq.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, quoting a military
communique, said Kurdish guerrillas beat back an assault by Iraqi
special forces on positions in Erbil province, killing or wounding
250 men.
   The agency said Iranian Revolutionary Guards killed or wounded
another 100 Iraqis in a bombardment of Iraqi positions in the
mountainous Kurdistan region. IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said
Revolutionary Guards gunners fired the three surface-to-surface
missiles at the Baghdad headquarters of Iraq's state-run television
and radio network and ``two military targets'' in Baghdad.
   IRNA said the Iranians fired the missiles in retaliation for
Iraqi air raids ``on non-military areas'' in Tehran, the Kurdish
city of Saqqez in northwest Iran, Dezful in southwest Khuzestan
province, and the western city of Hamadan in recent days.
   It said 28 civilians were killed in those raids, with scores
more wounded.
   The communique warned ``the Iraqi government that its renewed
attacks on civilian areas will not go unanswered,'' IRNA reported.
   Baghdad Radio did not identify the Baghdad residential districts
it said were hit by the missiles, believed to be Soviet-made,
Scud-B weapons supplied to Iran by Libya and Syria.
   The explosions were heard across the city of 5 million.
   ``Many Iraqis were killed, among them women, children and old
people. Many more were wounded and many houses were destroyed,''
the communique said. No exact casualty figures were given.
   The radio quoted an unidentified military spokesman as warning:
``All Iranian cities are now targets for our air and missile forces
until further notice. The losers in the end will be the rulers in
Tehran.''
   The missiles were the first to hit the Iraqi capital since Nov.
8. The Iranians have fired eight missiles into the city since the
U.N. Security Council called for a cease-fire in the 7-year-old war
on July 20 last year.
   Altogether, Iran has fired 37 missiles into Baghdad since March
1985, when the two sides began the ``war of the cities.''
   Thousands of civilians on both sides have been killed or wounded
in the intermittent campaigns involving air raids, missiles and
long-range artillery bombardments. In one of the worst missile
attacks, more than 30 children were killed and more than 100
wounded when their school was hit Oct. 13.
   Tehran's War Information Headquarters said Iranian warplanes on
Sunday bombed a petrochemical plant in the southern Iraqi port of
Basra, oil installations in Abul Khassib in the southeast and a
bridge linking Iraq with Umm Rassas island in the Shatt al-Arab
waterway.
   Baghdad said long-range Iranian artillery shelled six border
towns and cities Saturday and Sunday, killing and wounding an
undisclosed number of civilians.
   Baghdad Radio said Iraqi warplanes later Sunday bombed Hamadan
in eastern Iran and Dezful in the southeast in retaliation for
``recent atrocities and crimes committed by the charlatans of
Iran.''
</TEXT>
