<1ST_LINE>r w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     02-29 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court to Consider Barring Customs from Conducting Drug Tests for
Applicants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   DRUG TESTS
   
   The court agreed to consider barring the U.S. Customs Service
from conducting drug tests for people seeking drug-enforcement
jobs, setting the stage for its first ruling on the
constitutionality of mandatory drug-testing for public employees.
   The court said it will hear a challenge to the testing program
by a federal workers labor union that says taking urine samples
from employees violates their privacy rights.
   The case is National Treasury Employees Union vs. Von Raab,
86-1879.
   
   ATOMIC TESTS
   
   The court refused to revive lawsuits charging the government and
federal contrctors with negligently causing deaths and disease
among people exposed to open-air atomic tests.
   The court, without comment, let stand a federal law that
effectively spared the government from having to defend itself
against claims seeking billions of dollars.
   The case is Konizski vs. Livermore Labs, 87-953.
   
   MEDICARE
   
   The court agreed to consider letting the federal government
apply retroactively a formula that limits reimbursement paid to
hospitals treating Medicare patients.
   The court said it will hear Reagan administraion arguments that
some hospitals could reap a windfall from the ban on retroactive
application of the formula.
   The case is Bowen vs. Georgetown University Hospital, 87-1097.
   
   EMBASSY DOCUMENTS
   
   The court let stand rulings that threw out a reporter's attempt
to force the State Department to release documents from U.S.
embassies around the world.
   The lawsuit by Donald F. Goldberg, a reporter on the staff of
syndicated columnist Jack Anderson, had been filed under the
Freedom of Information Act. He had sought from the State Department
responses to an unclassified 1982 questionnaire on foreign
governments' diplomatic practices.
   The case is Goldberg vs. State Department, 87-655.
   
   BINGO
   
   The court asked the Reagan administration whether it thinks
high-stakes bingo games run by Indian tribes are subject to state
sales taxes.
   The court said it wants to hear from Justice Department lawyers
before it says whether it will review an attempt by Oklahoma
officials to tax revenue from a bingo game in Tulsa run by the
Muscogee Creek Nation.
   The case is Oklahoma Tax Commission vs. Muscogee Creek Nation,
87-1068.
   
   SECURITY RISKS
   
   The court agreed to decide whether employees of a Pentagon
intelligence agency are entitled to administrative hearings when
the government fires them as security risks.
   The justices said they will hear Reagan administration arguments
that those who work for the National Security Agency are not
entitled to such procedural protection.
   The case is Carlucci vs. Doe, 87-751.
   
   PATERNITY
   
   The court agreed to decide whether states may block a man from
trying to prove he fathered the child of a woman married to someone
else.
   The court said it will study a challenge by a man identified in
court records only as Michael H., to a state evidentiary rule
creating a conclusive presumption of fatherhood to a wife's husband.
   The case is Michael H. vs. Gerald D., 87-746.
   
   HI-FI KILLINGS
   
   The court let stand the conviction of a man sentenced to death
in Utah for his role in the 1974 killings of three people forced to
swallow drain cleaner before they were shot.
   The justices let stand William Andrews' conviction and death
sentence for the three murders committed during an Aril 22, 1974
robbery of an Ogden hi-fi store.
   The case is Andrews vs. Shulsen, 87-5449.
   
   RACETRACK SEARCHES
   
   The court let stand rulings that warrantless searches of
Illinois racetrack employees' on-grounds living quarters violate
constitutionally protected privacyrights.
   The Illinois Racing Board for years had authorized state law
enforcement officers to search, without warrants, the rooms of
employees who feed, groom, exercise and generally take care of
racehorses.
   The case is Arkansas vs. Mayfield, 87-1105.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
