<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Violence 3rdLd-Writethru a0533 02-29 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Violence, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0533,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rioting Reported In Azerbaidzhan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs, dissident says violence linked to
conflict between Armenia, Azerbaidzhan. Picks up 7th graf pvs ``An
official at... '' CORRECTS Soveit Union to Russian Republic in
next-to-the-last graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rioting broke out in an industrial city in
Azerbaidzhan, the Tass news agency reported today. A dissident said
the violence was sparked by tensions between Armenians and
Azerbaidzhan's dominant ethnic group, the Azeris.
   The Tass report said the disturbances Sunday in Sumgait, a city
on the Caspian Sea, were provoked by ``a group of hooligans,'' and
``rampage and violence followed.'' The agency said measures were
adopted ``to normalize the situation.''
   The official Soviet agency gave no indication what led to the
violence.
   Armenians in huge numbers took to the streets last week in their
capital, Yerevan, to demand that a region of Azerbaidzhan that has
a largely Armenian population be made part of their republic.
   Of Sunday's violence in Sumgait, a city some 1,500 miles from
Moscow, dissident Sergei Grigoryants said: ``Thugs in Sumgait went
up to people and asked them if they were Armenian or not. They
started to beat people who said they were Armenians. Several people
were knifed.''
   Grigoryants, who lives in Moscow but is of Armenian origin, said
it appeared that no one was killed in Sumgait. He said ``several
dozen'' Azeris were reportedly involved in the attacks.
   Grigoryants said by telephone that he received his information
on the unrest from sources in Yerevan.
   Tass said an investigation has been launched into the violence
at Sumgait.
   The four-paragraph Tass dispatch gave only sketchy details of
the violence and did not say whether there had been deaths or
injuries. The report did not say who was involved in the unrest or
say what caused the violence.
   An official at the Azerbaidzhani government's offices in Moscow
contacted today by telephone refused to give any details of the
unrest.
   ``Everything will be printed in the central press and shown on
television,'' said the official, who refused to give his name.
   Telephone calls placed from Moscow to Baku, the Azerbaidzhani
capital 20 miles southeast of Sumgait, did not immediately go
through.
   Sumgait, with a population of more than 160,000, is the second
largest city in Azerbaidzhan after the capital. Sumgait is 150
miles from the autonomous region of Nagorno-Karabakh, which is at
the center of a dispute between Armenia and Azerbaidzhan.
   The Armenians want the Nagorno-Karabakh region, which has been
part of Azerbaidzhan for 65 years, returned to Armenia. Three
quarters of the 157,000 residents are Armenian.
   Last week hundreds of thousands of Armenians took to the streets
in Yerevan, Armenia's capital, calling for the region's annexation.
   Protests also occurred in Nagorno-Karabakh backing the call.
   On Friday, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed for
``civil maturity and restraint'' in an address read on Armenian
television by a senior party official. In the address, Gorbachev
promised that the Communist Party Central Committee would review
relations among the Soviet Union's more than 100 nationalities.
   That same day Gorbachev also met with two prominent Armenian
writers to help work out a solution to the Armenian problem.
   Azerbaidzhan is the largest of three Soviet republics in the
Caucasus. It is bounded on the west by the Soviet republics of
Armenia and Georgia, on the north by the Russian Republic. The
Caspian Sea runs for nearly 800 miles along its eastern edge and to
the south lies Iran.
   The republic is predominately Shiite Moslem, expect for the
Armenian Christians living in the Nagorno-Karbakh region.
</TEXT>
