<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KennedyConfusion     02-29 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Confusion,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Ron Burrows, A 25-Year `Nuisance' Coming To An End</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HYANNIS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has happened so many times over the
past 25 years that Ron Burrows long ago lost count.
   A car drives toward Burrows' house, the heads inside turning
about, until it comes to a stop in his driveway at the end of the
short road leading to Craigville Beach. The befuddled motorist
either turns the car around or asks Burrows for directions.
   The problem: The Kennedy family compound is accessible only from
Irving Avenue in Hyannisport, a half mile from Irving Street, where
Burrows lives.
   ``I'm so used to directing cars to the Kennedy compound that
I've even thought of setting up an information booth and charging
them 10 cents a piece,'' Burrows joked Monday.
   Now, his days as an informal tour guide are coming to an end.
   He and the other residents of Irving Street last week persuaded
town officials to change the name of the dead-end street to Inwood
Lane. The name change became official Thursday; Burrows is just
waiting for a public works crew to change the street sign.
   ``That might take a couple of months,'' he said.
   Burrows, 80, doesn't blame tourists for seeking a peek at the
Kennedy compound.
   ``But it was a nuisance with all the cars coming up such a small
street and sometimes it was a problem because big trucks trying to
deliver merchandise to the compound would end up here.''
</TEXT>
