<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Argentina-Faith Bjt   02-29 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Faith, Bjt,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protestant Evangelism Growing Rapidly in Argentina</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protestant fundamentalism is
growing rapidly in this predominantly Roman Catholic nation, and
American missionary Don Exley's yellow and white revival tent
symbolizes the movement.
   One night last week, 63 people crossed a muddy field in a hard
rain to hear Exley, who represents the Assemblies of God, preach a
spirited sermon in Spanish. He told them God would save their souls
if they prayed hard enough and sang loud enough.
   Before the two-hour revival ended in the tent in suburban
Martinez, many of the men, women and children, had ``spoken in
tongues'' and eight bowed before Exley to be saved. Exley said his
revival attract crowds of up to 200 people.
   ``The Assemblies of God is trying to minister to felt needs,''
Exley said in an interview. ``People come, and they're coming more
and more, because they're hurting financially, physically or in
their relations with family.''
   Sidney Rooy of Buenos Aires, a historian of religion, said
Pentecostal churches are the fastest-growing religious movements
among Argentina's 31 million people. The Assemblies of God arrived
here 40 years ago, but its rapid growth began just five years ago.
   Another historian, the Rev. Timothy Hamilton of Buenos Aires,
said the popularity of Protestant evangelism has been growing for a
decade. Exley claims Argentina now has about 2.8 million
evangelical Christians in a population that is 90 percent Catholic.
   Jimmy Swaggart, the disgraced Assemblies of God television
evangelist, visited Argentina in 1986 on a four-nation crusade that
included Brazil, Chile and Paraguay. A packed house of 60,000 heard
him preach at the River Plate Stadium in Buenos Aires.
   Carlos Annacondia, a former salesman, probably is the most
popular Argentine evangelist. He preaches in Quilmes, just outside
the capital.
   In his magazine Abundant Life, he published pictures of a recent
crusade in Paraguay during which he met President Alfredo
Stroessner, the general who has ruled that neighboring country
since a coup in 1954. He features the meeting with Stroessner in
promotional material.
   Exley attributes the popularity of his religious movement, in
part, to years of high inflation and ``disillusionment with
military government and democratic government.''
   He holds revivals four to six nights a week in the tent. Exley,
38, has been an Assemblies of God missionary since 1976 in
Argentina and Argentina.
   As an example of his denomination's growth, he cites Cordoba,
the northwestern industrial center and second-largest city of
Argentina. Exley said he began the Assemblies of God ministry there
12 years ago with 75 people in a small church, and Cordoba now has
20 churches serving 3,000-4,000 members.
   The church claims up to 14 million members in Brazil, one-tenth
of the population, and 12,000 in Paraguay.
   When asked how the movement will be affected by the Swaggart sex
scandal, Exley said: ``For sure it affects his credibility, it
affects his credibility a lot. I'm sure it'll affect his finances.
But it's very early to know how far-reaching.''
   Swaggart's tearful confession of sin was was front-page news in
Argentina.
   Exley said Swaggart and the Assemblies of God provided most of
the money for the block-long lot where the tent stands, provide the
Swaggart television program dubbed in Spanish and were expected to
help build a church complex.
   Other financial help from the Swaggart group included financing
an elementary school in the lower-class Lomas de Zamora section of
Buenos Aires, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
