<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CityWorkers     02-29 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-City Workers,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Orders Investigation After Film Shows Idle City Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Federico Pena has ordered an investigation
into reports that street crews spend more time eating and reading
than working.
   ``I am outraged by the information ... that a handful of city
employees has been wasting taxpayers' dollars by intentionally
neglecting their assigned responsibilities as members of the city's
work crews,'' Pena said in a statement.
   He commented after seeing a news series that KUSA-TV of Denver
began broadcasting Sunday. The station's news crews followed city
crews for eight hours and videotaped them with a hidden camera.
   Complaints about the city's Public Works Department, including
slow cleanup following a December blizzard, have fueled a recall
effort against Pena.
   The station taped several street crews leaving public works
yards in the morning, then spending time at stores, restaurants and
talking with other crews.
   In one case, KUSA said, a crew drove 64 miles but did no work in
its eight-hour shift while visiting five food stores.
   Pena said disciplinary action would be taken against city
workers who could be identified from the videotape.
   ``While the evidence appears to implicate less than 10 of the
city's 11,000 employees, the type of intolerable and inexcusable
behavior allegedly involved unjustly damages the reputation of the
overwhelming number of city employees who have worked long and hard
on behalf of the people of Denver,'' Pena said.
   Pena also said earlier evidence had led him to begin a
management review to improve supervision in the city's pothole
repair operation.
   Chuck Mills, president of the city employee's union and a public
works employee, said if there were problems with workers taking
excessive time off, they were isolated.
</TEXT>
