<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WarPowers     02-29 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-War Powers,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Urges Appeals Court To Stay Out Of Dispute With
Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Monday urged a
federal appeals court to stay out of a dispute over whether the War
Powers Resolution should have been invoked when the Navy began
escorting oil tankers in the Persian Gulf.
   Justice Department attorney James Spears urged a three-judge
panel to uphold a lower court's dismissal of a lawsuit brought by
110 members of Congress to force President Reagan to report to
Congress that U.S. forces were sent into hostilities last summer in
the Persian Gulf.
   ``Our policy has begun to bear fruit,'' Spears said of the
Navy's operation to protect reflagged Kuwaiti oil tankers from
attack by warring Iraqi or Iranian forces in the Persian Gulf.
``For a court to recharacterize the U.S. role threatens to undercut
this progress.''
   Spears called the issue ``quintessentially a non-justiciable
political question'' that courts cannot decide.
   ``This is a situation where a political decision has been made
by the political branches, it is not one for the judicial branch to
come in and second guess,'' Spears said.
   The 1973 War Powers Resolution requires that in the absence of a
declared war the president must notify Congress within 48 hours of
placing U.S. forces in hostilities.
   The lawsuit was filed by Rep. Michael Lowery, D-Wash., and other
members of Congress, after President Reagan refused to file a
report notifying Congress that the Navy ships escorting reflagged
Kuwaiti oil tankers had been sent into hosilities.
   The case was dismissed late last year by U.S. District Judge
George Revercomb, who ruled that courts did not have jurisdiction
to consider the claim.
   Alan Morrison, an attorney representing the lawmakers, argued
that ``unless we are to say the statute is unenforceable... it
seems to me the court has the power to at least require that the
president file the report'' with Congress.
   Chief Judge Patricia Wald questioned Spears' assertion that
courts are not qualified to decide what situation amounts to
hostilities, which is essentially a military and diplomatic
question.
   Recalling Vietnam, Wald said that if ``people are in jungles
fighting and dying ... you would say that is still a political
question, if the president did not want to submit the report'' to
Congress.
   ``No matter what's going on overseas, that's a political
question,'' Spears said. He said Congress has the power under the
Constitution to declare war. ``Congress can't take the power that
the Constitution assigned it and assign it to a court'' to decide
the question.
   Judge Stephen Williams questioned why Congress had not passed
resolutions declaring that the Persian Gulf operation was covered
by the War Powers Resolution.
   ``The fact that Congress hasn't acted is not relevant'' to
whether the president must obey the resolution's requirment that he
notify Congress that a military operation has begun, Morrison said.
   The War Powers Resolution was enacted because Congress was
concerned that its role in deciding whether to send U.S. troops
into armed conflict had been greatly diminished, Morrison said.
   ``The whole purpose of the War Powers Resolution is not to have
to pass a new law every time we have a Vietnam or a Cambodia,''
Morrison said.
   But Williams said the lawmakers who filed the suit were
``inviting courts to add a third voice to U.S. foreign policy where
events found by a court fitted into the meaning of the resolution.''
   The resolution provides that once he has reported that U.S.
forces have entered hostilities, the president must withdraw troops
in 60 days if Congress doesn't formally declare war or the
lawmakers take action to extend the deadline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1416EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NATOSummit Bjt   02-29 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO Summit, Bjt,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allies To Back Reagan But Express Private Doubts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For European leaders, this week's NATO
summit is a welcome chance to join President Reagan in trumpeting
alliance unity and highlighting its recent successes.
   Privately, though, the Europeans may add some words of worry.
   The most immediate concern to Europeans is a lack of Western
consensus on how to balance the need to guard against a possible
Soviet attack with the hope for further reductions in East-West
tensions.
   A more deeply rooted worry is that budgetary pressures may soon
compel Washington to pull some of its 326,000 troops out of Western
Europe.
   The summit meeting Wednesday and Thursday is likely to declare
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization united on the need to keep
some nuclear weapons in Europe. The problem is deciding how many
and which kinds.
   It also is expected to demand that the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact
alliance accept proportionally bigger conventional arms and troop
cuts than the West, according to NATO sources familiar with
preparations for the summit.
   But the summit will sidestep, at least in public, the questions
of whether and when to improve NATO's very short-range atomic arms,
most of which are deployed by the United States on West German
soil. Smaller numbers are in Belgium, Britain, the Netherlands,
Italy and Turkey.
   Attention has been drawn to these weapons, which include
ballistic nuclear missiles and artillery, since Reagan and Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed a treaty in December eliminating
more than 2,000 U.S. and Soviet nuclear missiles which have ranges
from 300 to 3,000 miles.
   Moscow has suggested scrapping all short-range nuclear arms, of
which the East bloc has more than a 10-1 numerical edge in Europe,
according to NATO figures.
   But Lord Carrington, the NATO secretary general, said in a
recent interview that all 16 alliance members are steadfastly
opposed to such a complete elimination. Alliance members see the
short-range weapons as vital to NATO's strategy of responding to an
attack with a full range of military options.
   ``The one thing that everybody is agreed on is that you can't
have a third zero,'' Carrington said, refering to the INF treaty
which eliminates two categories of nuclear missile.
   West Germany, however, wants NATO to begin negotiations to bring
the Soviet total of short-range nuclear arms down to NATO's level.
But most of the other allies worry that such talks would eventually
lead to a total ban on these weapons. They want to hold off until
progress is made in reducing Soviet advantages in conventional and
chemical arms.
   A further complication is Washington's desire, backed most
strongly by Britain, to upgrade NATO's short-range nuclear arsenal,
in part by deploying a new, longer-range version of the Lance
ballistic missile. Key factions of the Bonn government strongly
oppose this, saying it would force West Germany to bear too much of
the nuclear risk.
   Although Bonn and Washington appear to have agreed to play down
the short-range nuclear issue, British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher is expected to tell the Brussels summit that NATO must
carry through with a commitment, first made in 1983, to upgrade
these weapons.
   French President Franoics Mitterrand, however, has indicated
that he is unhappy with the public focus on improving NATO's
remaining nuclear arsenal.
   ``It would be paradoxical and inopportune to overarm just now''
as Washington and Moscow are striving to further improve East-West
relations, Mitterrand said in an interview published Monday by
France's largest circulation newspaper, Oeust-France.
   The presence of Mitterrand at the NATO meeting is significant.
It demonstrates a growing desire by France to tighten its political
links to the alliance.
   No French president has attended a NATO summit since President
Charles de Gaulle pulled French forces out of NATO's joint command
in 1966.
   Beyond the immediate concerns about how to organize Western arms
control priorities, the European leaders view the Brussels meeting
as an opportunity to underscore their support for the U.S.-Soviet
missile treaty, which must receive a two-thirds vote of approval in
the U.S. Senate.
   The Europeans also are eager to publicize their support for
Reagan in advance of his expected meeting with Gorbachev in Moscow
in May or June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
