<DOCNO> AP880229-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FineInflation     02-29 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fine Inflation,250</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release 6 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Inflation Erodes the Impact of Fines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation has pulled the enforcement teeth
from many government safety laws by reducing the impact of fines, a
coalition of consumer groups said Monday.
   Penalties for violating various health and safety laws have
remained essentially unchanged over the years, while inflation has
reduced the value of the amounts involved, the Consumer Federation
of America and the U.S. Public Interest Research Group said in a
report.
   ``Letting civil penalties be eroded by inflation operates as if
there were a built-in depreciation schedule in our key health and
safety statutes,'' said Michael Waldman of the group Public
Citizen's Congress Watch, in a statement released with the study.
   Examples cited in the study included:
   _The Occupational Safety and Health Act of 1970 retains its
original penalties of $1,000 per violation and $10,000 for failure
to provide a safe workplace. To keep place with inflation these
would have to increase to $2,970 and $29,700.
   _The Federal Aviation Act has retained the same $1,000 fine for
violations of safety rules since 1958. Inflation has reduced its
value to one-quarter of the original worth.
   _The Consumer Product Safety Commission Act civil penalties of
$2,000 per violation up to a maximum of $500,000 have not changed
since 1972, with inflation reducing them to 36 percent of their
original impact.
   The consumer groups submitted copies of the study to Congress in
support of a bill to adjust the civil penalties in federal laws to
keep them up to date with inflation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
