<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burt     02-29 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burt,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Ambassador Says Soviet Land War Capability a Key Topic</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ability of the Soviet Union to
wage an offensive land war is the ``most destabilizing factor'' in
European security and is likely to be a key topic at this week's
NATO summit, the U.S. ambassador to West Germany said Monday.
   Ambassador Richard Burt, in an interview with The Associated
Press, also termed ``a publicity stunt'' last week's removal of
some Soviet missiles from East Germany and Czechoslovakia.
   He predicted that differences of opinion over modernizing
short-range nuclear missiles and other points of dispute would not
disrupt the Atlantic Alliance meeting in Brussels Wednesday and
Thursday.
   ``There is a growing consensus emerging within the Alliance _
which I believe will be reflected in the summit _ on the importance
now of negotiations on enhancing conventional arms stability,''
Burt said.
   ``There has been a focus on the nuclear dimension of security in
Europe,'' he said. ``But there is a growing view that the time has
come now to focus on the most destabilizing factor in European
security, which is the Soviet capability to wage an offensive war
against Western Europe.''
   ``Their forces are deployed, structured and trained to fight an
offensive war in Europe,'' Burt said, adding later that he meant an
``offensive land war.''
   Burt said it was mandatory to address this problem in arms
control negotiations.
   ``Military power casts a political shadow. The threat is not
just one of outright invasion.''
   There are about 990,000 active duty NATO troops in central
Europe, most of them in West Germany. Western sources say they face
about 1.2 million Soviet-led Warsaw Pact troops in Eastern Europe.
   West German leaders already have begun calling on the Soviet to
reduce their superiority in conventional weapons and undertake
other arms control measures.
   During the pre-summit preparations, Washington officials had a
highly publicized dispute with West German officials over U.S.
insistence on the need to modernize short-range nuclear weapons in
Western Europe.
   The Reagan administration later promised not to insist on the
modernization issue as a topic at this week's summit.
   ``There are no serious differences between Bonn and Washington
on these subjects,'' added the 41-year-old ambassador, an expert on
arms control and European security issues.
   Burt has been speaking out against claims by some politicians in
Bonn that the intermediate-range missile treaty signed in December
leaves West Germany vulnerable to Soviet nuclear attack.
   ``We will continue to be able to deter an attack in Europe with
U.S. nuclear weapons deployed in Europe and at sea,'' he said.
``There is a sense that this agreement leads to the
denuclearization of Europe. That is not the case.''
   ``In fact ... we should resist a trend towards the
denuclearization of Europe,'' he added.
   Asked about the highly publicized removal of some Soviet SS-12
rockets from Warsaw Pact members East Germany and Czechoslovakia
last week, Burt said: ``I tend to think this was basically a
publicity stunt.''
   ``I think they were mainly aiming to win points with Western
public opinion,'' Burt said.
   The ambassador added that only when the Soviets comply with the
verification provisions of the treaty will there be certainty that
the missiles have been destroyed. The treaty is awaiting
ratification by the U.S. Senate.
</TEXT>
