<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Supco-MentalIllness     02-29 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Supco-Mental Illness,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Rules Psychiatrist Not Negligent In Mental Illness Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychiatrist who failed to commit a
mentally ill man can not be held negligent in the man's commission
of murder three days later, the Maine Supreme Court ruled Monday.
   Laurence D. Herst was acting in an official capacity on behalf
of the state and therefore immune from civil liability when he
examined Henry A. Taylor and determined he did not need to be
involuntarily committed to a mental institution, the high court
ruled in a 6-0 decision.
   Herst was employed by the Maine Medical Center at the time.
While that is not a state-owned facility, Herst examined Taylor at
the request of the Cumberland County Sheriff's Department.
   ``Even though Dr. Herst is not employed by a state mental
hospital, he is acting in an official capacity on behalf of the
state when performing the task of determining, for involuntary
commitment purposes, whether a `person is a mentally ill individual
and because of his illness, poses a likelihood of serious harm,'''
the court said.
   Taylor was arrested Nov. 14, 1978, after he drove through toll
booths and onto a restricted area at the Portland International
Jetport. He was taken to the Cumberland County Jail, where he began
to show ``erratic and violent behavior,'' the court said.
   Herst examined Taylor and found that he did not exhibit
tendencies that indicated he was a danger to himself or others.
After Taylor refused to voluntarily commit himself, he left the
hospital.
   Three days later Taylor killed Louise Michaud, 84, during a
shooting spree. He barricaded himself in his house but surrendered
four hours later when tear gas was used to force him outside.
   In 1979, he was acquitted of murder by reason of insanity and
sentenced to the Augusta Mental Health Institute. He was released
shortly after a 1984 Supreme Court ruling that set aside a lower
court's denial of Taylor's petition that he be released from the
institute as an outpatient.
   No suit had been filed. The Supreme Court issued its opinion at
the request of a lower court with the consent of Taylor and Herst.
   Taylor's attorney, Eugene C. Coughlin of Bangor, said he had not
received a copy of Friday's decision and declined to comment.
Steven J. Mogul, an attorney for Herst, was in court and could not
be immediately reached, his secretary said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
