<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh     02-29 0498</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Resumes Bid To Derail Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN SAEED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters hurled bombs at a police
jeep and burned other vehicles Monday in a new wave of
anti-government violence designed to disrupt this week's
parliamentary elections, witnesses and police said.
   Three people, including a policeman, were injured in two bomb
blasts during a rally called to protest the deaths of three people
reportedly killed during demonstrations the day before, witnesses
said.
   Meanwhile, an opposition leader called for continued protests to
disrupt Thursday's parliamentary balloting, charging that a fair
election is impossible under the administration of President
Hussain Mohammad Ershad.
   Obaidur Rahman, general secretary for the anti-government
Bangladesh Nationalist Party, told supporters at the rally here to
form ``resistance committees'' in the villages to disrupt ``this
farcical election called to perpetuate the rule of Ershad.''
   Mohammad Ershad, a senior police official posted near the rally
site, said ``people threw three bombs at a jeep carrying
paramilitary troops. One bomb exploded inside, injuring a
policeman.''
   Four cars were set ablaze by rioters in different parts of the
city, police said.
   In downtown Hazari Bagh, protesters set fire to three election
posts and damaged seven vehicles, witnesses said. They exploded
several crude bombs before police dispersed them, the witnesses
said.
   Five vehicles were attacked and damaged near the Dhaka
University, a center of anti-government protests.
   The opposition has called for a nationwide strike on Wednesday
and Thursday to disrupt the elections. The government has ordered
all schools and colleges closed to enable teachers to work at
polling places.
   At least 100 people were killed during local elections Feb. 10
in clashes among rival political groups.
   But government officials said they already were beefing up
security at polling places.
   Information Minister Anis Ul-Islam said at least 9,000 soldiers
would be deployed to help maintain peace on election day, forming
part of a 300,000-member force that also includes village defense
forces.
   ``They are moving out now. In some places they have already
moved,'' He said.
   There are about 50 million voters but only a small percentage is
expected to vote, according to political analysts.
   Sheik Hasina, leader of the opposition Awami League, said three
people were killed during a violent clash on Sunday. The violence
began shortly after Hasina and opposition leader Khaleda Zia
addressed separate rallies at the city's main square.
   The women have led a series of strikes and demonstrations since
Nov. 10 to try to oust Ershad, a former army general who took power
in a bloodless coup in 1982.
   Ershad's Jatiya Party and several minor opposition parties are
runningup candidates for the 300 elected seats of Parliament, but
the main opposition groups have boycotted the balloting.
   The military has been the driving force in Bangladesh's
politics. In the country's 17-year history, every change in
government has been by coup. Ershad, 58, seized power in 1982 and
was elected president in a 1986 vote the opposition boycotted and
contends was rigged.
</TEXT>
