<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--SAfrica-Draft,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Goes On Trial For Draft Resistance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 35-year-old white doctor who
has worked in black townships since 1980 went on trial Monday for
refusing to report to a two-week military camp.
   Dr. Ivan Toms, who opposes mandatory conscription of whites
males, faces a jail term of up to three years if convicted.
   He has refused to apply for designation as a religious objector,
the only legal avenue available for those wishing to avoid military
service.
   Instead, Toms has called on the government to provide some form
of alternative national service for young men who object to joining
the army. He has urged that alternatives be found for those who do
not want to serve in black townships or in the bush wars in Angola
and South-West Africa.
   Toms served as an army doctor for two years following graduation
from medical school in 1978. However, he has decided to refuse
participation in the annual two-week camps required of all white
men who are physically fit.
</TEXT>
