<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     02-29 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0681</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Negotiating With Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Monday it had
sent emissaries to talk with exiled President Ferdinand Marcos, who
has praised the Aquino government and said he was ready to
negotiate his return to the Philippines.
   President Corazon Aquino said earlier Monday she would not yet
let Marcos come home. But other officials hinted he may be allowed
to return if he promises to behave and to return a some of the
billions of dollars he allegedly stole during his 20-year rule.
   In Honolulu, where Marcos has lived since his ouster in February
1986, a spokesman for the former president read a statement. It
said in part:
   ``We must recognize the achievement of the present
administration in being able to survive this long when many
countries, especially those belonging to the Third World, have
floundered and gone under water. For this we must openly and
candidly congratulate the Aquino government.''
   The statement said Marcos was ready ``to negotiate the details
and conditions under which my family and I shall return to the
Philippines for the salvation of the country from the bloody
takeover by communist insurgents.''
   Marcos spokesman Lonnie Tan said Marcos had held meetings
recently in Hawaii with Philippine Reps. Francisco Sumulong and
Egmidio Tanjuatco, both relatives of Mrs. Aquino.
   ``Indeed there were negotiations. They came over here to talk to
the president to discuss the subject of him returning to the
Philippines,'' Tan said.
   He would not say what Marcos might offer to secure his return.
   Tanjuatco, a cousin of Mrs. Aquino, told reporters Monday that
he met Marcos on Jan. 26.
   ``We met only once,'' Tanjuatco said. ``The meeting was between
him and myself only. During the meeting, Mr. Marcos reiterated to
me his desire to return to the Philippines at the earliest
opportunity.''
   Sumulong, Mrs. Aquino's uncle and majority floor leader of the
House of Representatives, said he met Marcos separately in
February. Sumulong said the former president's health was
deteriorating and that he wanted to return home ``possibly because
he believes he is near the end of his life on Earth.''
   In a statement issued through her spokesman Teodoro Benigno,
Mrs. Aquino confirmed she had sent her relatives to Honolulu.
   ``Go there and listen,'' Benigno quoted her as saying. ``If we
can listen to other people, why can't we listen to Mr. Marcos.''
   Benigno revealed no details of the talks but said there was ``no
official response to the message as far as I know.''
   Marcos fled the Philippines during a civilian-military revolt in
the wake of fraud-tainted Feb. 7, 1986 presidential elections in
which both he and Mrs. Aquino claimed victory.
   Mrs. Aquino canceled the passports of Marcos and his immediate
family and banned them from the country. Asked by reporters Monday
if she would lift the ban, she replied, ``Not yet.''
   But Sen. Neptali Gonzales, a former justice minister, told
reporters Marcos might be allowed to return if he swears allegiance
to the Aquino government and settles claims that he plundered
billions of dollars from the treasury.
   Emmanuel Pelaez, the Philippine ambassador to the United States,
told reporters in Manila that if Marcos ``returns the stolen
wealth, I think there are good chances for him to come home.''
   Meanwhile, officials said the name ``Imelda Marcos'' was on the
passenger list of a flight to Manila from Australia. A Marcos
spokesman said the former first lady was still in Hawaii.
   Immigration supervisor Rolando Mancilla said the woman arrived
Saturday on a Philippine Airlines flight from Sydney and gave a
home address in Ilocos Norte, Marcos' home province. He said a
Narcotics Command agent found the name during a routine check of
the manifest.
   In Honolulu, a servant who answered the phone at the Marcos
residence said ``she's here, he's here, both of them.'' But he
refused to give his name or put either Marcos or his wife on the
line.
</TEXT>
