<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--SpaceShuttleTransport     02-29 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Space Shuttle Transport,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA To Get Jet To Move Shuttle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA announced Monday it will
acquire a Boeing 747-100 jetliner to use as a second space shuttle
transporter.
   The 231-foot-long aircraft will be modified to carry shuttles
piggyback from landing sites back to the launch center here.
Officials said the second vehicle would increase ferrying
capability and eliminate a transportation problem that could result
if there were only one carrier and it was grounded or suffered a
mishap.
   The three remaining shuttles have not flown since the Challenger
accident two years ago. When flights resume, presently planned for
August, NASA said that, for safety reasons, shuttles will land for
the foreseeable future at the dry lakebed at Edwards Air Force
Base, Calif., instead of on the runway here, where there is little
margin for error.
   A letter contract has been signed for the aircraft with Boeing
Military Airplane Co., a division of the Boeing Co. of Seattle.
Required modifications and cost are being negotiated, NASA said.
</TEXT>
