<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1511EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-SouthernDemocrats     02-29 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southern Democrats,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leaders Discuss Endorsing Candidate Before Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Democratic leaders are
discussing the possibility of acting together on a pre-Super
Tuesday endorsement of one of the six candidates pursuing their
party's presidential nomination.
   Former Gov. Charles Robb of Virginia and Sen. Sam Nunn of
Georgia confirmed on Monday such discussions have taken place but
both cautioned against assuming that an endorsement would be
forthcoming.
   ``It's only a possibility,'' said Robb.
   Nunn described it as ``a question that is in considerable
doubt.''
   Robb and Nunn discussed the endorsement in separate interviews
during a meeting of the Democratic Leadership Council, a group of
elected officials who banded together in 1985 to halt what they
considered the leftward drift of the national party.
   Robb was chairman of the DLC the past two years and Nunn
succeeded him at this meeting.
   The agenda for the two-day meeting included discussions of the
economy, but politics was the topic that dominated most
conversation, particularly the impact of Super Tuesday March 8 when
20 states, most of them south of the Mason-Dixon Line, and American
Samoa will hold Democratic presidential primaries or caucuses.
   In a luncheon speech, Nunn, who considered entering the
Democratic presidential race and decided against it, warned that
``political marketing seems to be replacing political leadership.''
   The Georgia senator said, ``First, campaign consultants tell the
candidates what they think the public wants to hear _ usually more
services and less taxes _ then the candidates deliver the message,
usually avoiding any implication of short-term individual sacrifice
for long-term national gain.''
   ``The art of campaigning,'' he went on, ``is in danger of
becoming divorced from the art of governing. The real question of
the 1988 election is not who wins, but whether the winner can
effectively govern America.''
   Members of the DLC took the lead in convincing Southern
legislatures to schedule their presidential primaries on the same
day in an effort to give the region a stronger voice in selection
of the Democratic presidential nominee.
   Robb told the group that Super Tuesday was important ``because
Democrats can't win the White House without winning the South _
it's that simple.''
   Robb noted that one-third of the delegates to the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta in July would be selected on that
day and that the 20 states also represented 207 electoral college
votes, 76 percent of those needed to be elected president.
   ``The general election chances of the Democratic Party rest with
these 20 states. The preliminaries are over and Super Tuesday is
indisputably the main event of the primary season.''
   Four Democratic presidential candidates are in a furious battle
for support in the Super Tuesday states _ Gov. Michael Dukakis of
Massachusetts, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, Sen. Albert Gore
Jr. of Tennessee, and Jesse Jackson. Dukakis, Gephardt and Gore are
from Super Tuesday states, while Jackson, a native of South
Carolina, has a powerful base in the region's black community.
   Sen. Bob Graham of Florida said that 30 days after Super Tuesday
``there are going to be three candidates left, there'll be Dukakis,
there'll be Jackson and there will be either Gephardt or Gore.''
   The former Florida governor described Gephardt, who has made
trade the central issue of his campaign, as ``the only candidate
who is running a message campaign. So he has the benefit of
operating almost in a vacuum.''
   Graham said Gore, who has been counting on his Southern
background to attract votes on Super Tuesday, ``has got to find
some reason beyond geography to get people to vote for him.''
   Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas summed up the debate between Gore
and Gephardt this way:
   ``Gore's major argument was vote for me and I won't lose the
general election for you because I'm tough on foreign policy.
Democrats get beat by being weak on foreign policy.
   ``Gephardt's argument is I'll win the general election for you
by having a good economic policy. Democrats win on economic policy.
   ``Both of them are telling the truth. Both of them are right.''
   Clinton said he had not been involved in discussions of an
endorsement and said, ``I doubt if we could all agree.''
</TEXT>
