<1ST_LINE>r w AM-StarWarsTest     02-29 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Star Wars Test,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SDI Officials More Confident They Can Defeat Decoy Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent Star Wars space experiment has
increased the confidence of Pentagon scientists that they can
defeat attempts to fool a missile defense by using decoy warheads,
the head of the program said Monday.
   Lt. Gen. James A. Abrahamson, the Air Force general in charge of
the Strategic Defense Initiative Organization, said the so-called
Delta 181 space experiment conducted three weeks ago had provided a
``tremendous amount of data'' that already was expanding scientific
understanding of how objects look as they travel through space.
   That, in turn, will be crucial to devising infrared, radar,
laser radar and other types of sensors that can tell the difference
between a real nuclear warhead and a fake one traveling through
space, Abrahamson said at a Pentagon briefing.
   While months if not years of research are still ahead, ``I think
all of our evidence, so far ... is that, yes, we should be able to
find effective ways to discriminate'' between decoy and real
warheads, he said.
   The three-star general also acknowledged, however, that budget
cuts imposed by Congress this year have slowed the Star Wars
program by at least a year and possibly more. The Reagan
administration had wanted to spend $5.2 billion on research this
year, but received $3.5 billion.
   A future president probably will not be in a position to make a
decision on deploying a rudimentary missile defense system until
1993 or 1994, Abrahamson said, and actual deployment then could not
begin until sometime after 1995.
   Star Wars _ known formally as the Strategic Defense Initiative _
is a research program aimed at developing lasers and other types of
exotic weapons that could be deployed in space and on the ground to
automatically shoot down incoming nuclear missiles.
   Abrahamson and a top program official, Maj. Andrew J. Green,
appeared at the Pentagon on Monday to discuss Delta 181, which has
been described as the most ambitious Star Wars experiment ever
conducted in space.
   Delta 181 was launched Feb. 8 from the Kennedy Space Center in
Florida. It boosted a special satellite into space that was used
for 12 hours to conduct a series of tests.
   Sensors on the 6,000-pound satellite were used to track how a
variety of different-shaped objects appeared in space and against
various backgrounds, such as the Earth's surface and the portion of
the atmosphere just above the ground called ``Earth's limb.''
   Data from the tests are still being transmitted back to the
ground but that process should be completed by the end of the week,
Green said.
   The data already in hand, however, show a laser radar sensor on
board the satellite succeeded in highlighting ``vast differences''
in the way various objects looked in space, including contrasts
based on the weight of the object, Green said.
   SDI officials consistently have termed the mission a success,
but the magazine Aviation Week and Space Technology reported on
Feb. 15 that the satellite had been unable to complete ``battle
management fire control computations.''
   The magazine blamed the problem on computers, but Air Force Col.
John Otten, assistant director of the SDI kinetic energy office,
said at the time that the problem was caused by an optical sensor
trying to lock onto an object beyond its range.
   Some test data were lost when the sensor gave false information
to on-board computers. But Otten said the losses were minor because
the tracking exercise, in which the sensor was to look away from a
target and then back to the target, was a secondary objective of
the mission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
