<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham-Scene Bjt   02-29 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Scene, Bjt,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmitting for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Just Another Monday at Arizona Capitol for Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grass was being cut, the windows
washed and the cactus garden weeded as employees hurried to work.
Just another Monday morning at the Arizona Capitol.
   Except for the governor, who went on trial.
   Only a few of Gov. Evan Mecham's supporters showed up as his
trial began in the Senate. Seats were open in the gallery. Three
bus loads of schoolchildren made their annual field trip to learn
about government, and the plaza in front of the Senate was quiet.
   ``Most of the people are working. I had to take a chance of
losing my job to be here,'' said Andy Cosentino, a supporter of the
governor who was carrying a Bible and a placard. ``People are going
to have to make a sacrifice to make sure justice prevails.''
   While Mecham's woes have drawn some large and loud rallies, the
embattled Republican's trial opened with little fanfare. Mecham did
not attend the opening sesion.
   By the 9 a.m. scheduled start of his trial, only a half-dozen
protesters patrolled the plaza. ``More are due anytime now,'' said
Cosentino.
   By 10 a.m., their ranks had swelled to about 20.
   One woman placed a large radio by her signs so she could hear
the proceedings in the Senate, which must deliberate 23 charges
made by the House.
   A few retirees milled about. One group laid a paper railroad
across the courtyard with a drawing of the governor, gagged and
bound on the tracks.
   ``He's being railroaded,'' said Wilma Harm of Phoenix. ``The man
has done nothing to be called upon like this.''
   When the doors were opened to public seating in the gallery,
only 15 people were in line. June Reynolds, a retired government
teacher who lives in Scottsdale, arrived two hours early and was
first.
   ``I'm concerned about what's happening to the state,'' she said.
   The loudest noises in the plaza came from the lawnmowers. Even
the air was calm, and the scent of orange blossom suffused the
still air.
   The House impeached Mecham on Feb. 5, accusing him of concealing
a $350,000 campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's
protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership and trying to
thwart an investigation of an allegation that a state official
threatened the life of a grand jury witness. Two-thirds of the 30
Senate votes are required to convict.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest regional
reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
