<1ST_LINE>r w AM-OMB-CreditCards     02-29 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-OMB-Credit Cards,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Expanding Program For Payment With Credit Cards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government is expanding a program
to allow more government services and non-tax debts to be paid for
with credit cards, budget officials said Monday.
   Under the program, the government is expected to process 130
million credit-card transactions annually by next year, or $6.5
billion worth, said Joseph Wright, deputy director of the Office of
Management and Budget.
   ``It will make us the largest credit card user in the world,''
Wright said.
   The government now accepts credit cards for some items,
including publications of the Government Printing Office.
   But Wright and Budget Director James C. Miller III told a news
conference this program would be expanded to include a wide array
of new items _ from purchasing passports to paying some fines.
   Credit cards will also be more widely used by the government
itself, both to pay expenses of officials who are travelling and
for some federal procurement, the officials said.
   ``Everybody uses credit cards _ except for the federal
government,'' Miller said.
   The comments came as the White House released President Reagan's
report to Congress on ``Management of the United States
Government.''
   The report noted that ``over half of U.S. households own one or
more credit cards,'' and that the administration planned to begin
making more use of them.
   ``For the government, credit cards make collections easier in an
electronic environment, reduce delinquencies, cut down on bad
checks, eliminate paperwork, and improve information received on
collections,'' the report said.
   The report said that agencies that would start accepting credit
cards by this April included:
   _ The Interstate Commerce Commission, for duties, fees and fines.
   _ The National Archives, for sales of documents and publications.
   _ The U.S. courts, for filing fees, fines, opinions, and
videotapes of proceedings.
   _ The Federal Trade Commission, for fines and fees.
   _ The Army Corps of Engineeers, for permits, fees and map sales.
   _ The Federal Emergency Management Agency, for sale of flood
maps.
   Wright said that OMB is also working with the IRS to develop
guidelines that might be used later on to enable taxpayers pay
their taxes with credit cards. However, he said to do so would
require legislation from Congress _ legislation the administration
is not currently seeking.
   The management report also said the government is studying, for
possible future use, a system under which ``smart cards'' would be
issued by the government to those who receive federal payments and
benefits, including Social Security recipients.
   ``These cards (would) have embedded on them information about
the cardholder that can be accessed electronically. Potentially
(the) cards could make available funds for food stamps, social
security payments, or grants and control their use electronically
through central computers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1802EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r n BC-SuperTuesdayTables Advisory   02-29 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Super Tuesday Tables, Advisory,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EDITORS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Democrats and Republicans in 20 states and American Samoa will
vote in statewide elections or participate in presidential caucuses
on March 8, Super Tuesday.
   We plan frequent transmission of at least 10 separate tables
summarizing the popular vote and delegate allocation both by state
and cumulatively for all participating states. In addition,
separate formats will summarize activity in five states conducting
precinct caucuses that night.
   
   All tables will be transmitted at least once an hour, and more
frequently as circumstances warrant.
   
   Our lineup includes the following:
   
   _ PRIMARY VOTE STATE-BY-STATE. Summary packages displaying the
latest popular vote, by state. Separate packages will cover
Democratic and Republican candidates. These tables are slugged
BC-PP-Dem-Pres-All and BC-PP-GOP-Pres-All.
   
   _ CAUCUS RESULTS STATE-BY-STATE. Identical in format to the
Primary Vote State-by-State tables, with separate transmissions for
Democratic and Republican caucuses. Since caucus rules may differ
from state to state, the numbers in each of the summaries may not
mean exactly the same thing. These tables are slugged
BC-PC-Dem-Pres-All and BC-PC-GOP-Pres-All.
   
   _ SUPER TUESDAY DELEGATES STATE-BY-STATE. Packages displaying
the latest delegate allocation by state, with separate packages for
the two parties. The formats are similar to the primary vote
formats. These tables are slugged BC-PP-Dem-Deleg-All and
BC-PP-GOP-Deleg-All.
   
   _ SUPER TUESDAY DELEGATE SUMMARY. Cumulative summary of
delegates allocated in all states holding elections and caucuses on
Super Tuesday, with a separate summary for each party. These
summaries are slugged BC-PP-Dem-Deleg-Sum and BC-PP-GOP-Deleg-Sum.
   
   _ SUPER TUESDAY VOTE. Cumulative summary of the vote in all
states holding primary elections on Super Tuesday, with a single
summary for both parties. These summaries are slugged
BC-PP-Pres-TotVot-Sum.
   
   _ NATIONAL DELEGATE TABLE. An update of the overall delegate
summary table that has been moving on national wires for several
weeks. It gives the breakdown of the presidential preferences of
all national convention delegates selected or allocated thus far,
plus trend information. A single table contains totals for both
parties. This table is slugged BC-US-Deleg-Sum.
   
   _ U.S. SENATE STATE-BY-STATE. Summary package displaying the
latest popular vote in U.S. Senate races in Maryland, Mississippi
and Texas, with a separate package for party. These tables are
slugged BC-Dem-Senate-State-by-State and
BC-GOP-Senate-State-by-State.
   
   Depending on election-night developments, we may transmit
single-state summaries on some presidential primaries.
   
   Samples of the first four formats listed above will follow this
advisory. Sluglines contain the word ``SAMPLE'' but otherwise are
as indicated above. For illustration only, the summaries and tables
include mock votes and percentages rather than zeroes.
   
   The samples contain the candidate names in order and total
precincts as they now exist for each state. That information may
change before election day.
   
   Please call Tom Jory at 212 621-1614 if you have questions.
   
   The AP
</TEXT>
</DOC>
