<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1538EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson'sVotes Bjt   02-29 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson's Votes, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Showing in Maine Seen as Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's strong second-place finish in
Maine, following respectable showings elsewhere, proves he is
attaining what he lacked throughout 1984 _ expansion beyond his
black base of support.
   In a state with a 1 percent black population, Jackson got 28
percent of the vote on Sunday after campaigning for only two days
in Maine. Winner Michael Dukakis, well known to Maine voters as
governor of nearby Massachusetts, garnered 42 percent.
   On Monday, addressing cheering students at Pembroke State
University in North Carolina, Jackson shouted, ``Talk about
mainstream; try the state of Maine.''
   Political consultant Ann Lewis, who has informally advised the
Jackson campaign, called Maine ``the most significant breakthrough
state for him so far.''
   In Iowa and New Hampshire he finished fourth out of seven
contenders, she noted, after devoting considerable time and
resources. In Minnesota he was second with 20 percent in last
week's caucuses, thanks to the state's liberal activists, she said.
   But in Maine, where Jackson's 28 percent contrasted to the 1
percent that he got when he ran in 1984, she said, ``The force of
his message produced votes for him in a state in which he has been
unable to make a major commitment of resources.''
   In Maine, Jackson did buy $10,000 worth of TV ads in the days
before the caucuses.
   Bob Beckel, a top political adviser to Walter Mondale's 1984
camapign, called Jackson ``one of the best hidden political stories
of the year.''
   ``I would say it's a sign of a growing movement among non-black
supporters of Jackson, and for people to try to ignore it, they're
making a great mistake,'' he said.
   ``People don't want to buy the notion that Jesse Jackson has got
a message that people listen to and that has begun to rise above
his blackness,'' he added. ``Somebody in this party has to to
recognize that this is a significant guy in the party.''
   Jackson carried two of Maine's largest cities, Portland and
Bangor, and won considerable support among the gay community and
students. In his bid to expand his base, he has targeted those
groups as well as poor people, blue-collar workers and farmers.
   He beat Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., handily in the mill town
of Jay. Both candidates went to Jay last fall to show solidarity
with workers of International Paper Co. who have been on strike
since last June. The company has hired replacements in the meantime.
   Gary McGrane, Jay Democratic chairman, commented that Jackson
``said a scab is a scab. He didn't call them replacement workers.
People understand plain talk.''
   Political analyst William Schneider said that while Jackson has
gotten white votes, there is evidence the votes come not so much
from the economically oppressed as from ``the radical chic.''
   ``It could be the Village Voice crowd instead of the
downtrodden,'' he said, citing exit polls from Iowa and New
Hampshire that showed a good portion of Jackson's white supporters
were upscale well-educated liberals.
   But he and other analysts also said that besides being better
known nationwide than the other candidates _ excepting former
Colorado Sen. Gary Hart _ Jackson has a clear, strong message that
does not change from state to state.
   ``There is no other candidate in the race who really stands for
the old politics ... what I would call Democratic fundamentalism,''
as espoused by the late Sen. Hubert Humphrey, Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., and New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, said Schneider.
   Beckel added, ``I think people consistently underestimate him.
They forget one important thing in politics. That is that message
matters. He has got a message ... and it appeals to a lot of
people.''
   Rick Barton, Democratic state chairman, who had predicted
Jackson would do as well in Maine as he had a week earlier in
Minnesota's caucuses, contended that timing was a key to Jackson's
success.
   Jackson's successful appearance at the University of Maine in
Orono on Feb. 11, just after Iowa's caucuses and just before the
New Hampshire primary, was ``just the right time ... when Maine
Democrats were starting to lock in,'' he said.
   Barton said the scaling back of the Paul Simon and Hart
campaigns also helped Jackson. He suggested that defections from
those candidates inflated Jackson's support by 5 percentage points.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
