<DOCNO> AP880229-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1919EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChaseMistake     02-29 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chase Mistake,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Agents Overturn Plane, Grab Pilot By Mistake</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unsuspecting pilot wound up with his face in the
dirt, M-16s pointed at his head and his ruined plane upside down on
the runway after drug agents mistook him for a cocaine smuggler.
   Gustavo Viera, a Miami accountant, has received an apology from
Vice President George Bush's anti-drug task force, the Drug
Enforcement Admimistration and the U.S. Customs Service.
   However, he said Monday he had received no compensation and
plans to file a claim against the government.
   Viera said he did not see or hear the Customs Service helicopter
that followed him to the airport, and worries what would happen if
the service's controversial proposal to shoot down suspected
traffickers is adopted.
   ``Had that been in effect, I wouldn't be here talking to you
today,'' said Viera. ``When you're in one of these airplanes and
the engine is loud and they shoot a warning, you're not going to
hear it.''
   The incident occurred July 9 when Viera flew his Piper Cherokee
_ bought only three weeks before _ over Biscayne Bay. He then
headed for a small airport south of Miami.
   A subsequent letter from William Rosenblatt, an assistant
commissioner in the Customs Service enforcement office, explained
what happened next.
   Rosenblatt said Customs Service radar had lost a suspected
trafficker in flight, then picked up Viera's plane.
   ``It was incorrectly assumed that your aircraft was in fact the
suspect,'' Rosenblatt wrote.
   According to friends of Viera who witnessed the incident, a
Customs Service Blackhawk helicopter followed Viera's plane as it
touched down at the Kendall Glider Port, but stayed behind him.
Viera said it was impossible to see or hear the helicopter in that
position.
   ``When (Viera) was turning left to get out of the runway,
presumably the pilot of the helicopter thought Gus was trying to
run away,'' said Rene Betancourt. ``He made a maneuver with a blast
of the prop, and turned Gus's plane upside down.''
   Viera first thought his nose gear had collapsed, then he
realized the danger he was in.
   ``I'm upside down on my runway, fuel was pouring out and the
thing was about to blow,'' said Viera. Then he saw the helicopter
land beside him and several men rush toward his plane.
   ``I thought they were going to rescue me,'' he said. Instead, as
he pleaded with them to pull him out of the plane, someone smashed
in his window and hit him in the back of the head, he said.
   The next thing he knew he was lying face down with a foot on his
back. Two Bahamian agents who accompanied the Customs team were
pointing their M-16s at his head, said Viera.
   ``They never identified themselves as Customs agents, they never
read me my rights and they illegally searched my plane,'' said
Viera.
   He was held for about 45 minutes until computer checks
established the error.
   The Viera wrote to Customs and the DEA, but only began to
receive apologies when he finally wrote Bush's task force.
   A letter from Howard Gehring, director of the task force's
national narcotics border-interdiction system, said ``any
inconvenience that this incident has caused is unfortunate.''
   Rosenblatt also apologized in a letter.
   ``As a resident of Dade County, Fla., you are in a position to
view firsthand the drug-related violence that occurs almost on a
daily basis,'' said Rosenblatt, adding that the danger results in
actions which ``might seem excessive.''
   Viera said the company which insured his plane paid off quickly
and he has bought a new plane.
   Roger Garland, chief of the Customs air branch at Homestead,
said as far as he knew, the Viera incident was the first of its
kind.
   ``Normally, we wouldn't even do that to a bad guy,'' said
Garland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1601EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole 1stLd-Writethru a0635 02-29 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0635,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Says Administration Sending Mixed Signals On Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with top 8 grafs new, picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``Dole,
the''</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede ATLANTA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Bob Dole
said Monday that the Reagan administration was sending mixed
signals about Panama's strong man Manuel Antonio Noriega, and he
suggested the United States ``may want to go back and take another
look'' at treaties turning over the Panama Canal to Panama.
   ``Say no to drugs. Say no to Noriega, and no, maybe, to giving
them the canal,'' Dole said at a news conference.
   Dole, the Senate's GOP leader, said that when he voted against
the Panama Canal treaties 10 years ago in the Senate ``we knew
about'' drug trafficking by members of the Panamanian military.
   He said that while the Reagan administration has accused Noriega
of dealing in drugs it has also been sending a different signal to
the Panamanian leader. ``It seems to me we have one signal saying
Noriega ought to stay, Noriega isn't such a bad guy,'' Dole said.
   Referring to the Panama Canal treaties, Dole said, ``We may want
to go back and take another look at that.''
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., appeared with Dole at a news
conference and offered his endorsement. ``The reason can be
described in two words _ effective leadership,'' Cochran said.
   Earlier, in Atlanta, Dole jabbed at George Bush and the other
Republican presidential contenders, declaring himself the tough
candidate for president and calling toughness ``a quality that some
may be lacking.''
   Trying to beat Bush in the big Southern presidential primaries,
which are one week away, Dole went before the predominantly
Democratic Georgia state House and Senate for separate addresses.
   Dole, the Republican leader in the U.S. Senate, proclaimed an
affinity with the Georgia Democrats through his rural Kansas
background, his start in rural politics and his legislative career.
By comparison, that underscored the point he has often made that
the vice president has had a more privileged background _ though he
didn't mention Bush by name.
   ``I got here just like you did. I got here the old fashioned way
_ I earned it,'' Dole said. ``Nobody gave it to me.''
   It was unmistakable who his target was as he stressed his
ability to work with Congress and said candidates shouldn't be
judged on ``who has the longest resume and most impressive
resume.'' Bush often notes the high-level government posts he has
held.
   ``There's one candidate and only one candidate with experience
in dealing with Congress and making tough decisions,'' Dole told
the Georgia Senate.
   ``I believe that I have a certain quality that some may be
lacking,'' he told the House. ``I am tough. I understand you have
to be tough to make tough choices.
   ``You have to be tough to deal with the legislature or to deal
with Congress or to deal with (Mikhail) Gorbachev or to deal with
(Daniel) Ortega,'' he said, referring to the Soviet and Nicaraguan
leaders.
   Dole strongly criticized Noriega, saying the United States
should impose a ``full-scale embargo'' on Panama if Noriega doesn't
give up power in 30 days. He said the United States should use
``whatever force is necessary'' to protect the Panama Canal and
other U.S. interests there.
   ``We don't need Noriega peddling drugs to our children,'' Dole
said. ``He's a bad influence and he has been a bad influence for 10
years.''
   Dole was making a series of campaign stops across the Southeast
on Monday as he campaigned toward the Southern primaries on Super
Tuesday, March 8. From Atlanta he flew to Jackson, and was going on
to Florida and to North Carolina.
   More than one-third of the GOP nominating delegates are at stake
in the contests on Tuesday, including races in most of the South.
   Bush leads Dole in most of the Super Tuesday states, according
to most polls. Dole aides said they were planning to begin airing
new television ads contrasting Dole and Bush's records in selected
Southern states.
   Dole repeated his call for a one-year budget freeze to reduce
the federal deficit, a proposal that he and Bush tangled over in
the Republicans' debate on Sunday. Dole said ``there is a
bipartisan majority for that kind of action.''
   He was accompanied to the Georgia Legislature by his wife
Elizabeth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1932EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     02-29 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Pilot Takes Stand in 14th Week of Lehder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Navy pilot testified Monday
that he made six cocaine flights for reputed Colombian drug lord
Carlos Lehder Rivas in 1979.
   Lehder, 38, reputed to be one of the leaders of Colombia's
violent Medellin Cartel, is on trial on charges he and others
conspired to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine into the United States
from Colombia via Norman's Cay in the Bahamas from 1978 to 1980.
   Leverett Francis, whose testimony opened the 14th week of the
trial, is described in the indictment against Lehder and
co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed as working with Ed Ward in flying
cocaine for Lehder.
   Francis, 66, said he began working for Ward, an admitted
marijuana smuggler, and then switched to flying cocaine, making
three trips from Norman's Cay in the Bahamas to Colombia and three
flights from the island to Astor Park, Fla.
   As a marijuana smuggler, Francis said, he was paid $30,000 a
flight. On his cocaine runs from Colombia to Norman's Cay, he
received $100,000 a flight, then $30,000 more to fly cocaine into
the United States, he said.
   U.S. Attorney Robert W. Merkle questioned Francis about his
contacts with defense attorneys and asked if he had wanted to
testify against Lehder.
   ``Nobody does. It's distasteful,'' said Francis.
   Merkle asked Francis if he had concealed illegal drug earnings
from the government because he wanted to avoid paying taxes. The
witness replied he had.
   ``Did you say that if you didn't get a promise, you would take
contempt instead of testifying?'' asked Merkle.
   Francis replied that his cooperation in the Ed Ward case had
earned the government a lot of money and he felt that had
discharged his obligation.
   When asked why he became a smuggler, Francis replied, ``I was
kind of wondering the same thing. It was the thrill of doing
something, in addition to the money.''
   Francis was shown a photograph of a stack of money and replied
that it was $88,000 given to him by Ward.
   He had allowed federal agents to take a picture in 1980.
   ``I understood that Mr. Lehder was the gentleman for whom Mr.
Ward was flying,'' he said.
   When asked to identify Lehder in court, Francis said he had
developed vision problems over the past few months. He was allowed
to leave the witness stand to get closer to the defendant.
   He walked up to attorney Stephen Weinbaum, who represents Reed,
and said, ``Is that you, Joe?'' Joe is Lehder's nickname.
   He also said he couldn't recognize Reed.
   Reed, 57, is charged only with being part of the alleged
conspiracy.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
