<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InsuranceBattle     02-29 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insurance Battle,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Will Have Bone Marrow Transplant, Despite Insurance Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dying boy who needs a bone marrow transplant
will go to Seattle for the treatment next week, even though a court
battle still is being waged over his father's health insurance
coverage, officials said Monday.
   Jim Lacina sued Nationwide Life Insurance Co. of Columbus,
contending the company mistakenly canceled his health insurance
policy without notifying him.
   Attorneys had rushed to bring the lawsuit to trial Monday
because doctors said Lacina's 11-year-old son, Jamie, needed a bone
marrow transplant by March 15 to survive more than a few months.
The boy has leukemia.
   But the trial was postponed until June 27, Visiting Cuyahoga
County Common Pleas Judge George G. McMonagle said, adding that
Lacina, of Geneva, had found a way to pay for the treatment at the
Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in Seattle.
   ``I understand Medicaid is taking care of the arrangements,''
the judge said.
   Officials of the Cuyahoga County Department of Health and Human
Services declined comment, saying Medicaid applications are
confidential.
   There was no answer at Lacina's home Monday in Geneva, and
Lacina's attorney, Gerald Jeppe, didn't return phone calls. But
Jeppe said last week that his client was applying for Medicaid.
   Edward E. Duncan, attorney for Nationwide Life, also declined to
comment.
   Lacina was an agent for Nationwide Life until five years ago,
when his job was terminated because of company cutbacks. Because of
his son's health, he paid to continue his health insurance after he
left the firm, attorneys for both sides agree.
   However, the policy lapsed in late 1983. Lacina said he never
got a copy of his policy, a notice that his premium was due or a
termination notice, Jeppe said in court last week.
   Lacina sued Nationwide Life on April 24, 1986. While the case
has been pending, his son has received chemotherapy treatments at
Rainbow Babies' and Children's Hospital in Cleveland. Court
documents show Lacina, who is unemployed, owes the hospital more
than $24,000.
   The lawsuit became more urgent when doctors advised Lacina to
take his son to the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center by March
15 for a bone marrow transplant. The center requires patients to
have $100,000 or proof of insurance coverage before it will treat
them.
   Susan Edmonds, Hutchinson spokeswoman, said Jamie Lacina is
scheduled to arrive at the center on March 7. She said she hasn't
received word from the boy's father that he has made arrangements
to pay for the procedure.
</TEXT>
