<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Senegal     02-29 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senegal,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Violence Paralyzes Capital After President Grabs Lead in Voting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY JAMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Abdou Diouf declared a state of
emergency Monday and truncheon-wielding police battled rioting
gangs of young people after news reports said Diouf was winning
re-election easily.
   Opposition leaders denounced the early returns of Sunday's
voting, which had Diouf getting 77 percent of the vote, as violence
spread throughout the city.
   Police arrested the presidential candidate of the major
opposition party, Abdoulaye Wade of the Senegalese Democrafamily said Monday
night. The wife of Ousmane Ngom, a
party press secretary, satic
Party, his id 20 men had come to her home, searched
it and arrested her husband.
   Diouf declared a state of emergency in the area around the
capital ``in response to grave troubles this morning,'' according
to a broadcast on national radio, which said all public meetings
were now banned.
   A 2{-mile stretch of Boulevard General De Gaulle, one of the
city's main thoroughfares, was littered with fire-gutted vehicles,
spent tear gas canisters and shattered glass.
   Young rioters burned a stack of tires at one traffic circle,
windows were smashed in many houses and large granite stones that
had been pulled from a monument lay in the street after they had
been thrown at police.
   Merchants in the downtown Plateau districtains to senior citizens seated
at long tables.
   At the school, Robertson was met by students shouting ``Go Pat
Go!'' Some students held signs passed out by campaign staffers.
   When a student asked if Robertson would ever renew diplomatic
relations with Cuba, he replied: ``I don't think we should have
diplomatic relations with a butcher and a tyrant!''
   Robertson began his Florida tour in Jacksonville Monday and
arranged a rally in Miami Monday night, followed by breakfast
Tuesday in Fort Lauderdale and stops in Hollywood, Fort Myers,
Sarasota, Gainesville and Orlando.
   In Jacksonville, Robertson told about 500 supporters that
``along with Texas, Florida is one of the two most pivotal states.''
   He added:
   ``We've got one week to the most crucial election, I believe, in
the history of America, certainly this century and maybe since its
beginning.
   ``We're at a crossroads in America. We're either going to return
to the ways that made this nation great, or we're going to go down
the road.''
   Robertson mentioned a gun problem experienced this year in
several Florida schools.
   ``How can a child study when he's living in mortal fear of
somebody shooting him with a handgun in the halls of the school? We
owe our children an education in a crime-free, drug-free school
environment,'' said Robertson.
   ``If we want to see this country strong. There's only one way in
my estimation to do it. We will restore the greatness of America
through moral strength,'' he added.
   Robertson also said that ``we've got to go back to a time in our
educational system when once again we teach our kids moral values.
We've got to bring God back into the public schools of America.''
   On trade, he said: ``There isn't one country that is treating us
fairly. ... As president of the United States, I'm not going to
shut down American factories and put Americans out of jobs to
improve the standard of living in communist China and communist
Russia.''
   At a news conference following his address, Robertson called
Panama military strong man Manuel Antonio Noriega ``a bandit,'' but
added that ``I don't see us sending troops (to Panama). I don't
think it is necessary.''
   On South Africa, Robertson said, ``I am totally opposed to
apartheid ... but the thing I'm concerned about is turning South
Africa into a bloody battleground.''
   ``I don't want to see a Marxist state in South Africa,''
Robertson said.
</TEXT>
