<HEAD>Billboard Breaks Down, But Marriage Proposals Still Stand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flashing billboard broke down but at least two
wedding offers still stood Monday, a day that leap-year lore
supposedly gives women the right to propose marriage.
   Four women were scheduled to have their marriage proposals
flashed on an electronic board in London, but British Telecom's
giant ``message master'' suffered an electrical glitch, said
spokesman Peter Chandler.
   The couples, who stood on a street corner waiting for the
proposals, were whisked to a nearby hotel for a consolation lunch.
   Two couples walked away without announcing their intentions, but
the other two said they would tie the knot.
   Donna Walker, 20, turned to her boyfriend, Mark Beva, 22, and
said ``Everything's gone wrong, but anyway will you marry me?''
   A stunned Beva blurted yes.
