<HEAD>Woman 100 in Real Life, Only 25 by Leap Year Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edna Brown turned 25 on Monday,
according to Leap Year standards, but lots of relatives gathered to
help her celebrate her 100 years on the planet.
   But Mrs. Brown can't claim the distinction of being the only
person in her family born on Feb. 29, which comes around only once
every four years.
   Her great-great grandson, David Jacobs, 20, is celebrating the
date of his birth for only the fifth time. And her nephew, Rex
Napier of Visalia, was having his 19th Leap Year birthday, although
he's really 76.
   Eula Jones, one of Mrs. Brown's 10 children, said her mother has
been resting up for her party. She just had a cast removed from an
arm that was broken around Christmas.
   ``Mother's real spunky, real sharp,'' Mrs. Jones said. ``We're
going to take her down and get her hair done and get her ready.''
