<HEAD>Six Fires In 11 Years Force Sisters From Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGFIELD, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sisters' homes burned within a day
of each other, bringing to six the number of residences they have
lost to fire.
   Pat Rader and her family have lost four trailers, the most
recent on Wednesday.
   ``The first three burned on the same spot,'' she said. ``The one
that burned (Wednesday) was on the same property, but not on the
same place. ``I don't know if I'll ever live in another trailer,
but I won't go back there.''
   On Thursday, fire hit a frame home owned by her sister, Wanda
Pratt, and her family. Mrs. Pratt said the house may be salvageable.
   The house stands near the spot where the Pratts lost a mobile
home to fire about three years ago.
   ``My uncle was living with us then,'' Mrs. Pratt said. ``He was
85. The fire started in his room, but we never knew what started
it.''
   Mrs. Rader, her husband and three children are staying with her
parents in Kingfield for now.
   ``I'm going to try to get me a house,'' she said. ``My
stepfather and my mother own the property my trailers have been on.
They're giving us a couple of acres, and we're going to try to
build on it.''
   Capt. Keith Crowell of the Williamson County Rescue Squad said
Monday authorities don't know what caused either fire.
