<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CopFuneral     02-29 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cop Funeral,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10,000 Cops Say Goodbye To One Of Their Own</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEAFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The streets were awash with dress blues and
angry tears Monday as 10,000 police officers attended last rites
for Edward Byrne, a 22-year-old policeman killed while protecting a
witness in a drug case.
   It was the largest police turnout for a fallen colleague in the
history of the New York City police, authorities said. They came
from Texas and Ohio, Maryland and Rhode Island, and they lined the
eight blocks approaching St. James Church.
   ``Eddie's murderers need to be pitied and also prayed for,'' the
Rev. Thomas DeVita said in his homily during Mass. ``They do not
know about the sanctity of life. They cannot really know or
understand what they have done, even though this is such a terrible
sin.''
   Byrne was slain early Friday as he guarded a witness who had
complained to police about crack dealers working in the South
Jamaica section of the borough of Queens. There have been no
arrests. Byrne, eight months on the force, was struck by three
shotgun blasts.
   Eight officers carried the coffin, draped in the green-and-white
flag of the department, into the church as a police bagpiper played
``When the Battle is Over.'' The family followed; his father, a
former city police lieutenant, carried a color photograph of his
son.
   ``Today we commit Eddie back to our God and Father, to God who
gave us Ed 22 years ago. ... If only it could have been longer,''
the priest said.
   He remembered Byrne as a smiling storyteller, an enthusiastic
friend, relative and police officer. Byrne turned 22 nine days ago.
   ``Maybe Eddie has done more in eight short months than other
people will do in a lifetime,'' DeVita said. ``He sacrificed his
life trying to protect the lives of others.''
   Six police helicopters followed overhead as the body was taken
to St. Charles Cemetery for interment.
   After the Mass, the Rev. Charles Norris of Bethesda Missionary
Baptism Church, located in the 103rd Precinct where Byrne served,
climbed to the altar to speak in support of police who are fighting
drugs _ ``this venom.''
   Mayor Edward I. Koch also spoke from the altar after the
service. He said he felt the same sadness he felt upon the deaths
of Franklin D. Roosevelt, John F. Kennedy and Martin Luther King Jr.
   ``In a strange way, Edward Byrne's death has the same
importance,'' Koch said. ``If drug trafficking has become so bold
that they can engage in the assassination of a police officer, then
our whole society is at risk. ... That is why his death is so
important.''
</TEXT>
