<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1958EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-USDA-Blacks     02-29 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USDA-Blacks,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Makes Progress on Jobs, Services for Blacks, But Still Has
Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As a general rule, the Agriculture Department
is making progress but still lags in expanding jobs and services to
black Americans, a special review panel said Monday.
   In 1986, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng directed all
agencies in the department to carry out new guidelines to improve
USDA compliance with civil rights and equal opportunity standards.
   As part of the department's February observance of Black History
Month, five study groups looked at how USDA has performed since
then.
   ``Black employees continue a modest but upward movement in all
occupational categories,'' the report said. ``Some increases have
been realized both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of total
USDA employment. This is especially important because the increases
have occurred at a time when overall employment in USDA was
declining.''
   The USDA employs the equivalent of approximately 102,000 full
time employees, according to recent budget documents. The task
force report said blacks comprise 8.4 percent of the department's
employees, up from 8.1 percent in 1986. But that ``is low compared
with other federal agencies,'' it added.
   ``To continue to improve its equal opportunity posture, USDA
must realize larger increases in the number of blacks hired,
promoted and trained,'' the report said. ``And such increases mus
be realized at a faster pace. Additionally the department must
place emphasis on retention strategies once black employees are
recruited at hired.''
   The task force report said there are ``encouraging signs'' that
USDA agencies are beginning to address the complex problems of
black farmers and their declining numbers.
   ``Coordinated efforts between the Soil Conservation Service,
Farmers Home Administration and Extension Service are just
beginning to show limited success at eliminating the historical
factors militating against small and economically disadvantaged
farmers,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
