<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua     02-29 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista-Contra Talks At An Impasse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mediator of peace talks between
the government and the Contra rebels said the Sandinistas'
insistence on a limited agenda for the discussions is a step
backward.
   Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, the mediator, broke off the last
round of meetings in Guatemala on Feb. 19, saying the two sides
remained far apart on ways to end the 7-year-old war.
   Since then, the Roman Catholic prelate has charged the leftist
Sandinista government with failing to compromise and President
Daniel Ortega has criticized the ``abrupt'' end to the second set
of direct talks.
   Ortega, in a speech Sunday, reiterated that the discussions
should be limited to how to arrange a truce. The U.S.-backed
Contras and Obando y Bravo are seeking to discuss political reforms
as well as a cease-fire.
   Earlier Sunday, the cardinal said the government's position
represented ``a step backward'' for his plan. The cardinal declined
to say whether further talks would be held, saying, ``We'll have to
reflect on that.''
   Agreement on details of a cease-fire could deter Congress from
voting for non-lethal aid for the rebels.
   The Democrat-controlled House on Feb. 3 narrowly voted down
President Reagan's proposal for $36.2 million in funding, including
$3.6 million in military financing.
   In the recent talks, Obando y Bravo expanded his role by
offering his own peace plan. In addition to cease-fire proposals,
it calls for complete press freedom, renewed talks with internal
opposition parties, a revision of the military draft law and a
total amnesty, reforms long sought by the Contras.
   The Sandinistas agreed to discuss the sections of the cardinal's
proposal that had to do with a cease-fire, but they have refused to
enter into what they call a ``political dialogue'' with the rebels.
   In a peace plan signed Aug. 7, the presidents of Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Guatemala, Costa Rica and Honduras committed themselves
to implementing cease-fires, amnesties and greater democracy and
called for an end to outside aid to insurgencies.
   Nicaragua has permitted the reopening of some newspapers and
radio stations it had closed. The government maintains that a full
amnesty will be granted when there is a cease-fire.
   Talks with the internal political opposition parties _ also
mandated by the peace plan _ broke down in December when the
government refused to discuss a new constitution.
   The Sandinistas accuse the cardinal, often harshly critical of
the government, of siding with the Contras.
   The cardinal called on those attending his Sunday Mass to pray
for peace. He estimates that 15 Nicaraguans die each day because of
the war.
   Nicaragua's internal problems have been increasing. Opposition
parties, taking advantage of new freedoms since the state of
emergency was lifted in January, have staged several demonstrations
against the Sandinistas.
   The Sandinistas have held their own marches to show their
strength and at times have quelled opposition demonstrations.
   The Sandinistas came to power in a 1979 revolution that ousted
pro-American dictator Anastasio Somoza.
</TEXT>
