<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Scattered Over West, Snow Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered over parts of the West on Monday, with some
snow around the Great Lakes, and record high temperatures were
reported on the northern Plains.
   Rain was scattered over west-central California and western
Washington state during the morning. Rain and thundershowers also
extended over northwestern Utah.
   Santa Maria, Calif., got 1.01 inches of rain in the six hours up
to 1 p.m. EST.
   Snow fell along Lake Superior, over northwestern Lower Michigan
and across much of northern New York state, but no measurable
snowfall was reported in that same six-hour period.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered over east-central Texas.
   On the northern Plains, Aberdeen, S.D., reached a record 45
degrees under a sunny sky, and Bismarck, N.D., posted a record 46
degrees.
   Advisories for strong, gusty wind were posted over the mountains
of central California, where gusts to 40 mph were measured at
Sandberg.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 11
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 86 at Alice, Laredo and
McAllen, Texas. The low for the day was 9 degrees below zero at
Houlton, Maine.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers were forecast from southern Idaho
across Arizona and western Colorado.
   Highs in the teens and 20s were predicted over the Great Lakes
and northern New England; in the 30s and 40s from central New
England across the Virginias, the Ohio Valley, from southern
Minnesota across northern Iowa, over the northern Plains and the
upper Missouri Basin, and from southern Colorado into central
Arizona; in the 70s over much of Florida and the desert Southwest,
and the southern Plains; near 80 across southern Texas; and in the
50s and 60s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
