<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Mecham-Charges     02-29 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham-Charges,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Specifics Spelled Out in Governor's Impeachment</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Mecham Impeachment, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham faces charges detailed in
23 counts in his impeachment trial before the Arizona Senate.
   The Articles of Impeachment brought against him by the House are
the equivalent of an indictment in criminal court. The specifics
center on three alleged violations of law _ misuse of $80,000 in
state funds, concealment of a campaign loan and obstruction of
justice in trying to thwart investigation of an alleged death
threat.
   Briefly, these are the accusations:
   _ Misuse of state funds.
   In May 1987, a governor's protocol fund was created from funds
raised by the governor's inaugural ball. The funds had been
earmarked to pay off Mecham's campaign debts, but a state law
limiting campaign contributions precluded that use. Two months
after the protocol fund was established to promote interests of the
state, $80,000 from it was loaned to Mecham's automobile agency.
The loan has been repaid, but prosecutors contend Mecham, with his
son, Dennis, tried to conceal an illegal loan of state funds.
   Mecham says the protocol fund was private, not state money, and
that he broke no law by loaning it to his dealership.
   _ Concealment of a $350,000 campaign loan.
   In October 1986, Tempe developer Barry Wolfson loaned $350,000
to the Mecham for Governor campaign. The loan, which has been
repaid, was not reported properly on required disclosure statements.
   Mecham says he didn't try to conceal the loan but contends his
brother, Willard, who was his campaign treasurer, tried to save
time by lumping it in with other funds on the financial statements
without including Wolfson's name.
   _ Obstruction of justice by thwarting investigation of a death
threat.
   On Nov. 12, 1987, Lee Watkins, an assistant director of the
Department of Administation, allegedly threatened to harm Donna
Carlson, the governor's former legislative liaison who then was
expected to testify in a grand jury investigation of Mecham's
reporting of the $350,000 campaign loan.
   Watkins is alleged to have said if Ms. Carlson did not keep her
mouth shut, she would ``take a long boat ride'' from which she
wouldn't return. Ralph Milstead, director of the Department of
Public Safety, says Mecham ordered him not to cooperate with the
Arizona attorney general's office in its investigation of the death
threat allegation.
   Mecham says he had already checked out the alleged death threat
and considered it ``a lot of hot air.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1929EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PoliticalBriefs     02-29 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Says Hart Fails To Qualify For New York Primary Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Board of Elections ruled Monday
that former Sen. Gary Hart, D-Colo., failed to qualify for the
state's April 19 Democratic presidential primary ballot.
   Petitions meant to put Hart on the ballot contained only 6,864
signatures, more than 3,000 under the required number, said board
spokesman Steven LaFever.
   To get on the ballot, Democratic candidates must file petitions
bearing signatures of at least 10,000 registered Democrats and at
least 100 of those must come from each of 17 of the state's 34
congressional districts.
   ``He has 14 days to go into court with an appeal,'' LaFever
said. ``But it's really difficult (to win in court) if you don't
even have the 10,000'' signatures, he added.
   Among other Democratic candidates, Jesse Jackson has collected
more than 64,000 signatures, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis got
42,615, Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri collected 22,477, Sen.
Paul Simon of Illinois had 22,076, and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of
Tennessee had 21,759.
   A group of Democratic county clerks filed petitions containing
more than 18,000 signatures to get a spot on the ballot for
``uncommitted.'' Most of those clerks want New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo to run.
   While Cuomo has said he is not a presidential candidate, he has
refused to rul out accepting a draft for the nomination if there is
a deadlocked national convention when the Democrats meet in Atlanta
in July.
   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche filed petitions containing
23,061 signatures. Those petitions may be challenged by mainstream
Democrats.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Attorney Says Georgia Law Violates Free-Speech Guarantee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia's law banning exit polls within 250 feet
of voting places violates the Constitution's free-speech guarantee,
an attorney representing three major television networks argued in
court Monday.
   The 1985 law does not define exit poll and therefore ``allows
certain types of speech but not others,'' said Floyd Abrams.
   Reporters ``can ask questions and take notes as long as they
don't do it in a systematic way,'' Abrams told U.S. District Judge
Robert Hall in a hearing on a lawsuit filed by ABC, NBC and CBS
against Georgia and Fulton County election officials.
   But Patrick McKee, an assistant attorney general representing
state elections officials, said poll workers have interpreted the
law as disallowing anyone from questioning voters about their vote
within 250 feet of the polling place.
   Former state Rep. Claude Bray, D-Manchester, who headed the
House State Governmental Affairs Committee when it considered the
exit poll bill, said election officials mostly in metropolitan
Atlanta complained that voters were being intimidated by exit poll
takers.
   ``This was a bill to help the voters keep their privacy so they
could vote and leave without being harassed,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Gephardt Endorsement Day Proclaimed In Missouri By Campaign</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Supporters
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
