<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0660 02-29 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Unleashes Stunning Missile Attacks On Tehran</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Iran reporting two more missiles
fired at Tehran, acknowleding late-night explosions.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq said it retaliated for pre-dawn
missile attacks on Baghdad by firing long-range rockets into the
heart of Tehran Monday. Iran reported 16 people killed in the
bombing of a hospital.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said its
gunners fired five surface-to-surface missiles into Tehran after
two similar projectiles had exploded in Baghdad, killing and
wounding ``many civilians.''
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency IRNA, also monitored in
Nicosia, said in urgent dispatches that ``two loud explosions''
were heard after nightfall in Tehran and ``there may have been
casualties and damage.''
   It said the blasts, 10 minutes apart, were ``from fresh Iraqi
attacks'' but gave no other details.
   Earlier, IRNA said Tehran was bombed twice in Iraqi air raids
but made no mention of missile attacks on the city.
   It said in one of the raids, 16 people were killed and ``dozens
wounded, including newborn babies,'' at a Tehran hospital.
   IRNA did not identify the hospital but said several people were
buried under the debris. Tehran Radio urged Iranians to take refuge
in bomb shelters.
   The later communique carried by IRNA indicated there was
confusion over the Iraqi attacks, possibly because Iraq had not
previously used surface-to-surface missiles against Tehran in the
war that began in September 1980. Instead it had relied on its
warplanes to strike deep inside Iranian territory.
   ``The Iraqi rockets will reduce the Iranian capital to rubble,''
the Iraqi News Agency said, quoting an unidentified military
spokesman. ``The Iraqi rockets will fall on Tehran all night until
the city is demolished on the heads of its rulers.''
   It said three missiles were fired at 5:45 p.m., 5:55 p.m. and
6:08 p.m., followed by two more at 11:10 p.m. and 11:20 p.m.
   Iraq was not known to have any surface-to-surface missiles
capable of reaching the Iranian capital about 200 miles east of the
Iraqi border.
   The Iraqi News Agency quoted a military spokesman as saying the
missiles fired Monday ``had been designed by Iraqi minds and put
together by Iraqi hands as a gift to the leader of Iraq (President
Saddam Hussein) and the people of Iraq.''
   Iraq's attacks began about 12 hours after Iranian missiles hit
Baghdad.
   IRNA quoted a Revolutionary Guards communique as saying the
Iranian missiles were aimed at the headquarters of Iraq's state-run
television and radio network and two military targets in Baghdad.
   State-run Baghdad radio said two missiles exploded in the city
of 5 million people. It reported a military communique said: ``Many
Iraqis were killed, among them women, children and old people. Many
more were wounded and many houses were destroyed.'' No casualty
figures were given.
   The Iraqi News Agency also reported that Iranian artillery
shelled residential areas in the southern port of Basra, the border
town of Khanaqin and Sirwan in northeast Iraq throughout the night.
It made no mention of casualties.
   It was the third day of attacks on population and industrial
centers. The attacks began Saturday when Iraqi warplanes bombed
Tehran for the first time since January 1987.
   On Sunday, Iran said its forces fired three surface-to-surface
missiles in 40 minutes in retaliation for the Iraqi air raids on
``non-military areas.'' It said 28 civilians were killed and scores
were wounded in the Iraqi raids.
   The exchange of attacks and reported use by Iraq of long-range
missiles heightened fears that the Persian Gulf foes are locked in
a fresh round of the ``war of the cities.''
   Iran has fired 37 missiles into Baghdad since that phase of the
war began in March 1985, but had not targeted Baghdad since Nov. 8.
   Meanwhile, President Ali Khamenei of Iran warned the U.N.
Security Council not to approve any resolution imposing an arms
embargo on Iran for failing to agree to cease-fire calls.
   IRNA quoted Khamenei as saying such a move would mean ``the end
of all political solutions to the war, imposed by Iraq.''
   The United States and its allies have been lobbying for an arms
embargo against Iran because of its refusal to agree to Security
Council Resolution 598 adopted in July. Iraq has said it would
agree to the resolution, which calls for a cease-fire, if Iran did.
   Khamenei said again that Iran would not accept any settlement
until Iraq has been condmned as the aggressor and punished by the
international community, according to IRNA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
