<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Bokassa     02-29 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bokassa,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Emperor's Death Sentence Commuted To Life in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGUI, Central African Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean-Bedel Bokassa, a
village chief's son who made himself president for life and then
emperor, was spared the death penalty Monday for murders committed
during his 14-year reign.
   President Andre Kolingba commuted Bokassa's sentence in an order
announced on the national radio.
   Bokassa was convicted June 12, 1987, of ordering the murders of
at least 20 political opponents. He also was convicted of diverting
huge sums from the state treasury.
   The former leader, who had changed the name of his country to
the Central African Empire and proclaimed himself Bokassa I,
unsuccessfully appealed the verdict to the Supreme Court.
   ``During the course of this trial I discovered crimes of which I
know nothing,'' he said. ``I assume the moral responsibility. I
affirm my innocence of the facts against me. I was motivated only
by the desire to serve my country. Today, I only want to live in
peace as a simple citizen.''
   Western governments and some African leaders had asked Gen.
Kolingba to spare Bokassa. Kolingba previously commuted other death
sentences imposed in this former French colony, and is said to
oppose capital punishment.
   Bokassa went into exile after he was overthrown in September
1979 in a French-backed coup after the deaths in custody of 100
schoolchildren who protested a government order to wear expensive
uniforms produced at a factory run by the emperor's wife. Bokassa
was alleged to have personally beaten 17 of them to death.
   A court in this nation of 3 million people, which he had ruled
since 1966, convicted him in absentia and sentenced him to death in
1980.
   In late 1986, he returned from France unexpectedly ``to be
judged'' by his countrymen. He was tried for offenses ranging from
corruption to murder and cannibalism.
   During the six-month trial, prosecutor Gabriel Mbodou said:
``There were no extenuating circumstances whatever in the odious
acts committed by the accused, his atrocities and his greed which
plunged the entire country into a nightmare throughout the 14 years
of his bloody reign.''
   The French legal system used in the Central African Republic
obliged the government to try Bokassa again.
   Officials and Western diplomats said privately last year that
Kolingba probably would commute a death sentence for fear execution
would stir unrest among Bokassa's minority M'baka tribe in the
southwest corner of the landlocked nation.
   Bokassa, 67, was educated in Roman Catholic mission schools. He
joined the French army, won a dozen combat medals in Indochina and
achieved the rank of captain.
   When the country became independent in 1960, President David
Dacko asked Bokassa to form an army. He led a coup against Dacko in
December 1965.
   After Bokassa proclaimed himself emperor, he was crowned in a
1977 ceremony that cost more than $200 million, one-quarter of the
nation's annual revenue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-SouthKorea     02-29 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-South Korea,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Hopes for Safe Olympics in Seoul, Praises President Roh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says he hopes the Summer
Olympics in Seoul, South Korea, will be incident-free and that he
has confidence in newly inaugurated President Roh Tae Woo.
   In responses to questions submitted by the South Korean
newspaper, Dong-A Ilbo, Reagan said a smoothly run Olympics
competition in September ``is in everyone's interests.''
   ``The prospect of North Korea, or anyone else's, attempts to
disrupt the games through violence is a danger that we and the
Soviets can agree to work against.''
   ``The key problem in Korea is North Korea's proclivity to use
violence,'' Reagan said, noting the bombing last November of a
South Korean airliner off the coast of Burma. ``The world was
shocked again by the recent murder of 115 innocent people aboard
KAL-858 by North Korea.''
   ``We hope that Moscow will use its close relations with
Pyongyang to urge moderation and to encourage the resumption of
direct North-South contacts on practical ways to reduce tension,''
the president said. ``It is time for the North to eschew violence
and get down to the serious business of resuming dialogue with
Seoul.''
   Reagan, in response to a question about whether he will meet
soon with Roh, replied that ``talk now of the details of summits
and such seems a bit premature.''
   ``As you know, I met President-elect Roh in Washington last
year,'' he said. ``He impressed me as a man committed to the
democratization of your country because he knew that was what
Koreans, including himself, wanted.''
   North Korea has been demanding to be a co-host of the Olympics,
but the International Olympic Committee and South Korea have
rejected the demand.
   A woman who claimed she was a North Korean agent, Kim Hyon Hui,
made a televised confession in Seoul last month in which she said
she destroyed the KAL flight to disrupt the Olympics.
   North Korea has denied it had anything to do with the bombing.
</TEXT>
