<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dominican-Boat     02-29 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-Boat,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boat With About 40 Dominicans Sinks; Survivor Says Most Got to
Shore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK GAUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AGUADA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small boat said to be carrying
about 40 illegal aliens from the Dominican Republic sank in rough
seas just off the west coast, but a survivor said Monday he
believed most made it to shore.
   One person was in custody, another hospitalized, two bodies were
recovered and a third was spotted but washed away before it could
be retrieved, said Luis Garcia, an agent of the U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service.
   Garcia spoke in a telephone interview from Aguadilla, about five
miles from Aguada.
   Hundreds of Dominicans leave in wooden boats each year on the
dangerous, 90-mile journey to Puerto Rico in search of a better
life. Estimates by U.S. officials of the number of Dominicans
living illegally in Puerto Rico range from 40,000 to 160,000.
   The bodies were of two girls, one 14 and the other 16, police in
Aguada said. The boat, estimated at 20-30 feet long, sank Sunday
evening off Aguada, about 85 miles west of San Juan.
   Garcia said Miguel Bigay, a survivor who was with him during the
interview, reported seeing most of the passengers scramble ashore
and flee.
   ``He said most were able to get to shore with him,'' Garcia
said. ``The people who got to shore ran off and hid in the brush.''
   Bigay, who gave his age as about 30 and said he was a part-time
truck driver, said the boat left a beach Saturday night in the
southeastern Dominican province of Higuey with 40-45 passengers,
including eight women.
   It crossed the 90-mile Mona Passage between the Dominican
Republic and Puerto Rico in good weather, but then the see became
rough and a big wave overturned the boat about one-eighth of a mile
from Aguada, Bigay said.
   Garcia quoted him as saying: ``People were screaming and calling
for help.''
   Bigay said he managed to swim ashore but ``thought he was going
to drown because the waves pushed him down every time they passed
over him,'' Garcia said.
   Those in the boat were from different towns and did not appear
to know each other, Bigay said. Police caught him on shore and
Garcia said he would be returned to the Dominican Republic.
   Officials continued searching, but Garcia said he doubted more
survivors would be found because they ``managed to get somewhere
else ... and escaped detention.''
   Pieces of boards believed to be from the boat were on the beach,
along with articles of clothing and a plastic bag labeled
``Dominican Republic.''
   At least 16 Dominicans drowned in December 1986 off Rincon, a
few miles away, when their boat capsized near shore. Last October,
50 or more Dominicans are believed to have died when their boat
sank about three miles off the northeast coast of the Dominican
Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
