<1ST_LINE>u p AM-GoreLoan     02-29 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore Loan,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Campaign To Borrow $1 Million To Finance Super Tuesday Blitz</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s presidential campaign
on Monday took out a loan to pay for media saturation going into
next week's Super Tuesday primaries, a campaign spokesman said.
   ``We have borrowed some money,'' said press spokesman Mike Kopp.
But he declined to say how much, saying that was confidential
campaign strategy information.
   ``We're gong to saturate Super Tuesday ... We want to pour it
on,'' before the March 8 series of 20 primaries and caucuses on
which Gore has staked his Democratic campaign, Kopp said.
   He insisted, however that the campaign is not in financial
trouble and only borrowed the money as ``icing on the cake'' for
the extensive media buy the Tennessee senator already has in place.
   In Tennessee, his state campaign treasurer Johnny Hayes said
Monday that Gore has taken a $1 million line of credit against
which money will be borrowed for a TV blitz in 20 states.
   He said part of the credit line was established with Tennessee
banks.
   Kopp reiterated Gore's pledge to spend more money on the Super
Tuesday contests than any other candidate.
   Gore's public financial statement through Jan. 31 showed that he
had just over $2 million in the bank at that point, considerably
less than the $4 million that money leader Michael Dukakis had on
hand. Kopp said Gore has raised about $1.2 million in February.
   The campaign has declined to give any specifics on its spending,
saying it does not want to tip off its rivals.
   Kopp said new commercials will go on the air Tuesday, following
on the biographical spots that have been running on cable TV
nationwide and on local markets in 14 southern and border states
for the past three weeks.
   The ads are produced both by the Campaign Group, Gore's initial
media consultants, and by Raymond Strother, a media consultant
hired last week.
   Kopp said the new ads will be message-oriented, touting Gore's
record. He said they do not include attacks on other candidates.
   Strother traveled with Gore last Tuesday, and the candidate has
been giving a new emphasis in recent days to his congressional
record being one of championing ``the average working man and
woman.''
   Kopp would not rule out the possibility of such ads, which was
essentially the same stance he took last week when asked to comment
on the $1 million loan.
   Television advertising is seen as a major factor to reach the
voters across the vast Super Tuesday spread of states.
   Dukakis, the Massachussetts governor, was advertising on prime
time television during the Olympics in Miami last week. It was also
a biographical commercial.
   Dukakis aides said commercials were also running in Texas and
Maryland.
   Aides for U.S. Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri said his
commercial promising trade retaliation to open up foreign markets
was going on the air in the South over the weekend.
</TEXT>
