<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Employees     02-29 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Employees,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lay Workers Donate Part of Salaries to Pope in Labor Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Vatican lay employees pledged to
donate part of their day's salary Monday to Pope John Paul II in a
labor protest which a Vatican official denounced as ``completely
unacceptable.''
   Mario Cerullo, president of the Association of Lay Vatican
Workers, said preliminary counts showed more than 90 percent of the
1,800 lay employees took part. The employees work at Vatican
museums, the post office, main library, the daily newspaper
L'Osservatore Romano, Vatican Radio and many offices.
   Workers performed their jobs as usual but signed a special form
promising to donate their first three hours' pay to the pope to
help feed the poor, Cerullo said. He estimated donations would
total about $40,000.
   The labor action _ called by the association an ``active
strike'' _ was called to protest plans to change the Vatican
workers' pay schedule and to demand creation of a special office to
resolve labor disputes in the world's smallest city-state.
   ``The Vatican employees want dignity and respect,'' Cerullo said
in an interview. ``We hate to bother the Holy Father but we had to
do something to show our unhappiness. I hope this is the first and
last time.''
   Archbishop Jan Schotte, a Belgian who handles labor relations
for the Vatican, said in letters to Cerullo and Vatican-based
cardinals that the protest was unjustified, extreme and
``completely unacceptable.''
   He said salary and work conditions were ``superior to those
existing in comparable work places'' and that negotiations could
lead shortly to creation of a special labor office.
   Cerullo said Vatican employees' salaries range from $927 a month
to $1,370. The workers are exempt from Italian taxes, work a
36-hour week and have one month of vacation and 26 paid holidays.
   The strike was triggered by the Vatican's recent decision to pay
workers at the end of each month instead of at the beginning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2022EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Debt     02-29 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Debt,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Other Countries Becoming Reluctant To Lend Money To US</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People in other countries are becoming less
willing to lend money to the United States, the head of the
International Monetary Fund said Monday.
   The congressional Joint Economic Committee has predicted that
U.S. debt would reach about $400 billion at the end of last year.
It is growing at about $150 billion annually.
   ``I have looked at a very long historical set of figures,'' said
Michel Camdessus, the fund's managing director. ``And I have to
tell you that there are no precedents. Each time similar imbalances
have been... reduced, it was through recession ...
   ``Our latest projections suggest that, on present policies and
exchange rates, the imbalances would still continue to be very
large over the medium term,'' he told a conference sponsored by the
Overseas Development Council, a private study group concerned with
problems of the Third World.
   For some time, the growth of U.S. debt has not been matched by
the willingness of business people in other countries to lend more,
he said.
   ``The risks that this portends for renewed disturbances in
financial markets, for increased protectionist pressures, and for a
weakening in global economic activity need no elaboration here,''
said Camdessus, who is French.
   He said the job of the fund is to help all 152 member countries
in setting strategy that will make them grow.
   He suggested that for a long time U.S. output must grow faster
than spending and that countries with surpluses have to do the
reverse. The process, Camdessus said, should take place without
either a slow-down in business or increased inflation.
   He did not name the surplus countries, but Japan and West
Germany are the major nations which in recent years have been
selling more goods than they buy. Surpluses have also been mounting
in Taiwan, South Korea and other newly industrializing areas.
   Camdessus went on to say that nothing can be done without
reducing the U.S. budget deficit.
   ``No reasonable policy instrument that can contribute to this
end should be ignored,'' he said.
   The U.S. Treasury must borrow to meet the deficit, and much of
the money it borrows comes from abroad. For the year ending last
Sept. 30, the deficit was about $149 billion.
   Camdessus called for new proposals that would help cut the debt
of Third World countries.
   ``Any ... proposal that would be market-based and would share in
a mutually agreed fashion between debtors and creditors the
discount on debt and the benefits of adjustment ... could only be
welcome,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>For Release at 8 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Also addressing the conference was American Express Chairman
James D. Robinson III, who suggested creation of a new
international financial organization to help ease the debt crisis
of developing nations by buying their loans.
   Robinson said the organization, which he named ``The Institute
of International Debt and Development,'' would buy outstanding
Third World loans at a discount.
   One possibility, he suggested, would be for the loans to be
acquired at about 60 percent of face value.
   The organization would then offer the banks which had held the
loans ``new, long-term, high-quality obligations,'' including bonds
and certain forms of stock, Robinson said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Embargoed Material</HEAD>
