<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1845EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0697 02-29 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delvalle's Envoy Refuses To Relinquish Post</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 9th graf pvs, bgng: The administration,
to UPDATE with Reagan to issue no new sanctions against Panama;
picks up 10th graf pvs, bgng: Over the; ADDS 1 graf to include
embassy plans to announce legal action against Noriega government</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's ambassador the United States,
proclaiming his loyalty to President Eric Arturo Delvalle, refused
to relinquish the embassy on Monday to an envoy designated by the
military controlled government to replace him.
   The second-ranking Panamanian official at the country's United
Nations mission, Leonardo Kam, showed up at the embassy to assume
his duties, but Ambassador Juan B. Sosa refused to turn the mission
over to him.
   Kam was appointed last Friday by the new government that was
formed after Delvalle was ousted by the National Assembly, which is
dominated by supporters of military strong man Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   After what Kam described as a ``frank'' discussion Monday, he
departed the embassy. Since Friday, Sosa has maintained that the
vote to oust Delvalle was unconstitutional and he has refused to
step down.
   Delvalle's dismissal was touched off by his bid Thursday to fire
Noriega, who ignored the order and then rallied his followers in
the Assembly to replace Delvalle with the former education
minister, Manuel Solis Palma.
   Before his encounter with Kam, Sosa was asked by a reporter
about the position of other embassy diplomats. ``The Panamanian
Embassy is loyal to its ambassador and the ambassador is loyal to
President Delvalle,'' he said.
   Reagan administration officials, meanwhile, said Delvalle's
attempt to reinstate himself as president has been strengthened by
going into hiding and refusing to flee the country. He has been at
an undisclosed location in Panama since the weekend.
   Delvalle is viewed in Washington as a more effective symbol for
opposition forces by being inside Panama than he would if he had
left the country.
   The administration has been pursuing other means to restore
Delvalle to office and to end Noriega's five-year domination of the
country's political life. A number of economic sanctions, including
a trade embargo, are under consideration, and high-level meetings
on that subject were held Monday.
   A U.S. official said Monday that President Reagan planned no new
economic sanctions against Panama, even though he has determined
that Panama has not been cooperating in curbing drug trafficking to
the United States.
   The official, speaking only on condition of anonymity, said
penalties to be announced Tuesday already have been applied against
Panama and thus will have no material impact on that country.
   Under a 1986 law, countries which do not take steps to halt drug
trafficking to the United States are no longer eligible for U.S.
aid and are not entitled to U.S. support for their assistance
requests to international lending institutions.
   Noriega was indicted by two U.S. grand juries on Feb. 5 on
charges that he is a major figure in an international drug
smuggling conspiracy.
   Over the weekend, Noriega won a credentials skirmish at the
Organization of American States when his OAS Ambassador, Ricardo
Leyton, was permitted to occupy Panama's seat for a meeting on the
Panamanian crisis.
   The United States had supported the seating of Lawrence Chewing
Fabrega, a Panamanian diplomat who broke with Noriega two weeks ago.
   Although the OAS refused to take a stand on the Panamanian
situation, a number of Latin American governments have backed
Delvalle. They include El Salvador, Argentina, Venezuela, Uruguay,
the Dominican Republic, Bolivia and Ecuador.
   Some officials have been anxious about the safety of the 10,000
U.S. military personnel in Panama and the thousands of other
Americans there in civilian capacities but Noriega has said all
Americans in Panama will be safe.
   Meanwhile, Panamanian opposition leaders in Washington have been
stepping up their activities against Noriega. They have been
telephoning Panamanian diplomatic missions around the world asking
them to withhold the fees they receive for consular services and
other activities instead of sending the money back to Panama for
use by the new government.
   Embassy officials said that on Tuesday they would reveal ``legal
steps that have been taken against the dictatorship of Noriega.''
