<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorldBankIncome     02-29 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank Income,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Made $679 Million in Second Half of 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank, largest source of aid loans to
the Third World, announced Monday that it made a profit of $679
million for the last six months of 1987, up from $655 million for
the same period the year before.
   The bank's profits come largely from its ability to borrow money
at low rates of interest, because its funds are guaranteed by the
152 member governments. The bank lends money at varying rates,
depending on how poor the country is.
   In the period, the bank borrowed the equivalent of $7.7 billion
in 17 currencies at an average cost of 6.92 percent. Its rate of
return on $20.8 billion worth of investments at the end of the year
was 8.88 percent.
   The profit helped it make $3.6 billion worth of new loans to
Third World countries, reducing the interest rate it charges them
to an annual 7.72 percent for the first six months of this year
from a previous 7.76 percent.
</TEXT>
