<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Bombs     02-29 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Bombs,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Hangs Two Bombers in Public Square</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men have been hanged in a Tehran
square where they planted bombs last year, Iran's official news
agency reported Monday.
   The executions occurred Sunday, the day after five people were
hanged in another square, also for terrorist bombings, the Islamic
Republic News Agency said.
   Hojatoleslam Serajeddin Musavi, commander of neighborhood
Islamic Revolutionary Committees, announced Saturday that 30 people
responsible for recent bomb attacks in Tehran and western Iran had
been arrested.
   Neighborhood committees are vigilante groups that handle some
security duties.
   According to IRNA, Musavi told a news conference those arrested
were ``paid Iraqi agents,'' who were promised 30 million rials
($470,000) for each bomb exploded in a busy area of Tehran and 6-10
million rials ($94,000-$156,000) for each one that went off in an
area less densely populated.
   He said they arrived in the capital Feb.1 to plant bombs during
the 10-day celebration surrounding the anniverary of the
fundamentalist Moslem revolution that ousted the late Shah Mohammad
Reza Pahlavi in 1979.
   IRNA said the bombers were found and arrested by Musavi's
organization soon after a booby-trapped car exploded Feb. 13 and
wounded 10 people on Martyr Bahonar Avenue a few hundred yards from
the residence of revolutionary patriarch Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini.
   The last bombing reported in Tehran was a car that exploded on
an expressway on Feb. 16, wounding two people.
   In its dispatches Monday, IRNA did not say whether the five
people hanged Saturday were among the 30 Musavi said were arrested
that day.
   Iran and Iraq have been at war since September 1980 and Iranian
authorities refer to members of Iranian resistance groups fighting
the Khomeini regime as Iraqi agents. Mujahedeen Khalq, the main
Iranian resistance group, has its headquarters and bases in Iraq.
</TEXT>
