<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nepal-Politics     02-29 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nepal-Politics,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Activists Detained</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leaders said the government
arrested more than 150 activists who were organizing a strike
Monday to protest suspension of six local officials, all of them
members of the outlawed Nepali Congress Party.
   Only a few shops were closed in this capital city on Monday
despite the general strike called by the opposition.
   All political parties were banned in 1960 following Nepal's
dissolution of a Western-style parliamentary system. The Congress
Party, led by Krishna Prashad Bhattarai, has for years sought to
change the present system of government through a disobedience
movement.
   The government said Monday it arrested about 60 strike
organizers.
   Bhattarai, however, told reporters more than 150 of his party's
members were arrested Monday. Congress Party leaders said 35 other
members were arrested in recent days, including the man elected
mayor of Katmandu in elections last March.
   The mayor, his deputy, and four presidents of district and town
assemblies were suspended indefinitely from their offices for
boycotting Constitution Day observances last Dec. 16.
   The government said the six had pledged to work under the
non-party system when they filed nomination papers.
   Nepal, a constitutional monarchy, is governed by a complex
system of district councils and a national legislature.
 
