<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Robertson 1stLd-Writethru a0703 02-29 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Revives Cuban Missile Allegation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new with Robertson-Cuban missiles; pick up 2nd
graf pvs bgng ``Robertson campaigning...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Pat Robertson
revived his charge that there are Soviet missiles in Cuba on
Monday, producing a Cuban refugee who said he had seen the weapons.
   Since Robertson first raised his claim two weeks ago, denials
have been issued by the White House, congressional experts on
U.S.-Soviet affairs and Cuban president Fidel Castro, who Robertson
called ``a butcher and a tyrant.''
   Robertson visited privately with the refugee, who identified
himself only as E. Rodriguez, saying he feared family members still
in Cuba would suffer retribution if he gave his full name.
   Robertson has yet to offer documentation to back up his claim
other than a Miami Cuban-American newspaper, Diario Libre, which
has printed copies of maps drawn by Rodriguez to pinpoint missile
sites.
   ``Ninety-five percent of the Cuban-Americans in Miami believe
there are missiles in Cuba,'' Robertson said at a news conference
where he held up a copy of the newspaper.
   Rodriguez, speaking through an interpreter, said his job in Cuba
as an agricultural planner gave him access to aerial photographs
and to areas where the missiles were based. He said he saw 60
long-range surface-to-surface missiles as well as air defense and
anti-ship missiles. He said he did not know if the missiles had
nuclear warheads. Rodriguez left Cuba three years ago.
   Robertson, campaigning for support in the balloting on Super
Tuesday, was on a two-day swing through Florida, one of the biggest
prizes in the 16-state round of Republican primaries and caucuses
March 8.
   He was greeted by about 400 mostly Cuban-American senior
citizens at the Allapattah Community Center and about the same
number of students at heavily Hispanic La Salle High School.
   ``I will work with you to see Cuba independent and democratic,''
Robertson said at the community center. ``Today I say it, tomorrow
I say it, the next day I say it, Viva Cuba Libre!'' _ long live a
free Cuba.
   He put on an apron and passed trays of chicken, rice and fried
plantains to senior citizens seated at long tables.
   At the school, Robertson was met by students shouting ``Go Pat
Go!'' Some students held signs passed out by campaign staffers.
   When a student asked if Robertson would ever renew diplomatic
relations with Cuba, he replied: ``I don't think we should have
diplomatic relations with a butcher and a tyrant!''
   Robertson began his Florida tour in Jacksonville Monday and
arranged a rally in Miami Monday night, followed by breakfast
Tuesday in Fort Lauderdale and stops in Hollywood, Fort Myers,
Sarasota, Gainesville and Orlando.
   In Jacksonville, Robertson told about 500 supporters that
``along with Texas, Florida is one of the two most pivotal states.''
   He added:
   ``We've got one week to the most crucial election, I believe, in
the history of America, certainly this century and maybe since its
beginning.
   ``We're at a crossroads in America. We're either going to return
to the ways that made this nation great, or we're going to go down
the road.''
   Robertson mentioned a gun problem experienced this year in
several Florida schools.
   ``How can a child study when he's living in mortal fear of
somebody shooting him with a handgun in the halls of the school? We
owe our children an education in a crime-free, drug-free school
environment,'' said Robertson.
   ``If we want to see this country strong. There's only one way in
my estimation to do it. We will restore the greatness of America
through moral strength,'' he added.
   Robertson also said that ``we've got to go back to a time in our
educational system when once again we teach our kids moral values.
We've got to bring God back into the public schools of America.''
   On trade, he said: ``There isn't one country that is treating us
fairly. ... As president of the United States, I'm not going to
shut down American factories and put Americans out of jobs to
improve the standard of living in communist China and communist
Russia.''
   At a news conference following his address, Robertson called
Panama military strong man Manuel Antonio Noriega ``a bandit,'' but
added that ``I don't see us sending troops (to Panama). I don't
think it is necessary.''
   On South Africa, Robertson said, ``I am totally opposed to
apartheid ... but the thing I'm concerned about is turning South
Africa into a bloody battleground.''
   ``I don't want to see a Marxist state in South Africa,''
Robertson said.
</TEXT>
