<DOCNO> AP880229-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2110EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Soviet     02-29 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Soviet,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Monthly Says 500,000 Poles Deported To U.S.S.R. In World
War II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official monthly acknowledged about
500,000 Poles were deported to the Soviet Union from territories
occupied by the Red Army at the outbreak of World War II, and said
many died as a result of harsh conditions.
   The unusual account of the fate of the Poles came in an article
in the February issue of Konfrontacje (Confrontation). It is
published by the Patriotic Movement for National Rebirth, a
national front organization.
   The article said much was written about the wartime deportations
of Poles to Nazi Germany.
   But it said ``the fate of Polish people in the East has been
unnecessarily covered in a mist of secrecy, although it was known
that there were hundreds of thousands of witnesses of those events
living who probably haven't concealed them from relatives.''
   It was the first time a widely circulated official publication
offered a detailed breakdown of the number of Poles deported to the
Soviet Union in World War II, although Polish underground and
Western publications have described the large-scale suffering of
Poles at Soviet hands.
   Last year, Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski criticized
abuses against Poles committed by Soviet dictator Josef Stalin in
an article in the Soviet Communist Party journal Kommunist. He said
thousands of Poles suffered deportation and repression in
territories occupied by the Soviets.
   After the Germans attacked Poland in September 1939, Soviet
troops invaded from the east and occupied eastern Polish
territories under provisions of the Nazi-Soviet non-aggression pact.
   Konfrontacje said Poles in the Soviet-occupied territories
``found themselves in a difficult situation'' suffering from police
harassment and restrictions on civic rights.
   About 4 million Poles lived in the eastern territories before
the war, along with millions of Ukrainians, Byelorussians and Jews.
   The article said a ``safe'' estimate indicates the Soviets
deported 500,000 Poles from the eastern territories in four mass
transports from February 1940 to June 1941, when the Nazis launched
a surprise attack on the Soviet Union.
   Those deported included state clerks, farmers and their
families, refugees who fled Nazi-occupied Poland, intellectuals and
workers, both leftists and right-wingers, the monthly said.
   It said an additional 200,000 Poles were recruited into the
Soviet army and later evacuated to the Soviet Union.
   About 270,000 of the Poles deported or evacuated ``died in
different circumstances _ in fighting with the Red Army, during
long and exhausting transports, as the result of difficult
conditions in Siberia and in other areas'' or else ``did not come
back to Poland'' after the war, it said.
   The monthly said that overall, about 600,000 to 800,000 Poles
from the eastern territories died during the war, almost half of
them killed in a terror campaign launched by Nazi-collaborating
Ukrainian nationalists in 1943.
   Polish and Soviet historians began a weeklong meeting in Warsaw
on Monday, a follow-up to a Moscow session last year devoted to
``blank spots'' in Polish-Soviet relations, referring to topics so
controversial they are unmentioned or distorted in official
histories.
   Participants told Polish television they would discuss the fate
of Poles in the Soviet Union during the war, including the
deportations, and would have at their disposal ``valuable and
important documents'' previously kept secret.
   The meeting is an outgrowth of an agreement signed last year by
Jaruzelski and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev on ideological
and cultural cooperation which discussed the necessity for a more
truthful history of Polish-Soviet relations.
   Gorbachev has encouraged greater examination of history through
his policy of glasnost, or openness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2113EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Wages     02-29 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Wages,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Says Employees Who Stopped Work May Get Higher Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spokesmen for Solidarity said management
promised to consider pay increases for employees of a railroad car
repair plant who stopped work to protest price increases.
   Solidarity's National Executive Commission accused the communist
government of ``alarming ineptness in the economic realm.''
   Spokesmen for the outlawed independent labor federation in
Wroclaw, a southwestern industrial city, said about 1,500 people
joined the job action at the Railway Rolling Stock Repair plant _
about half the work force. Plant officials declined comment.
   A government spokesman denied such a large number of people
participated, and said the stoppage ended when managers dispelled a
misunderstanding about how the annual profit bonus would be paid.
   It appeared to be the biggest work stoppage in Poland since the
government imposed major price increases earlier in February.
   Government spokesman Zbigniew Augustynowicz said plant workers
were disturbed over profit-sharing. He said distribution of the
annual bonus based on profits began last week but many workers
found it too small.
   About a third of the staff stopped work at various times Monday
morning but resumed after plant officials explained how the bonus
was calculated, he said.
   Jozef Pinior, a Wroclaw leader of Solidarity, said about half
the plant's 3,000 workers downed tools at 9 a.m. in response to a
Solidarity call.
   Pinior said plant director Wojciech Zmyslony pleaded with
workers to return to their jobs and said management would consider
increasing monthly pay by the equivalent of $8 to $11.
   Union members said Sunday plant workers were in a ``combative
mood'' because of price increases imposed Feb. 1.
   Besides claiming too much bonus money was going to managers,
they said raises given to offset price increases were inadequate.
   Prices of staple goods were increased 40 percent, with increases
in school tuitions and energy prices set for March 1 and April 1,
as part of an economic reform program aimed at reviving the economy.
   In its statement Monday, the Solidarity National Executive
Commission said: ``Drastic price increases have lowered the living
standards of all society, pushing low-income groups to the level of
subsistence.''
   Union adviser Jacek Kuron read the statement, which accused
police of tightening surveillance of commission members and said
the number of activists jailed, ``often under criminal pretext,''
is growing.
</TEXT>
