<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DemocratsDebate 4thLd-Writethru a0764 02-29 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats Debate, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0764,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Gephardt Wrangle Anew in Democratic Debate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson on issue of race, inserting 4 grafs
after 15th graf pvs, ``Lobbyists would</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender
Richard Gephardt came under attack from rivals in a debate Monday
night for taking contributions from special interest groups, with
Michael Dukakis saying Gephardt had accepted the money and raced
``around the country beating up on the establishment.''
   When Gephardt replied that he had often voted against the
policies advocated by people who had given him contributions,
Dukakis scoffed.
   `This isn't a fairy tale; this isn't kindergarten; you're
talking politics,'' he said.
   Gephardt fought back. ``To suggest that ... you're going to take
direction on how to vote is an affront,'' he said.
   He said he was sure that Dukakis, as governor of Massachusetts,
had taken contributions from firms doing business with the state.
``Does that make you less of a public servant?''
   Yes, said Dukakis, but ``I am not running around the country
beating up on the establishment.''
   Gephardt accepted $341,000 in contributions from political
action committees last year.
   The exchange during the debate at the College of William and
Mary, came eight days before voters in 20 states, most of them in
the South, make their decisions in primaries and caucuses on Super
Tuesday. The debate, the Democrats' third in three days, was, by
the count of moderator Judy Woodruff, the 24th time the Democrats
had met in debate.
   The candidates, at Jesse Jackson's suggestion, wore yellow
ribbons on their jackets in protest of the arrest of Anglican
Archbishop Desmond Tutu in Capetown, South Africa, on Monday.
   To Gary Hart, who joined in the criticism of Gephardt for taking
money from political action committees, the Missourian retorted:
``You took contributions for your Senate campaign.''
   Nonetheless, Hart said, reform is needed: ``The system is out of
control.''
   Gephardt, on the defensive, said, ``We all understand the need
for reform, but to suggest that people have voted according to the
wishes of people who have given them money, I just think is out of
touch with reality. I haven't done that and I know you haven't done
that.''
   Hart said he hadn't and hoped Gephardt hadn't.
   But Jackson said Gephardt's contention that he ignored the
wishes of his contributors was unrealistic.
   ``Lobbyists would lose their jobs if they gave money
continuously against the interests of who they were working for,''
Jackson said.
   At another point, Jackson seized an opportunity to say he was
being treated differently than the other candidates because he is a
black.
   He cited a poll which he said NBC took after the New Hampshire
primary. In it potential voters were asked if they could support a
black for president.
   ``I said did you ask how many would vote for a Greek?'' said
Jackson, a reference to Dukakis, whose parents were Greek
immigrants.
   ``They said no. I said why even bring race into it. My race is
self-evident and my leadership is obvious. Let's take the issues to
the people.''
   For the most part, the candidates wrangled over familiar issues,
with Gephardt belittling Dukakis' plans for increasing government
revenues without a tax increase and Dukakis saying Gephardt has
changed his positions.
   ``In Iowa, Dick was telling us I'm sorry for that vote,''
Dukakis said of Gephardt's vote for the 1981 tax cut proposed by
President Reagan _ a bill that other Democrats say led to the huge
deficits that followed. ``That was the Iowa Gephardt. Now we have
another one here,'' Dukakis added.
   ``I'm trying to figure out which one I'm debating.''
   Gephardt defended his vote for Reagan's tax cuts, saying they
had reduced taxes for the average American.
   And he said the Dukakis plan to collect taxes now evaded by many
Americans _ the New Englander says billions of dollars are involved
_ won't do much to combat deficits.
   ``Sure we want revenue agents but that is not going to solve the
problem,'' Gephardt said.
   Dukakis attacked Gephardt on another front, saying the oil
import fee that Gephardt advocates would damage Mexico.
   ``You're going to kill Mexico,'' Dukakis said.
   Asked Gephardt: ``Are you running for president of Mexico or
president of America?''
   That drew a gasp from the audience and then applause. But more
applause came when Dukakis replied: ``If I'm president of the
United States, I'm going to pay attention to that country.''
   Gore, stressing the harder line he takes on defense issues in
comparison with his rivals, defended the decision by the Reagan
administration to send American ships to protect Kuwaiti tankers.
   ``When the ayatollah said he was going to shut down our access
to 70 percent of the oil available to the free world, no one else
(among the candidates) was willing to say we had a right to keep
the sea lanes open,'' he said.
   The only Democratic candidate who didn't take part in the debate
was Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois.
   The affair's sponsor was the Democratic Leadership Council, an
organization of moderate Democrats who decided after Walter
Mondale's 49-state loss in 1984 to seek to move the party somewhat
toward the right.
</TEXT>
