<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People Sub a0632 02-29 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People, Sub, a0632,0196</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf of final item to CORRECT spelling to Oprah,
sted Ophrah</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oprah Winfrey bought a Mercedes and a Jaguar
when a syndicated television deal made her a millionaire, but the
talk-show host laughs at the notion that fame and fortune may spoil
her.
   ``My feet are still planted firmly on the ground,'' Winfrey said
in an interview published in TV Guide. ``They're just wearing more
expensive shoes.''
   Winfrey's lifestyle reflects her success. She lives in a luxury
apartment with a wraparound view of Lake Michigan, and owns a
Mercedes-Benz 560 SEL and a Jaguar.
   Gayle King Bumpus, an anchorwoman in Connecticut, does not think
wealth and fame have gone to her friend's head. As a fifth
anniversary present, Winfrey sent Bumpus and her husband to Paris,
Rome and Venice.
   ``I remember once she came to visit us in Connecticut in a
stretch limo,'' Bumpus said. ``She was wearing one of her five fur
coats, probably a $25,000 number, and white tennis shoes with
rhinestones on them and a red sweat shirt that said `Husbands Can
Be Temporary but Best Friends Last Forever.'''
</TEXT>
