<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Punjab-Christians     02-29 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Punjab-Christians,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill Seven Members of Christian Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh gunmen killed seven members of a
family in the bloodiest attack on Christians in Punjab state since
Sikh militants began a campaign for autonomy in 1982, police
reported Monday.
   ``It is a gruesome killing, the assailants systematically wiped
out the entire family of Kulwant Massiha,'' said J.P. Virdi, police
chief of Gurdaspur district where the attack occured late Sunday.
Gurdaspur is 40 miles south of the Sikhs' holy city of Amritsar.
   Virdi said the motive for the killings was not known. There have
been several cases in recent years of Sikh extremists killing the
entire families of Hindus or Sikhs suspected of being police
informers.
   Four gummen entered the Massiha house and opened fire with
automatic rifles on the victims who were sitting in one room,
according to Virdi.
   He said the seven killed were Massiha, three brothers, one
sister, their 70-year-old mother and Massiha's 7-year-old son.
   Massiha's wife was away in the village of Kalibramnia when the
terrorists struck, Virdi added.
   He said that as the killers fled they wounded seven people in
Kalibramnia.
   Sikhs, who make up about 2 percent of India's 780 million
people, claim they are discriminated against by Hindus who form
about 82 percent of the population. Punjab state is predominantly
Sikh, and separatists are demanding an independent homeland there.
   Christians compose 2.5 percent of India's population, and most
of the few who live in Punjab are in the Gurdaspur district that
borders Pakistan. Many of the Christians in Punjab are immigrants
from predominantly Moslem Pakistan.
   Police say Sikh extremists have killed at least 313 people in
Punjab this year. Last year they were blamed for more than 1,000
killings in the state.
   Sikhism is an offshoot of the Hindu religion.
</TEXT>
