<DOCNO> AP880229-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Waldheim 3rdLd-Writethru a0752 02-29 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Waldheim, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0752,0830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nazi Document Shows Waldheim Forwarded Letter On Deporting Greeks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6-13, ``Waldheim says ... with 9 grafs to UPDATE with
name of officer receiving document, Waldheim post at time.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A key Nazi document made public Monday
shows that Kurt Waldheim signed a German letter seeking approval
for mass deportation of Greek civilians in 1943 in a ``cleansing
operation.''
   The document, found in U.S. National Archives, was vital in the
Justice Department's decision to place Waldheim, now Austria's
president and formerly U.N. secretary-general, on a ``watchlist''
barring him from the United States.
   ``The document was one of those used in making the watchlist
decision,'' Justice Department spokesman John Russell told The
Associated Press by telephone from Washington Monday.
   That U.S. government decision said in part that Waldheim
``assisted or otherwise participated'' in ``mass deportation of
civilians.''
   The document, dated Aug. 15, 1943, was made available to the AP
by the World Jewish Congress and its authenticity was confirmed by
Justice Department sources.
   Waldheim says he was innocent of war crimes. He was serving as
deputy operations officer of the German General Staff attached to
the 11th Italian army in Athens at the time the document was sent.
   The document shows Waldheim, while not authorizing the
deportations, received the communication via radio, transcribed it
and forwarded it, the World Jewish Congress said.
   In the message, a German army officer in the field was seeking
authorization from headquarters to deport all the male civilians in
northern Greece where the division was operating. The request was
sent to a Gen. Gyldenfeldt who subsequently approved the
deportation, the World Jewish Congress said.
   However, the order was countermanded before it could be used to
deport any Greek civilians, the World Jewish Congress said.
   The communication mentions ``heavy bandit concentrations'' and
says, ``Bridgehead formations by groups seem particularly
promising, for which reason scheduled cleansing operations in this
area are deemed necessary.
   ``(There is) Hope of success only if all male civilians are
seized and deported.''
   The Nazis often used the term ``cleansing operations'' to refer
to destruction of towns and mass execution of inhabitants as a
warning to others to report partisans to German authorities.
Deported Greek civilians were generally sent to German labor camps.
   The document also says the ``Jewish Committee'' operating in the
town of Joannina, Greece, ``must be regarded as a center of
preparations for a resistance movement.''
   The following March, the Nazis deported 1,860 Jews, virtually
the entire Jewish population of Joannina, to Auschwitz death camp
in Poland, the World Jewish Congress said. The document signed by
Waldheim did not seek authorization to deport the Jews.
   The Austrian government has complained that the Justice
Department has not turned over all information on which it based
its decision to prohibit Waldheim's entry into the United States.
   The U.S. government said it is not up to the United States to do
Austria's investigation. It said the documents are available to the
Austrian government and that Waldheim can appeal the watchlist
decision if he wishes.
   He has not done so.
   A commission of six international historians appointed by the
Austrian government found in February that as a German army
officer, Waldheim knew about Nazi war crimes and could have done
more to prevent atrocities. It said it did not have evidence he
actually committed atrocities, but left open the question of
whether he was guilty of any crime.
   Waldheim said he was vindicated by the commission.
   Under the Nuremberg Charter, the deportation of civilians is
both a war crime and a crime against humanity, the World Jewish
Congress said in a statement.
   Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress,
said Monday his organization provided the document to the Justice
Department in 1986.
   The translation of sections of the document from German into
English was done by the World Jewish Congress. It was not
questioned by the Justice Department.
   In London, the British Defense Ministry appealed to the public
Monday for information about Waldheim's wartime activities that
might help its investigation into the Nazi executions of six
British commandos in 1944.
   The commandos, a raiding party captured in the Balkans off
Alimina island in April 1944, were handed over for interrogation to
the unit in which Waldheim served.
   They refused to talk and were executed by the Nazis _ a war
crime under the Geneva convention on prisoners of war.
   The Conservative government ordered an investigation two weeks
ago to try to pin down whether Waldheim interrogated the six men.
   Ian Stewart, minister of state for the armed forces, announced
in a written reply in the House of Commons that ``anyone who has
concrete evidence that might be relevant to the review is
encouraged to submit it to the Ministry of Defense for
examination.''
