<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PLO 1stLd-Writethru a0718 02-29 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0718,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Independence, U.S. Prestige At Stake in Dispute Over PLO
Mission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-5 recast 1st graf, UPDATE with U.S. allies
opposing closure. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Later this ...; INSERT 2
grafs after 12th graf pvs, The United ... UPDATING with Walters'
remarks. Picks up 13th graf pvs, Zehdi Labib ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American intention to close the PLO
mission by March 21 jeopardizes U.N. independence, Arab and Western
diplomats told a special General Assembly session Monday.
   Representatives of the 21-nation Arab Group, the PLO and the
45-nation Islamic Conference urged the United States to submit the
dispute to binding arbitration, and asked the assembly to request
an advisory opinion from the World Court in The Hague.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar also recommended
arbitration and said the integrity of the world organization was at
stake.
   Even close U.S. allies such as Canada, members of the European
Community and the Scandinavian countries urged the United States
not to close the PLO mission and joined in the call for arbitration.
   ``At stake at this point are the effective functioning of the
United Nations and the right of the organization to hear the views
of those invited to attend as observers,'' Canadian Ambassador
Stephen Lewis said, speaking also on behalf of Australia and New
Zealand.
   Later this week, the 159-nation General Assembly is expected to
approve resolutions echoing all those recommendations. A resolution
passed in December asked the United States not to close the mission
of the Palestine Liberation Organization, which has non-voting,
observer status.
   The confrontation over the PLO mission, which Congress has
ordered closed by March 21, has become the bitterest argument ever
between the United Nations and the host country.
   Several speakers said Monday the dispute could hurt U.S. peace
efforts in the Middle East, where Secretary of State George P.
Shultz has been on a shuttle mission.
   U.S. prestige at the United Nations already was waning when the
PLO issue arose, primarily because Washington's failure to pay its
full share of U.S. expenses for the several years has contributed
to the worst financial crisis in the organization's 42-year history.
   Peter Florin of East Germany, president of the General Assembly,
opened the Monday session with a reminder by citing a charter
provision saying a member can lose its vote if arrears grow too
large.
   The United States, which is assessed a quarter of the U.N.
budget, now owes more than $535 million in dues and contributions
to peacekeeping forces. At the current rate of funding by Congress,
the United States could face losing its vote in 1990.
   Last week, U.S. Ambassador Vernon Walters said: ``We cannot
continue to neglect our financial commitments to the United Nations
and then expect that our opinions, policies and positions will
carry their former weight in the world body.''
   Arab diplomats said Monday the credibility of the United States
and the independence of the United Nations are at issue, not just
the fate of the 13-year-old PLO mission.
   The United Nations and U.S. State Department both say the
anti-terrorism bill ordering the PLO mission closed violates the
1947 U.S.-U.N. headquarters agreement, but Attorney General Edwin
Meese III is said to be planning to implement the legislation.
   Walters told a news conference Monday he didn't know what Meese
was going to do.
   He said a ``series of discussions is going on within the U.S.
government as to what is the appropriate action to take under the
circumstances and I am not aware the various agencies in the U.S.
government have reached some decision in this matter.''
   Zehdi Labib Terzi, PLO representative at the United Nations,
said Monday: ``Will the U.N. headquarters in New York be in a
position to continue operating in the absence of a respected and
adhered-to headquarters agreement?''
   Karim Ebrahim al-Shakar, ambassador of Bahrain and chairman of
the Arab Group, said the decision to close the mission was ``part
of a feverish Zionist campaign against the Palestinian people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
