<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslav-Book     02-29 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslav-Book,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Bans Another Book By Dissident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Belgrade District Court on
Monday banned another book by dissident sociologist Vojislav
Seselj, saying it could ``imperil public peace,'' the state's
Tanjug news agency reported.
   The book, titled ``The Books For The Pyre,'' deals with court
documents and proceedings from several previous trials involving
Seselj's works.
   Yugoslav courts have banned at least five of the sociologist's
books.
   Seselj was convicted in July 1984 of counter-revolutionary
activity, largely on the basis of an unpublished manuscript that
took a critical look at Yugoslavia's economic and social problems.
He served nearly two years of an eight-year prison sentence.
   Tanjug said Seselj's latest work slandered Josip Broz Tito,
founder and leader of Communist Yugoslavia who died in 1980. By
law, anyone publicly denigrating Tito is liable to criminal
prosecution.
   Tanjug did not say if further action might be taken against
Seselj.
</TEXT>
