<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Unions     02-29 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Unions,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Trade Unions Attack Proposal To Establish Independent
Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's official trade unions on Monday
denounced a proposal by a group of academics to consider
establishing the country's first independent union.
   In a statement carried by the government news agency MTI, the
Central Council of Hungarian Trade Unions said the group seeks ``to
destroy the unity of trade unions and set up organizations outside
the movement.''
   On Feb. 19, some members of the Hungarian Academy of Sciences
met to discuss the possibility of establishing an independent
union, well-informed sources in Budapest said Monday.
   Several hundred people attended the meeting to consider creating
the Tudosz Union of scientific workers, said the sources who spoke
with the condition they not be identified. They were contacted by
telephone from Vienna.
   The sources said after the meeting, academics from several
universities, including the Karl Marx Economics University,
expressed in university newspapers their support and their
intention to join the new union if it were completely independent.
   Some academics have criticized the official unions in communist
Hungary for not protesting a government decision to cut the
nation's scientific budget by 15 percent.
   According to the sources, a committee of about 30 people was set
up at the Feb. 19 meeting to determine under what conditions the
union could operate.
   The scientists currently belong to the Union of Public
Employees, which is under the umbrella of the central union council.
   The sources said the preparatory committee has sent a report to
scientific insititutions across the country asking them to
recommend delegates to the committee to ensure broad representation.
   There are no independent trade unions in Hungary.
   The first independent union in the Soviet bloc was Solidarity,
formed in Poland in August 1980 during nationwide strikes. It was
chartered by the government but then suspended in December 1981 and
subsequently outlawed.
   MTI reported the union council statement did not directly
mention the academics, but referred to ``a limited group'' that it
said was ``motivated by ill-willed political considerations.''
   The agency quoted the statement as saying the council rejects
``the intentions of those who make an attempt to set up
organizations opposing the trade union movement.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
