<2ND_LINE>AM-Hart-New York,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hart Doesn't Make It Onto New York Primary Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential hopeful Gary Hart, mired in the
back of the Democratic pack, failed to qualify for New York's
Democratic primary ballot, the state board of elections ruled
Monday.
   Board spokesman Steven LaFever said petitions meant to get the
former Colorado senator a spot on New York's April 19 primary
ballot contained only 6,864 signatures, more than 3,000 less than
required.
   To qualify for the statewide primary ballot, Democratic
candidates must file petitions containing the signatures of at
least 10,000 registered Democrats and at least 100 of those
signatures must come from each of 17 of the state's 34
congressional districts.
   The other five announced major candidates and political
extremist Lyndon LaRouche all filed petitions last week with more
than enough signatures to qualify for the ballot.
   Jon Kaiman, New York coordinator for the Hart campaign, said a
court appeal of the board's ruling would be considered.
   ``We don't know what to make of it,'' said Kaiman of the board's
finding. ``We were under the impression we had them (enough
signatures).''
   LaFever said the Hart petitions were received in the mail Monday
morning. The deadline for getting a postmark on the petitions was
midnight Thursday.
   Hart dropped out of the presidential race in May amid reports of
his relationship with a Miami model and rejoined the race in
December. He has been running well behind the rest of the field in
early contest states.
</TEXT>
