<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater-Boys'Life     02-29 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater-Boys' Life,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Boys' Life,' A New Play, Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Remember the '70s?,'' asks one of the three
rapidly aging young men who dominate the action in ``Boys' Life,''
a brittle, boorish and unappealing comedy that stumbled into the
Mitzi Newhouse Theater at Lincoln Center on Monday night.
   All that another member of this troubled trio can recall about
the decade is Watergate and the Sex Pistols, but then he's not
having such a great time in the 1980s either.
   All three guys have women problems, and playwright Howard Korder
examines their woes in numbing detail. Phil (Steven Goldstein) is a
good-natured schmo, still trying to score with a girl who already
has dumped him. Don (Jordan Lage) is equally dim-witted, but he
manages to find a woman who will put up with his jock mentality.
   The most interesting _ and sarcastic _ character in the play is
Jack (Clark Gregg) who already is married but willing to fool
around. His mean-spiritedness gets a workout during the evening at
the expense of the other characters.
   Some of Jack's comments are funny, but he's really a nasty
fellow. The playwright finally gives him his due in the last scene,
a wedding reception. Between sips of champagne, Jack gets to
confront the emptiness of his own life. By then, the audience
doesn't care. They have had to confront the emptiness of Korder's
play for some 90 minutes.
   The large cast _ some 13 actors, in all _ works hard and
undoubtedly will go on to better things. So will director W.H. Macy
who at least keeps the actors in motion on James Wolk's mobile set.
It's the play that never goes anywhere at all.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
