<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2206EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MultipleKillings     02-29 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Killings,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simmons Competent to Stand Trial, Judge Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUSSELLVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of killing 16 people,
including 14 members of his own family, is competent to stand
trial, a judge ruled Monday before setting a May 9 trial date.
   Circuit Judge John Patterson accepted a state mental hospital
finding that R. Gene Simmons was competent to aid in his own
defense.
   The State Hospital in Little Rock also found that Simmons, 47,
was sane at the time of the slayings, but that ultimately will be
decided by a jury, defense attorney John Harris noted.
   Simmons was transferred Monday to the Pope County Jail at
Russellville from the State Hospital, where he has undergone a
psychiatric examination since late December.
   On Dec. 28, Simmons surrendered to police in Russellville after
a 45-minute shooting spree in which two former co-workers were
killed and four people were wounded.
   Police then searched Simmons' rural home near Dover where, over
a two-day period, they found 14 bodies _ Simmons' wife, four
daughters, three sons, two spouses of his children, three
grandchilden, and a child who officials say Simmons fathered by his
oldest daughter.
   Dr. Roy Ragsdill, director of the hospital, said the agency
answered yes to both questions asked by the judge: first, whether
Simmons was competent to stand trial and, second, whether he had an
ability to appreciate his actions and conform his behavior within
legal limits.
   But Simmons may still plead innocent by reason of insanity,
Harris said. Simmons could contend either he was unable to tell
right from wrong at the time of the killings or if he was, he was
nonetheless unable to conform his behavior to the law.
   ``They said he was responsible; that means he's not legally
insane,'' prosecutor John Bynum said. ``We thought all along he was
competent to stand trial. ... We're real pleased with the ruling.''
   Harris said he visited Simmons Monday and that he seemed in good
spirits. Harris said more psychiatric tests are needed, and that it
could take a couple of months to get the results back.
   ``Psychiatrists are like lawyers,'' Harris said. ``You get a
different one, you get a different opinion.''
   Simmons has not been arraigned. Lt. Jay Winters of the Pope
County Sheriff's Office said the arraignment may occur Tuesday.
Bynum said it should be soon, but said he didn't know if it would
be Tuesday.
</TEXT>
