<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     02-29 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Women End Fast for Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Tamil women ended their 10-day
fast for peace Monday by taking water mixed with salt and sugar,
witnesses said.
   The hunger strikers, Anama David, 58, and Nesamma Vadival, 50,
are members of the Tamil Mothers Front and had vowed not to eat
until Indian troops ceased anti-rebel operations and Tamil
separatist guerrillas agreed to negotiations.
   The witnesses spoke on condition of not being identified.
   There was no indication the women's demands had been met.
   An official at the Indian High Commission, or embassy, in
Colombo said Indian troops had reduced operations in northern and
eastern Sri Lanka, zones where the Tamil minority form a majority.
   But the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
move was not related to appeals from the two women and he insisted
the scaling down did not amount to a cease-fire.
   In New Delhi, Foreign Ministry spokesman Gopalaswami
Parthasarthy said operations against the Tamil rebels were
continuing. He said India would agree to talks with the rebels only
after they surrendered their weapons.
   A senior Sri Lankan military official, who also spoke on
condition that he not be identified,, said, however, that Indian
soldiers suspended operations in eastern Batticaloa district in a
bid to save the lives of the women, who were reported in poor
condition before abandoning their fast.
   Officials at the Sri Lankan military headquarters in Colombo
said there was no fighting between Indian troops and Tamil rebels
for the previous 24 hours. The officials, who cannot be identified
under briefing rules, said Indian soldiers were continuing search
operations and patrols, however.
   More than 45,000 Indian soldiers are in Sri Lanka to enforce an
Indian-sponsored peace accord signed last July 29 with the Sri
Lankan government to try to end the rebels' four-year war for an
independent Tamil homeland in the northern zone of this island off
India's southern coast.
   A spokesman for the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the
largest rebel group, said Sunday the Tigers were prepared for
unconditional talks with the Indian government.
   More than 8,000 people have been killed in Sri Lanka since the
Tamil insurrection began. Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, comprise
18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people. They claim the
Sinhalese Buddhist majority discriminate against them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
