<DOCNO> AP880229-0220 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater-Tapman     02-29 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater-Tapman,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moses Gunn Stars as Blues Player</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moses Gunn is such a good actor that when he's
speaking, as the blues singer-musician in the new play ``Tapman,''
he makes the character credible.
   However, the play, which opened Sunday at the off-Broadway
Hudson Guild Theater, holds together about as well as a cookie that
has been stepped on.
   The plot focuses on Tapman, who's nearing 50, thinks of himself
as old, ruminates about death and worries because he never has made
a recording.
   Tapman recently has married a chic, well-dressed woman (Kim
Hamilton), after his first wife died. His daughter (Seret Scott)
from his first marriage dislikes the new wife and has a chip on her
shoulder. It's an awkwardly written part awkwardly acted.
   Tapman gets drunk when it's time to go on stage, so the other
three members of his band perform without him and they lose jobs.
He then misses three dates entirely. His musicians, Dean Irby,
Helmar Augustus Cooper and Guy Davis, venerate him but resolve to
work without him.
   The band finally gets a chance to play at the opening of a huge
blues club in Houston, and Tapman rejoins them for the night. But
the play drifts pointlessly, as Tapman begins drinking again and
sends his daughter, who hates blues, on to sing with the band. He
says she is his legacy.
   Author Karen Jones-Meadows has had one other play produced
off-Broadway. Samuel P. Barton directed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissUSA-Assault     02-29 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss USA-Assault,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Investigate Circumstances Surrounding Setting of Suspect's
Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are conducting a criminal
investigation to discover why a judge set bail of only $100 for a
man accused of attempted sexual assault on television actress Tracy
Scoggins, authorities said Monday.
   One of those under investigation is associate municipal
magistrate Rodolfo Romero, police Lt. J.R. Grijalva said.
   Pedro Concepcion Padilla, 35, of El Paso was arrested and
charged with attempted sexual assault after Miss Scoggins, in town
to serve as co-host of the Miss USA pageant, was attacked in a
hotel elevator Thursday night.
   The assailant tore Miss Scoggins' clothes and pushed her into
the back of the elevator. She fought the man off and Padilla was
detained by hotel guests and security before police arrived and
arrested him.
   Romero set $100 bail on the third-degree felony; prosecutors
normally ask for $15,000 bail in similar cases. The decision drew
strong criticism from Miss Scoggins, best known as for her role as
Monica Colby in the television show ``The Colbys.''
   Police are investigating ``the actions of the parties involved
in setting the bond,'' Grijalva said.
   ``We received information over the weekend that there may have
been collusion between the subjects involved,'' he said. ``We may
be looking into some type of misconduct charges.''
   Grijalva would not elaborate on who else is being investigated.
Padilla was represented by lawyer Jose Montes.
   Padilla, who had given police an alias and a false address,
surrendered to police Saturday after District Judge Brunson Moore
issued a new warrant that carried a $100,000 bail. Padilla posted
the required 15 percent of that amount and is free.
   Romero has not returned telephone calls to his office seeking
comment on the case. His home telephone number is unlisted.
</TEXT>
