<2ND_LINE>AM-Officer Slain, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0708,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Missionary Remembered At Memorial Service</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 16th graf, `Harvey was...', to CORRECT Stallworth bond
to $100,200 sted $300,000; update with Cooks being returned from
Houston. Picks up 17th graf, `McCarthy was...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An off-duty policeman shot during an attempted
robbery was remembered Monday as a ``hero in the strictest sense''
at a memorial service for the third Dallas officer slain in six
weeks.
   Hundreds of officers, some weeping and others with their badges
taped in black, filled the Eagle's Nest Cathedral at a memorial
service for Gary D. McCarthy, a former missionary who joined the
force 14 months ago.
   At least 2,200 people attended, police spokesman Ed Spencer said.
   ``He left the foreign mission field but he found another mission
field,'' said the Rev. Clyde Box, pastor of Brook Hollow Baptist
Church in DeSoto where McCarthy, a husband and father of two
children, attended church.
   ``While Gary was a policeman, the streets became his mission
field. Last Friday he gave his life on that field.''
   McCarthy's funeral will be Tuesday in his hometown of Amarillo.
   Police were holding three men in connection with McCarthy's
death Friday, but the district attorney's office said none had been
formally charged by Monday afternoon. The three were arrested on
capital murder warrants.
   One of them, Vincent Edward Cooks, 23, was paroled Aug. 4 from
the Texas Department of Corrections less than a year after he began
serving a five-year sentence for aggravated assault of a police
officer.
   Cooks had originally been charged with attempted capital murder
after apparently shooting at an off-duty police officer outside a
club in Houston.
   Houston Police Sgt. V.W. West said Cooks pleaded no contest to
the reduced aggravated assault charge and began serving his
sentence in December 1986.
   Cooks was arrested Sunday at a Houston apartment where he tried
to escape from a second-story window, said Dallas Police Lt. Ron
Waldrop.
   Another man arrested in the case, Tony Ray Harvey, 23, of
Houston, was paroled Jan. 18 after serving 18 months of a six-year
sentence for aggravated robbery and unauthorized use of a motor
vehicle, police said.
   The third man, Tracy Dewayne Stallworth, 27, of Irving, has no
prior convictions.
   Police would release few details in the case.
   ``We'd rather not get into specifics about what we're going to
allege that any of the participants did because, obviously, this
case is coming back to Dallas for trial and we want to protect as
much of the investigation as we can,'' Waldrop said.
   Harvey was held Monday on $500,000 bond, while Stallworth's bond
was set at $100,000, plus an additional $200 bond for possession of
a controlled substance. Cooks was moved from Houston to Dallas on
Monday but bond was not immediately set, a jail spokeswoman said.
   McCarthy was escorting a grocery store manager back from a bank
visit when a man jumped out of a car to rob the manager, police
said.
   The off-duty officer was shot three times, including once in the
heart, but was able to return fire, police said. He died several
hours later.
   McCarthy's death was the seventh in six shootings involving
police this year. In addition to the three dead police officers,
four civilians have been killed by police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
