<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HostageSutherland     02-29 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostage Sutherland,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Events Scheduled to Mark 1,000th Day of Captivity for Hostage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT COLLINS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former Lebanese students of
hostage professor Thomas Sutherland said Monday that the U.S.
government has failed to provide leadership in solving the hostage
problem and Lebanon's civil war.
   Farij El-Awar and Basil Hamdan, who studied under the Colorado
State University professor when he was agriculture dean at American
University in Beirut, spoke at a news conference announcing CSU
activities planned this week to mark Sutherland's 1,000th day of
captivity Friday.
   Both El-Awar and Hamdan are graduate students at CSU.
   Hamdan said Sutherland believed his role as a professor extended
beyond the classroom to helping underdeveloped countries.
   But, Hamdan said, ``the U.S., as a government, is not providing
the leadership it needs to solve the problem. ... They have chosen
to ignore it because of political reasons.''
   Sutherland, 56, was abducted in Beirut on June 9, 1985. He was
working at the Beirut university while on leave from CSU.
   El-Awar said Sutherland ``introduced a new spirit to the
school'' and obtained a new computer for the university in Beirut.
   CSU has planned a number of activities in honor of Sutherland
this week, including the distribution of yellow ribbons Wednesday,
Thursday and Friday; a video with statements by former hostages
Friday; and a ceremony and reception Friday to include appearances
by two of Sutherland's daughters and the Rev. Lawrence Martin
Jenco, a former Beirut hostage held captive with Sutherland.
   CSU President Philip Austin has proclaimed Thursday as ``Tom
Sutherland Awareness Day'' on campus.
   Hamdan said he thinks the Reagan administration is too afraid of
risking small setbacks in the Middle East to begin the complex
strategy required to solve the region's problems.
   ``There is no easy answer to the Lebanese problem. It would be
really childish to say the U.S. could solve the problem tomorrow
... but the government has to have some large vision. If it built
one thing at a time, it would come to a solution,'' Hamdan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
