<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersTalks 1stLd-Writethru a0763 02-29 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Talks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0763,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outlook Dim for Averting Writers Strike; Could Begin As Early As
Thursday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf pvs, `A strike...', to add
later comment from union. Picks up 7th graf, `The writers...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major issues were unresolved Monday just
hours before the expiration of a contract between the 9,000-member
Writers Guild of America and movie and television producers.
   Negotiations between the two sides were expected to continue
until early Tuesday, and union officials declined to say what they
would recommend to members until after the producers' final offer
was on the bargaining table. The union's contract was to expire at
midnight, but the earliest a strike could begin is Thursday,
officials said.
   ``But it doesn't look optimistic,'' said Cheryl Rhoden,
spokeswoman for the WGA, which represents about 6,500 writers on
the West Coast and 2,500 on the East Coast.
   Herb Steinberg, spokesman for the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers, agreed, saying, ``The situation is not good.''
   West Coast union members are to vote Tuesday evening on whether
to accept what emerges from the latest round of talks or reject it
and go on strike. East Coast members vote Wednesday, and results of
the votes aren't expected to be available until midday Wednesday.
The walkout could come as early as Thursday, Ms. Rhoden said.
   A strike by writers would be felt first by daily daytime
programs and talk shows that go through many scripts, Ms. Rhoden
said. It would take longer for a walkout to affect shows that need
fewer scripts and have a longer lead time.
   In what he said would be the final public statement before
meeting with the membership on both coasts, the guild's chief
negotiator said Monday evening that the WGA will stay at the
bargaining table as long as necessary.
   ``Perhaps something will break in the next 12 hours or so,''
said Brian Walton, also the executive director of Writer's Guild
West. ``At the moment, the companies and the networks have still
declined to meet us in finding reality-based solutions to our
concerns in many areas.''
   He accused the alliance and the networks of ``continuing to
promulgate press releases with doomsday statistics about how the
film and broadcast industries are in disastrous shape.''
   The writers union, which has a reputation as one of Hollywood's
most militant, last went on strike three years ago. That walkout
lasted for two weeks before writers voted to accept a package
offering them essentially the same terms as the one they had
earlier rejected.
   The median annual income for writers is $40,000 a year, but
about half of the WGA's members are unemployed at any given time,
Ms. Rhoden said.
   Main issues separating the two sides are disputes over creative
rights, residuals from foreign markets and residuals for one-hour
programs.
   On the creative-rights issue, the union wants original writers
to have the power to do the first rewrite of any material, plus the
right to be on the set when the program is being produced.
   ``Sometimes,'' Ms. Rhoden complained, ``original writers aren't
even notified when rewrites are being done.''
   However, Steinberg said such issues are appropriately handled in
individual negotiations when writers agree to terms on which they
will sell their work, not in a national contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0228 </DOCNO>
