<BYLINE>Today in History</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Saturday, March 12, the 72nd day of 1988. There are 294
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On March 12, 1912, Juliette Gordon Low founded an organization
in Savannah, Ga., called the Girl Guides, which later became the
Girl Scouts.
   On this date:
   In 1664, New Jersey became a British colony as King Charles II
granted land in the New World to his brother James, the Duke of
York.
   In 1925, Chinese revolutionary leader Sun Yat-sen died.
   In 1930, Mohandas K. Gandhi began a 200-mile march to protest a
British tax on salt.
   In 1932, the ``Swedish Match King,'' Ivar Kreuger, committed
suicide in Paris, leaving behind a financial empire that turned out
to be worthless.
   In 1933, President Franklin D. Roosevelt gave the first of his
``fireside chats,'' telling Americans in a radio broadcast what was
being done to deal with the nation's financial crisis.
   In 1938, German troops entered Austria, completing what Adolf
Hitler described as his mission to restore his homeland (he had
been born in Branau) to the Third Reich.
   In 1939, Pope Pius XII was formally crowned in ceremonies at the
Vatican.
   In 1940, Finland surrendered to the Soviet Union during World
War II.
   In 1947, President Harry S. Truman established what became known
as the Truman Doctrine to help Greece and Turkey resist Communism.
   In 1959, the House joined the Senate in approving statehood for
Hawaii.
   In 1969, Beatle Paul McCartney married Linda Eastman in London.
   In 1980, a Chicago jury found John Wayne Gacy guilty of the
murders of 33 men and boys.
   Ten years ago: Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin held a news
conference in which he denounced a Palestinian guerrilla raid the
day before that claimed the lives of 34 Israelis, and hinted at
retaliation for the ``architects of the bloodbath.''
   Five years ago: Secretary of State George P. Shultz opened a new
diplomatic drive to get foreign armies out of Lebanon as he met at
the State Department with Lebanese Foreign Minister Elie Salem.
   One year ago: A federal judge in Washington dismissed lawsuits
by Lt. Col. Colonel Oliver North seeking to stop an independent
counsel's investigation of his role in the Iran-Contra affair.
   Today's Birthdays: AFL-CIO president Lane Kirkland is 66. Former
astronaut Wally Schirra is 65. The president of Argentina, Raul
Alfonsin, is 61. Playwright Edward Albee is 60. Atlanta Mayor
Andrew Young is 56. Former NBC newsman Lloyd Dobyns is 52. Actress
Barbara Feldon is 47. Actress-singer Liza Minnelli is 42.
Singer-songwriter James Taylor is 40.
   Thought for Today: ``My life needs editing.'' _ Mort Sahl,
American comedian.
</TEXT>
