<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Brazil-USVisas Adv07   02-29 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-US Visas, Adv 07,0813</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, March 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Brazilians Lining Up at 4 a.m. for U.S. Visas</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was 4 a.m., and the line of
Brazilians seeking tourist visas had already formed outside the
U.S. Consulate in Rio de Janeiro. It started near the front door
and before long wound around the corner.
   Ever since the Brazilian government on Jan. 1 rescinded a
25-percent surtax on overseas airplane tickets and on U.S. dollars
purchased for foreign travel, the Consulate has been besieged with
visa requests.
   On this particulary morning, one man in the line _ he refused to
give his name _ had no intention of going to Disneyworld or looking
out over New York City from the top of the Empire State Building.
He was there, he said, because he can sell his place in line later
for 10,000 cruzados _ about $100.
   The desire of Brazilians to travel to the United States is
growing, not only because it is cheaper nowadays, but because at
least some hope to stay there, even if illegally.
   In 1987 the number of those seeking U.S. visas averaged 300 a
day. Now it is 450, sometimes more than 600.
   ``There has been an increased demand for services, but our
resources have not expanded accordingly,'' Clyde Bishop, the head
of the Consular Section, said in an interview.
   The Consulate has just one U.S.Foreign Service officer to handle
non-immigrant visas.
   ``Me,'' Bishop said.
   The result is delay, and grumbling and dissatisfaction on both
sides.
   ``Our people are working 10 to 12 hours a day processing
visas,'' Bishop said. ``Often they go without lunch.''
   The Consulate's air conditioning broke down recently, and the
temperature inside reached 100 degrees.
   ``The situation is serious,'' said Oscar Dalsenter, president of
the Brazilian Association of Travel Agencies. ``We have people with
reserved flights and booked hotels who miss their trips because of
the visa delay,''
   Most of the visa seekers are legitimate travelers, happy about
the repeal of the tax and hoping to take advantage of cheap charter
flights to the United States.
   A Brazilian can fly to Disneyworld in Florida and back in a
charter group for $650. The normal round-trip economy fare from Rio
de Janeiro to Miami is $1,600.
   The price drops even more if a tourist _ ticket and visa in hand
_ decides to buy the permitted $1,000 for foreign travel at the
official government exchange rate. Near the end of February, for
example, a traveler could have bought the $1,000 for 97,000
Brazilian cruzados and immediately sold the dollars back in Rio's
loosely controlled black market for 121,000 cruzados. The profit
then goes to offset the cost of the plane ticket.
   But some in the lines are Brazilians hoping to use tourist visas
to stay in the United States as illegal aliens. The U.S. State
Department has reported that the number of illegal Brazilians in
the United States recently has been on the rise.
   According to newspaper polls, a growing number of Brazilians
want to leave the country for good because of serious economic and
political problems.
   Among the measures the U.S. Consulate has taken is to require
potential tourists to show proof of income to pay for an American
vacation. It also has stopped issuing visas assigned just to ``the
bearer'' and requires photographs with each application. All this
has slowed the process.
   ``The prime duty of a consular officer is to make sure
foreigners do not get into the United States under fraudulent
pretenses,'' Bishop said. ``On the other hand, U.S. policy is to
facilitate matters for legitimate tourists who want to visit our
country. So we have to carefully go over each request.''
   The travel agents have proposed, and the Consulate is
considering, separate visa handling, en masse, two days a week for
Brazilian passports submitted by registered travel agencies.
   The travel agents association has promised to police its own
ranks.
   Dalsenter, the association's president, maintained the travel
agencies' proposal would reduce the confusion in the visa lines and
discourage the selling of places.
   Bishop said, ``We have heard reports of money changing hands out
there, but we have no concrete proof.''
   ``It goes on every day,'' Dalsenter said. ``Everybody knows it.''
   On the day an Associated Press reporter and photographer arrived
at the Consulate at 4 a.m., no one on line would agree to be
interviewed or give his or her name. Many turned their backs or
covered up documents they were holding.
   A Brazilian policeman then came by and chased away the
photographer, citing reasons of ``security.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, March 7</NOTE>
