<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TVWeek Adv13   02-29 0840</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--TV Week, Adv 13,0860</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Kirk Douglas says he learned just how
controversial ``Inherit the Wind'' is when the movie company was
turned away from filming at a private school in Oregon.
   ``This is a play about the Scopes Monkey Trial in 1925, but the
issue is as relevant today as it was then,'' he says.
   ``The best example of that came when we planned to shoot a scene
in a schoolhouse in a small town in Oregon. We had made
arrangements with the school's board to film scenes of the young
teacher teaching Darwin's theory of evolution. But when they found
out what we were going to film they threw us out. They said they
only teach Biblical creationism.''
   Douglas, Jason Robards, Jean Simmons and Darren McGavin star in
the new two-hour production of ``Inherit the Wind.'' David Greene
directed from a screenplay by John Gay, based on the play by Jerome
Lawrence and Robert E. Lee.
   Douglas plays Matthew Harrison Brady, a brilliant orator and
fundamentalist politician invited to prosecute a teacher for
bringing Darwin's theory into the classroom. Robards is Henry
Drummond, a liberal lawyer who defends the teacher. Simmons is
Brady's wife and McGavin is a cynical reporter named E.K. Hornbeck.
   The play, of course, is based on the trial of John Scopes in
Tennessee. Brady is really William Jennings Bryan, the three-time
Democratic presidential nominee. Drummond is Clarence Darrow and
Hornbeck is H.L. Mencken. It was made into a movie in 1960 with
Spencer Tracy as Drummond, Frederic March as Brady and Gene Kelly
as Hornbeck.
   ``It's interesting for an actor to play a role with a point of
view you don't believe in,'' Douglas says. ``I think he was very
sincere. He wasn't a charlatan, he wasn't a buffoon. He believed
every word in the Bible should be accepted as it was written.
   ``That's what creates the dramatic friction between my character
and Jason Robards'. They were both sincere in their beliefs. The
pathetic quality which we develop is that these two men had been
friends. Clarence Darrow had backed Bryan in his first run for the
presidency. It's touching because these two men are now bitter
enemies.''
   Douglas says he wasn't interested when his son, Peter, the
executive producer, first brought the idea to him. He didn't want
to do a remake of the movie, in which Brady was more buffoonish.
   ``I never thought he should be played as a fool,'' he says. ``I
played him as a mixture of Pat Robertson, Billy Graham and Jimmy
Swaggart. Brady wasn't gluttonous and eating all the time, the way
he was in the movie.''
   He also began to see how relevant the subject was because of the
ongoing debate, evolution vs. creationism.
   The time of the trial was also moved to the fall.
   ``In the movie you see a hundred extras fanning away because of
the summer heat,'' Douglas says. ``We didn't want that. We also
went back to the original trial transcript and picked up a few
things. Brady dies in the courtroom, but in reality Bryan died five
days after the trial ended. The play was never an attempt to be
exact history.''
   ``Inherit the Wind'' is Douglas' second movie with son Peter.
The first was called ``Amos,'' which was set in a home for the
elderly.
   ``That's the exciting thing about doing movies for television,''
he says. ``You can deal with subjects you can't do for theatrical
films. Theatrical films seem to fall into certain formulas _ wild
comedies, violence or young kids finding out about sex.
   ``On television you can do something with substance. This is the
first program in the new `AT&T Presents' series. What I like about
that is that we have fewer commercial breaks.''
   Douglas' last theatrical film was ``Tough Guys,'' which also
starred Burt Lancaster.
   ``I've got several projects pending, but I've been devoting my
time to my autobiography,'' he says. ``I've just finished it and
Simon & Schuster will publish it. It was interesting to write, like
taking a self-inventory. It was hard work. I found it painful. I
wrote it by myself.
   ``One of my motivations for the book is that I have four sons.
I'll say something and one of them will say, `Gee, Dad, I didn't
know that.' I think this book is my chance to say who I am.''
   Douglas believes that the public has a different image than the
one he has of himself.
   ``Before `Champion' in 1949 I'd played an intellectual
schoolteacher, a weak schoolteacher and an alcoholic. After
`Champion,' I was a tough guy. I did things like playing van Gogh,
but the image lingers. That's one of the things I loved about
`Inherit the Wind.' It was a battle of ideas rather than of
physical violence.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
