<1ST_LINE>s e BC-APN--TheaterWeek Adv13   02-29 0918</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Theater Week, Adv 13,0940</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv13</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Second Stage has devoted an entire theater
season to the plays of Michael Weller, a rare honor for playwrights
these days.
   Since November, the enterprising off-Broadway company has
presented ``Moonchildren'' and ``Loose Ends,'' two of Weller's
best-known efforts. In April, it will offer the world premiere of
his latest drama, ``Spoils of War,'' at the troupe's small theater
in what was once an old gymnasium on the Upper West Side.
   And in between there will be staged readings of other Weller
plays, panel discussions about Weller and his work and viewings of
``Ragtime'' and ``Hair,'' two movies for which Weller wrote the
screenplays.
   For Weller, the Second Stage celebration is a homecoming of
sorts. Since its start nine years ago, the company, which
specializes in second looks at plays that may not have been
successful the first time around, has been receptive to the
playwright's writing.
   ``Mike is one of the people who started the theater with us,''
remembers Robyn Goodman, one of the company's two artistic
directors. ``He was one of the first people to write a play for
us.''
   And he's doing it again this year. ``Spoils of War,'' the story
of a mother and son in the 1950s, was commissioned by Goodman and
her Second Stage partner, Carole Rothman. Kate Nelligan plays the
mother.
   ``One of the enticements in writing a new play was that Mike
would be cushioned to a certain extent by having his other plays
done during the same season,'' Rothman says. ``New York has kind of
a hit-or-miss mentality. With our current season, people will be
able to see a body of work. It's not as frightening for a
playwright to premiere a new play when it's surrounded by plays
that have been done before.''
   The object of these theatrical festivities is a boyish,
45-year-old writer who does his writing out of an East Village
studio.
   The man is surprisingly low-keyed, considering he is under
deadline to get ``Spoils of War'' finished before it goes into
rehearsal and considering he is juggling phone calls from Texas
where his latest screenplay actually has gone into production. It's
a movie _ as yet untitled _ directed by Hugh Hudson and starring
Donald Sutherland and Adam Horovitz of Beastie Boys fame.
   ``The film is about kids whose parents don't supervise them too
much,'' Weller says. ``The movie follows one boy through his
adventures with a gang and getting into trouble with the law.''
   He had no problem taking a new look at his old plays and was
closely involved with the casting and directing of each revival.
Weller found the experience a pleasant one and didn't feel
compelled to rewrite what he had written years ago.
   ``It's like going into your old neighborhood again,'' Weller
says. ``I usually work out of a real emotional knot and once that's
untied, I don't feel much inclination to go back to a play.''
   ``Moonchildren,'' a look at college students in the 1960s at the
beginning of the Vietnam War protests, was his biggest success. It
flopped on Broadway in 1972 but had a successful off-Broadway run
the following year and has been a staple of regional theaters and
acting classes ever since.
   ``Loose Ends'' examined the same generation 10 years later, when
they were struggling to sort out their lives and loves. It was a
harder play to write, Weller says.
   ``For one thing, I knew more,'' Weller says. ``The more
deliberate you are in your writing, the harder it is. When you're a
kid, you think no one's ever done this before. But the next time,
you realize it's been done a million times.''
   Weller didn't start out to be a writer. He wanted to be a
composer and studied music composition at Brandeis.
   ``I wasn't a good musician,'' he admits, but when an opportunity
came up to write a college musical, he enrolled in a playwriting
course. Writing eventually took precedence over composing and
Weller went off to England to study playwriting before eventually
coming back to the United States.
   A handwritten copy of ``Spoils of War'' lies on the desk in
Weller's study. The penmanship is small and precise.
   ``I write quite a bit every day but I hardly use any of it,''
the playwright says. ``I keep going back and poring over it,
pulling things out. In that way, I am very slow to select what I'm
finally going to use.''
   Weller's parents were both painters, so artistic discipline was
in his blood. And success wasn't what counted the most.
   ``I saw people who went off to their workshop every day and
painted,'' he recalls. ``For some of them, the glory train came in
and for others, it didn't. You couldn't allow that to hinder your
daily output. You couldn't allow yourself to get thrown by it.''
   For that reason, Weller, when he isn't helping take care of his
young son, keeps to a rigid writing schedule. He jots down in
notebooks ideas and notes for projects he will get to when he has
time.
   ``I think the only hard lesson is not to have any big
expectations,'' he says. ``Just concentrate on what you are doing
and get it right.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
