<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1353EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Spotlight-FrenchJews Adv06-2Takes   02-29 1064</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Spotlight-French Jews, Adv 06-2 Takes,1088</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: French Jews _ A New Era of Pride</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, the main story of a package of three.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Nazi occupation in World War II and a
lingering anti-Semitism left the Jews of France in disorder and
disarray _ so much so that many renounced their heritage and took
French names. But more recent years have seen a rebirth of Jewry in
a nation that is largely Roman Catholic, and a new era for Jews has
set in.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BY MARILYN AUGUST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friday is a busy day on the rue des Rosiers, a
narrow street in the heart of Paris' oldest Jewish quarter. It is
there that shoppers preparing for the Sabbath find everything from
kosher chickens to prayer books and sacramental wines.
   This colorful neighborhood, and many others like it throughout
predominantly Roman Catholic France, have come alive again as the
Jewish community revels in a new era of Jewish pride and an upsurge
of Judaism.
   Traumatized by World War II, which saw the virtual dismantling
of French Jewry and the deportation of some 117,000 Jews to Nazi
gas chambers, the community of guilt-ridden survivors lived in fear
of anti-Semitism and new persecutions.
   Many renounced their Jewish identities, changing their names,
refusing to circumcize newborn boys as prescribed by their faith or
to give their children Jewish educations.
   Today, those are just bad memories.
   Jews again are playing major roles in the upper levels of French
life _ government, industry, the intelligentsia, entertainment and
the media.
   The change is largely due to the 150,000 Sephardic Jews from
Algeria, Morocco and Tunisia who poured in during the 1950s and
1960s as the French colonies in North Africa gained independence.
   The Sephardim are Jews who originated in Spain in the Middle
Ages and who migrated to North Africa after the Spanish Inquisition
in 1492. Many also moved to the Middle East and the term now refers
to all Jews who are not of Askenazic, or Eastern European, origin.
   The Sephardim make up more than 60 percent of France's
population of 650,000 Jews, the world's fourth-largest Jewish
community after the United States, Israel and the Soviet Union.
   No one was as startled as today's Sephardic Jewish community
when word came from Washington earlier this year that they were
considered wretched enough to warrant $8 million in emergency
relief from the United States.
   Sen. Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii, one of the measure's
congressional backers, said the money for schools for North African
Jews in Paris was earmarked for ``these unfortunates, these Jews .
.. who have not been absorbed or assimilated.''
   The American funding, later cancelled by Congress, was to build
schools for Ozar Hatorah, a non-profit organization that promotes
education, assistance and charity in 20 countries.
   ``Globally, you can say that the integration of North African
Jews into French society has been a real success story,'' said
Emile Touati, director of Consistoire, the religious governing body
for French Jews.
   Besides their own folklore, culinary habits, tight-knit family
stucture and so-called ``Mediterranean mentality,'' North African
Jews brought their unconditional devotion to Judaism and a demand
for Jewish culture.
   In the past 15 years, the number of synagogues in the Paris
region has increased from 30 to 70. In 1950, Paris had just three
kosher butchers; today they number more than 100.
   Touati says it has become virtually impossible to keep track of
the dozens of restaurants, grocery stores, professional caterers,
supermarkets and fast-food outlets serving kosher fare. Before the
coming of the Sephardim, there were virtually none.
   ``There was a time when you couldn't even find a bottle of
kosher wine for the Sabbath meal,'' Touati said in an interview.
``Now, the finest chateaux in Burgundy, Bordeaux and Champagne
produce kosher wines which we export all over the world.''
   The ``pletzl'' in the Marais, a ghetto-like haven for poor
Askenazic Jews since the Middle Ages, has seen an influx of
Sephardim too, and the shops that once sold chopped liver and
gefilte fish have been joined by fast-food joints serving falafel
and kosher couscous.
   ``These places are filled with young people looking for their
Jewish identity and a sense of community,'' said Eric Ghebeli,
fomer president of France's Jewish Student Union. ``They are
mini-cultural centers where people get together to enjoy a dish
their mothers once made. But there is also a thirst for knowledge.''
   Enrollment in Jewish schools is higher than ever, with 10
percent of school-age children, about 15,000 enrolled full-time in
one of France's 33 Jewish schools. An equal number attend Sunday
school.
   A century ago the watchword was assimilation. Today, it is the
preservation of Jewishness among France's 55.5 million people. The
Lucien de Hirch school, founded in the early 1900s to help new
immigrants adapt to French life, has done an about face: today it
teaches the principles of Judaism to its 850 students, 75 percent
of whom are North African Sephardim.
   Since the arrival of the Sephardim, more than 6,000 study
groups, with different goals and religious tendencies, have sprung
up around the country, along with countless adult education courses
teaching Hebrew and Yiddish.
   In a country where Jews have long believed that flaunting their
Jewishness was asking for trouble, the Lubavitch, ultra-orthodox
Hasidic Jews originating in 18th century Poland, have seen their
memberships swell, thanks to new Sephardic recruits.
   Dressed in long black coats, wearing beards and earlocks, some
have even learned Yiddish to read in the original the works of
Rabbi Menachem Mendel Schneerson, head of the sect who lives in the
Brownsville section of Brooklyn, N.Y. In December they plastered
billboards around Paris with posters telling Jews to light Hanukkah
candles and installed a giant menorah at the Place de la Concorde.
   Jews around France can tune in to any of 13 radio stations
playing Hebrew and Yiddish songs and broadcasting cultural programs
and news commentaries. The three Paris stations claim a daily
audience of 37,000.
   Jewish publications also have more readers than ever. Numerous
weeklies are distributed free in Jewish centers and shops. The
monthly ``L'Arche,'' geared to France's educated middle class,
reaches 10,000 subscribers. It was joined in December by
``Passages,'' a magazine offering what it calls a Jewish point of
view on the news.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1354EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Spotlight-FrenchJews Adv06-1stadd   02-29 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Spotlight-French Jews, Adv 06-1st add,0713</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, March 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>PARIS: the news.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Jewish community as a whole has been deeply troubled by the
recent events on the Israeli-occupied West Bank in the Middle East.
   ``We deplore the violence, but our support of Israel is
unconditional,'' said Roger Pinto, president of SIONA, a Zionist
group made up of North African Sephardim. ``Unlike many Askenazim,
we support Israel first, and then ask questions.''
   In a recent statement, an umbrella organization of Jewish
institutions known as CRIF, reiterated its support of Israel and
condemned its Arab neighbors for ``refusing a real and useful
dialogue ... to solve the problems of the region.''
   In an editorial in the monthly ``Information Juive,'' the
Consistoire's Touati asked, ``Under the circumstances, what army in
the world would have behaved better than Tsahal (the Israeli
army)?''
   Nonetheless, nearly a dozen Jewish groups have publicly called
for a peaceful and political solution to the violence.
   (The French government strives for even-handedness in relations
with Israel and the Arab nations of the Middle East, where
historical ties translate today into what France considers
``special relationships'' with several of the Arab nations. France
supports the convening of an international conference with all
parties represented to resolve the Middle East conflict.)
   Many French intellectuals of Jewish origin have begun
identifying with Judaism, some for the first time.
   Benny Levy, militant founder of the Proletarian Left and close
friend and secretary of the author-philosopher Jean-Paul Sartre in
the years before his death, has abandoned politics completely and
embraced a life of piety and study of the Torah, Judaism's Holy
Scriptures.
   Philosopher Jacques Derrida, the father of Deconstruction, a
textual analysis based on the theory that language refers to
itself, has been discussing Jewish and Biblical themes in seminars
at the elite Ecole Normale Superieure and at Yale University in New
Haven, Conn., for several years.
   Intellectuals Bernard-Henri Levy, Andre Gluckmann and Alain
Finkielkraut, once committed leftists and later the major force
behind the New Philosophy movement of the mid-1970s, are among
France's most visible Jews, publicly rediscovering their Jewish
roots, writing on Jewish issues and supporting Jewish causes.
   But for Joseph Sitruk, France's newly installed Grand Rabbi,
they are hardly examples of what he calls in Hebrew ``teshuva,'' or
return.
   ``Many of them are interested in Judaism the same way they would
be interested in Buddhism or Leninism,'' he said in an interview.
``They may be going through an identity crisis, and that's
respectable, but they're not calling themselves into question and
going all the way.''
   Rabbi Michael Williams, of the ``liberal'' Copernic synagogue,
said he understands the cyncism of the religious establishment.
   ``How can the so-called return be anything but superficial when
its standard-bearers don't respect the very basic rules of Judaism,
and marry out?''
   Williams maintains that French Jews are ``going through an
intense crisis of love.'' He says he regularly meets with observant
young people planning to marry Gentiles.
   Indeed, studies show that intermarriage is on the rise, at about
50 percent. Among the Sephardim, the figures are only slightly
lower.
   ``The family structure among North African Jews is still quite
strong, and plays an important role in influencing decisions made
by family members,'' Touati said. ``The increase in intermarriage
is one of the consequences of rapid assimilation and integration
into French society.''
   Yet Sitruk maintains the current upsurge in Judaism is not
superficial but profound, touching all classes and backrounds, rich
and poor.
   ``It comes in the wake of the Holocaust, the birth of the state
of Israel, the new positions of power held by Jews worldwide and
the profound and far-reaching need to identify with the Jewish
Biblical message,'' Sitruk said.
   Reform Jews too, have been swept up in the trend towards
orthodoxy. Five years ago, Friday night services at Copernic,
France's largest reform community, were mostly in French. Today,
three-quarters of the service is in Hebrew.
   ``There is definitely an unspoken demand for a return to Jewish
knowledge and values,'' Williams said. ``But we must be careful
that it doesn't come at the expense of a new ghetto-like
mentality.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
