<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0544</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western banks and Brazil have reached agreement
on important elements of a loan restructuring package for the Third
World's most indebted country, providing it with more money at
lower interest rates.
   Banking sources familiar with the agreement say the negotiations
reflected a surprising level of cooperation from Brazil, which last
year toughened its position over loan repayment terms and aroused
considerable concern in the banking industry.
   Fernando Milliet, president of Brazil's central bank, and
William R. Rhodes, chairman of the Bank Advisory Committee for
Brazil, said Sunday that under the agreement reached in New York,
Brazil will get more than $6 billion in new financing to help make
debt payments through the first half of 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy has shrugged off the worst
effects of the October stock market collapse and should be able to
escape a recession this election year, economists for top U.S.
corporations predicted today.
   The National Association of Business Economists said optimism
among its members has risen appreciably since the last survey
conducted in the month following the Oct. 19 plunge in stock prices.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose a moderate 0.3 percent in
January, but a decline in energy costs cloaked increases in many
other areas, the government said.
   The January increase reported Friday in the Labor Department's
Consumer Price Index followed a revised December increase of 0.2
percent. The December rise initially been reported as 0.1 percent.
   The advance equaled an annual inflation rate of 4.2 percent.
That compares with the 4.4 percent rate of inflation in 1987 and
with the Reagan administration's projection of 4.3 percent
inflation for 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of existing single-family homes suffered
their third consecutive monthly decline in January, a 3.6 percent
drop which pushed activity to its slowest level in 2{ years,
according to a real estate trade group.
   The National Association of Realtors said Friday that sales
dropped to a seasonally-adjusted annual rate of 3.21 million units
last month, following declines of 1.2 percent in December and 2.9
percent in November.
   The association said consumer fears raised by the collapse of
the stock market in October partly caused the slowdown.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' incomes rose 0.3 percent in
January, matching the gain in consumer spending during the month,
the government has reported.
   The Commerce Department said Friday the 0.3 percent rises in
incomes and spending followed identical 0.7 percent advances in
both categories during December.
   The gains were taken as positive signs that consumer spending
will grow enough this year to prevent a recession.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of newly started construction fell 8
percent in January from the previous month, led by a steep drop in
non-residential buildings, according to a report by a construction
research concern.
   The F.W. Dodge division of McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co.
said Sunday the latest decline continued a downward drift from
highs reached last August.
   The report said the annualized value of new construction
contracts fell to $228 billion in January from $247.3 billion in
December 1987.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
