<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0573</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former stockbroker Peter Brant has been
sentenced to 120 weekends in jail and fined $10,000 for his role in
the insider-trading scandal involving a former Wall Street Journal
reporter.
   U.S. District Judge Charles E. Stewart on Friday also put Brant
on probation for five years and ordered him to do 750 hours of
community service. Brant, 35, a former broker at Kidder Peabody &
Co., pleaded guilty July 12, 1984 to conspiracy and securities
fraud. He admitted his part in a scheme to trade stock based on
information to appear in the Journal's influential ``Heard on the
Street'' column.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. companies surveyed by the government
reported a loss of $23.8 billion in 1986 because of foreign piracy
of U.S. patents, trademarks and copyrights, according to a U.S.
International Trade Commission study.
   The ITC said Friday that actual losses are much greater because
not all companies filled out questionnaires on the subject.
   The commission said it received responses from 431 companies.
The questionnaire was sent to 736 U.S. companies, including all
those on the Fortune 500 list.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Champion Spark Plug Co. plans to lay off
nearly 20 percent of its 1,700 production workers nationwide
because of overcapacity in the auto parts industry.
   The bulk of the cuts announced Friday, which will begin March 22
and will be phased in over the next four months, are being made at
the plant here.
   The layoffs come just one month after workers at four U.S.
Champion plants approved a new four-year contract that includes a
provision that the company try to increase production at two of its
domestic plants.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metromedia Co. has agreed to acquire the
Ponderosa Inc. restaurant chain for an undisclosed amount.
   Metromedia, a privately-held telecommunications and technology
holding company, said Friday it planned to keep Ponderosa
management in place and anticipated no changes in the company's
operation.
   Ponderosa, which was taken private in a $331 million buyout led
by New York investor Asher B. Edelman in January 1987, is one of
the nation's largest steakhouse chains, with annual sales of $500
million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three companies accused of selling thousands of
pounds of non-kosher poultry as kosher to customers in up to 22
states have agreed in a legal settlement to get out of the kosher
business.
   ``We wanted to make sure something like this never happened
again,'' said Rabbi Victor Segal, president of Goldman-Segal Kosher
Caterers of Chicago, which had accused the three companies of fraud
in a federal lawsuit.
   Segal said Friday it was the largest case of fraud involving
mislabeling of kosher foods, and potentially affected Jewish
families in 22 states where the companies' kosher poultry products
were sold.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market closed a choppy week with a small gain in quiet
trading Friday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 5.64
points to 2,023.21, finishing the week with a net gain of 8.62
points.
   Bond prices rose in thin trading.
   The dollar slipped against most major currencies in quiet
trading. Gold prices declined.
   Cocoa futures prices dropped sharply, energy futures mostly were
lower, soybeans rose while grains were mixed, and cattle and pork
futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
