<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankChecksOut     02-29 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Checks Out,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A California County's Only Bank Makes Withdrawal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN GRUBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARKLEEVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Alpine County's main
industries is a silver mine, but neither silver ore nor a gold mine
of ski business are enough to keep the county's only bank from
checking out.
   Bank of America will close its Markleeville branch tonight, 30
years after the county tax collector cajoled the banking giant to
set up shop in California's least populated county.
   The bank says the closure is a cost-cutting move forced by keen
competition following deregulation of the banking industry. It
promises to continue serving Alpine County customers at its South
Lake Tahoe Branch, about 35 miles away.
   The move angers many customers, who lament bygone days when
resident bank managers would open the bank and approve loans after
hours, attend neighborhood potlucks and host an annual holiday
buffet in this Sierra Nevada community.
   They claim the bank would have done well in the county had it
made efforts to secure accounts such as the Kirkwood ski resort and
the Washoe Indian tribe. Now, Alpine is the only one of
California's 58 counties without a bank.
   ``It's not the community failing the bank,'' said Don Jardine,
one of five members of the Alpine County Board of Supervisors.
``It's the bank failing to aggressively go out and just provide
basic services.''
   Corporate spokesman Richard Beebe said ``it's not our intention
to abandon anyone.''
   Beebe said Alpine County clients won't see any interruption in
their accounts and will be able to do much of their banking,
including loan applications, by telephone.
   Although some customers are grumbling they'll bank in Nevada, 20
minutes away by car, the county doesn't have that option.
   State law requires that local governments bank in California.
Alpine county, which has cash assets of $3 million and an annual
budget of $5 million, is considering hiring an armed transport
service for $70 a trip to deposit its money at South Lake Tahoe.
   Dee Rudden, who moved here two years ago from San Jose with her
husband, Bob, and bought the Markleeville General Store, said the
bank's closing ``is really going to be a problem for everyone.
   ``I guess what we're going to do is buy a safe,'' Rudden said.
``We're going to have to do something.''
   In Markleeville, the economy seems as slow as the pace of life.
Welcome signs on the edge of town boast a population of 165 in a
county of 1,200 people. Work is seasonal at the silver mine, four
miles south of town.
   Doranna Tognotti, deputy treasurer-tax collector, said the
estimated $755,00 it would cost to start a new bank in Alpine
County may be prohibitive.
   ``You can't help but wonder if we're going to end up being a
ghost town,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
