<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Mexico-Economy     02-29 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Economy,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goverment Boosts Minimum Wage 3 Percent Under Anti-Inflation Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican government said it would raise by
3 percent the minimum daily wage in March and freeze officially
regulated prices under its inflation-fighting program.
   It also said the value of the peso currency against the dollar
would be maintained in March at the level reached today. The
government had been paring the currency's value by 3 pesos per
trading day.
   ``The national motto is no increase in prices in the month of
March,'' President Miguel de la Madrid said Sunday, in announcing
that the government was stepping up the pace of its anti-inflation
program.
   He said the decision was made after fresh inflation figures
showed ``an important de-acceleration'' in February.
   The inflation tally for February, he said, will be about half
the record 15.5 percent posted in January. Consumer prices rose 8.7
percent in the first half of this month, the government reported
last Wednesday.
   In outlining inflation-fighting steps for March, the
presidential office said the prices of government-produced and
-controlled goods and services, such as gasoline, telephones and
electricity, will be frozen.
   Private companies, it said, will be urged to absorb the increase
in the minimum wage and not pass it along to consumers in the form
of higher prices.
   Moreover, it said, the government will push ahead with plans to
reduce the government's red-ink spending.
   The government had been expected to announce over the weekend a
target for boosting wages and prices in March, under an indexation
plan scheduled to go into effect on Tuesday.
   Under that plan, wages and prices of government-regulated goods
and services were to be increased by a set amount, based on
projected inflation.
   But officials decided instead to raise only the minimum wage,
which will move from 7,765 pesos a day to just under 8,000 pesos,
or about $3.50 at the current exchange rate. The higher pay will go
into effect Tuesday.
   The small increase dealt a setback to labor. Labor officials had
called for a gain of at least 10 percent to help workers keep pace
with the sharp rise in prices in recent months.
   But during a meeting at the presidential office, labor chief
Fidel Velazquez said he believed the fresh steps would help
``attack inflation.'' He said workers had, once again, ``placed the
interests of the country ahead of their own interests.''
   The inflation rate in all of last year was a record 159.2
percent, up sharply from the 105.7 percent of 1986.
   De la Madrid unveiled the anti-inflation program, called the
Economic Solidarity Pact, in mid-December in an effort to prevent
the nation from spinning into hyper-inflation. Officials have
predicted that the plan will reduce the monthly inflation rate to
just 1 percent to 2 percent by year's end.
   As part of the Solidarity Pact, the government authorized sharp
increases in the prices of a variety of officially controlled goods
and services, which kicked up costs throughout the economy.
   The exchange rate on Friday was 2,270 pesos to the dollar in the
controlled market, which is regulated by the government and used in
about 75 percent of commercial transactions.
   The rate in free-market trading, used in tourism and
transactions along the U.S.-Mexico border, was 2,327 pesos to the
dollar.
   In February, the Bank of Mexico, the central bank, sliced the
currency's value by an average of 3 pesos per working day. The rate
had held fairly steady from mid-December to February.
</TEXT>
