<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Scotus-BankTax     02-29 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Bank Tax,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Seeks Administration Opinion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today asked the Reagan
administration for its opinion of a ruling that states indirectly
may tax interest paid to financial institutions from investments in
Federal Home Loan Bank (FHLB) bonds.
   The court said it wants to hear from Justice Department lawyers
before saying whether it will review fully a challenge to a
Maryland bank franchise tax.
   The Maryland National Bank challenged the tax, seeking a refund
of $197,310 it paid under protest to the state for the years 1979
through 1982.
   During that period, the bank reported $2.82 million in interest
from FHLB bonds.
   The sum was included in the bank's net earnings that were
subject to Maryland's franchise tax, which is imposed on financial
institutions for the privilege of doing business in Maryland.
   The difficulty over whether earnings from FHLB bonds are taxable
arises because of two apparently conflicting federal laws.
   The 1932 law that created the FHLB generally exempts the bonds
from taxes.
   But a law enacted in 1862 permits states to levy a
``non-discriminatory franchise tax'' on ``stocks and obligations of
the United States government'' that generally are exempt from state
and local taxes.
   The Maryland Court of Appeals upheld the state franchise tax,
ruling in October that the 1862 law takes precedence.
   The state court based its ruling in part on a 1975 opinion by
the general counsel's office of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   The state court said a franchise tax paid for the privilege of
doing business in the state is not the same as a direct tax on a
bank's income.
   The state court also said the tax does not violate the
Constitution's Supremacy Clause, which binds states to adhere to
federal law.
   The case is Maryland National Bank vs. State Department of
Assessments, 87-1080.
  
</TEXT>
