<2ND_LINE>PM-Fidelity Investments,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fidelity Announces 800 Layoffs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest mutual
fund firm, today announced plans to lay off about 800 workers, with
more than 70 percent of the cuts in its Boston area offices.
   The company attributed the 10.5 percent workforce reduction to a
slump in new stock transactions and slower money management
business since the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
   The layoffs, to take effect immediately, include 530 workers in
Greater Boston, about 150 in Dallas and about 50 in New York, said
Fidelity spokeswoman Karen Ernst.
   The remainder of the cuts will come from other offices around
the country, she said.
   The action reduces Fidelity's nationwide staff to approximately
6,850, about the same number of workers employed by the firm in
mid-1987. Since the early 1980s, Fidelity experienced significant
growth as the economy improved.
   Most of the layoffs were from corporate staff department and
``volume-sensitive'' areas, such as telephone representatives and
order takers, said the corporate announcement. No investment
personnel were effected.
   Fidelity, which operates 54 offices in the United States,
presently manages about $80 billion in assets, down from a peak of
about $85 billion in mid-1987.
   The company dismissed about 300 part-time and 50 fill-time
workers Feb. 11, including 50 in Boston and 125 each in Dallas and
Salt Lake City.
   Earlier this year, Fidelity laid off 32 workers at investment
centers nationwide.
   Among Fidelity's other services include discount stock brokerage
and institutional pension management.
   Eric Kobern, a former Fidelity employee who publishes an
independent newsletter that monitors the company, predicts future
layoffs if business does not accelerate.
   ``This is a first step,'' said Kobern. ``I would not be
surprised if we see further cuts after the IRA season if business
stays at the same pace. This may be the first round of cuts, and
they will digest it and see how they are doing then proceed with
others.''
</TEXT>
