<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dart-Stop&Shop     02-29 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dart-Stop & Shop,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stop & Shop Announces Merger Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITS to add byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stop & Shop Cos. Inc. announced today it would go
private in a $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co. The deal could thwart Dart Group Inc.'s attempt to
take over the supermarket and department store chain.
   The buyout agreement, signed after several days of negotiations
between Stop & Shop directors and several interested firms, calls
for a Kohlberg Kravis subsidiary, SSC Holdings Corp., to purchase
all 28 million outstanding Stop & Shop shares at $44 each, Stop &
Shop said in a statement.
   Kohlberg Kravis is an investment company specializing in
management-led acquisitions, including the $6.2 billion leveraged
buyout of Beatrice Cos. in 1986. In a leveraged buyout, investors
borrow heavily to buy out a company and then pay off the debt with
the target company's cash flow or the sale of its assets.
   Stop & Shop's board had rejected as inadequate Dart's offer of
$37 a share, or a total of $1.03 billion.
   Officials of Dart could not be reached for comment today, but a
spokesman had said they would likely make a counter offer.
   Other companies reportedly interested in Stop & Shop were Thomas
H. Lee Co. of Boston, and Riordan, Freeman & Spogli Inc. of Los
Angeles.
   Stop & Shop has 113 supermarkets and 169 Bradlees in 12 states
in the Northeast.
   The company's stock has gone up more than $25 a share since Dart
first announced its takeover intent in January. In early New York
Stock Exchange trading today, it was up another 75 cents to $43.37{
a share.
   The sale, which must be approved by a majority of Stop & Shop
shareholders, is expected to commence on or before March 4, Stop &
Shop said. Kohlberg Kravis has received a financing commitment from
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co., the retailer said.
   Stop & Shop said it will retain its present management and
remain based in Braintree.
   On Friday, Dart said it would launch a proxy fight and called
for a special meeting of Stop & Shop shareholders at which it would
move to replace the directors.
   Dart, based in Landover, Md., is known for a series of
unsuccessful but profitable bids to gain control of other
companies, and its chairman, Herbert Haft, and president, Robert
Haft, have acquired reputations as corporate raiders.
   Their most recent targets include Supermarkets General Corp. and
Dayton Hudson Corp.
</TEXT>
