<1ST_LINE>r f BC-HoustonBankruptcies     02-29 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Houston Bankruptcies,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Houston Business Bankruptcies Hit High Last Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of local businesses bankruptcies
reached an all-time high in 1987, and increased for the fifth
consecutive year, according to an accounting firm's report.
   There were a record 1,688 bankruptcies in Houston last year, a 4
percent increase from the previous year, a Price Waterhouse-Houston
study showed. The small percentage increase indicates a
stabilization of the business climate, the company said.
   Price Waterhouse said the number of bankruptcies increased by 17
percent in 1986 and 33 percent in 1985.
   ``We expect bankruptcies in Houston to decline in 1988,'' said
Carol Bennett, senior manager and economist with Price Waterhouse.
``Such a decline would be the first we have reported since we began
these bankruptcy analyses in 1982.''
   In its survey last year, the company predicted Houston
bankruptcies had peaked in 1986.
   Retail businesses represented the largest industry segment in
the bankruptcy figures with a 41.5 percent share, the study said.
   But the beleaguered oil and gas industry improved dramatically
in its survival statistics, showing a 53 pecent decrease in
business failures and bankruptcy filings last year compared with
1986. The 59 filings in the energy sector last year were the fewest
since 1982.
</TEXT>
