<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Federated-Campeau     02-29 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated-Campeau,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federated Says It Has New Suitor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The possibility of a bidding war for Federated
Department Stores Inc. arose today after the nation's fifth-largest
retailer announced that another party in addition to Campeau Corp.
was presenting an acquisition proposal to the Federated board.
   Federated did not identify the new bidder, but said it had been
advised that the party planned to submit a proposal that appeared
competitive with Campeau's $6.1 billion, $68-per-share bid to buy
Federated.
   Federated's board of directors, meeting today to consider
Campeau's proposal, was to consider the rival bid as well, the
retailer said.
   The Cincinnati-based Federated, which owns chains including
Bloomingdale's, Filene's and Burdine's, declined to say where the
board was meeting, or when it would announce a decision.
   Representatives of Federated and Campeau negotiated over the
weekend on a merger plan. However, the retailer said last week
there was no guarantee its directors would agree to a merger with
Campeau, which owns store chains including Jordan Marsh, Ann Taylor
and Stern's.
   Federated stock was up $1.50 to $66.25 a share in late morning
trading on the New York Stock Exchange today.
   Federated ended weeks of fending off Campeau's takeover attempts
by announcing Friday that its board of directors authorized merger
negotiations after the Toronto-based development company offered
$68 per share.
   The directors previously rejected lower Campeau offers and
ordered managers to study alternatives to a takeover.
   Analysts speculated that Federated decided to negotiate with
Campeau because it could not find a favored buyer to acquire the
company or develop a restructuring plan that would pay shareholders
what Campeau was offering.
   Most analysts said that if an agreement was reached, Campeau
probably would sell some Federated divisions to help pay off the
$4.5 billion in debt it would incur to make the acquisition.
   Campeau took similar steps after acquiring Allied Stores Corp.
in December 1986 and sold off 16 of 24 store units.
   Campeau has already indicated it would sell Federated's
non-department store operations, which include Gold Circle discount
stores based in Columbus and Ralph's supermarkets in Los Angeles.
It indicated it would combine headquarters operations of Federated
and Allied Stores.
   Some analysts said the Cincinnati-based Lazarus department store
chain is considered among Federated's weaker performing units and
could be sold.
   There have been rumors that a number of other retailers, such as
May Department Stores, would step in and buy Federated. William
Smith, a retail analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co., said
St. Louis-based May would be interested in acquiring some of
Federated's stores, ``but they don't have to buy the whole company
to do that.''
   Federated had $11 billion in sales last year. It operates 650
stores nationwide. Its holdings also include Abraham & Straus,
Rich's, Bullock's and Bullocks Wilshire and I. Magnin.
   Campeau said last week it would raise a substantial amount of
equity for its proposed buyout of Federated by selling the Brooks
Brothers division of Allied Stores to Britain's Marks and Spencer
PLC for $770 million. The Brooks Brothers sale was conditioned on
Campeau acquiring Federated.
</TEXT>
