<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Trade     02-29 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Trade,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain's Trade Deficit Soars 33 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit soared 33
percent to a record 1.5 billion pounds in January as exports fell
more sharply than imports, the government said Monday.
   The latest seasonally adjusted figure, equal to about $2.7
billion, compared with a deficit of 1.01 billion pounds in the
previous month and 597 million pounds in January 1987, the
Department of Trade and Industry said.
   Britain's current account deficit, which includes invisible
trade such as services and overseas investment earnings, more than
doubled to a record 905 million pounds, or $1.6 billion, in January
from a deficit of 410 million pounds in December.
   The current account deficit was 28 million pounds in January
1987.
   The invisible trade in Janaury was estimated to be in a surplus
of 600 million pounds.
   Exports fell 9 percent to 6.2 billion pounds, or $11 billion, in
January from 6.8 billion pounds, or $12 billion, in December.
   Imports fell 1.3 percent to 7.7 billion pounds, or $13.6
billion, from 7.8 billion pounds, or $13.8 billion, in December.
</TEXT>
