<DOCNO> AP880229-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Norway-Wages     02-29 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Norway-Wages,0372</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Wage Freeze Proposed</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway's Labor government proposed a wage
freeze Monday in an emergency measure to put a lid on inflation,
which leaped to 8.7 percent last year.
   The government said the freeze, which also covered stock
dividends, would be temporary until economic planners can prepare a
more comprehensive program to regulate salaries.
   The second stage was due to be introduced in about two weeks and
would keep salaries under control at least until 1989.
   Norway's inflation rate has grown steadily over the past three
years, from 5.7 percent in 1985 to 7.2 percent in 1986 and 8.7
percent last year. By comparison, the average rate in European in
1986 was 3.8 percent, according to the Organization of European
Cooperation and Development.
   Under the proposed bill, prices would be controled but not
frozen. An already existing monitoring agency would be instructed
to ensure prices were not raised unreasonably.
   It was the most extreme anti-inflation measure since another
socialist government froze prices and wages ten years ago.
   On Saturday, Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland said she would
introduce the wage legislation after the national employers'
organization closed a deal with the country's federation of trade
unions giving workers wage increases and benefits amounting to
roughly five percent.
   The agreement affected 350,000 union members in the private
sector, but the proposed wage freeze would extend the agreement to
most of Norway's work force.
   The bill raised a cry of protest from other unions that their
own negotiations were cut off and superceded by a deal in which
they had no say.
   Exemptions were made for teachers and nurses, who have staged
sporadic strikes over the past several weeks and who were holding
separate pay negotiations.
   Although Mrs. Brundtland's government lacks a majority in the
157-member parliament, the Storting, the legislation was almost
certain to win approval in a vote later this week with the likely
support of the opposition Conservative Party.
   Mrs. Brundtland told a news conference the bill was designed to
bring inflation down to the level of other European countries and
make Norway's industry more competative.
</TEXT>
