<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Diamond-Obie 1stLd-Writethru f0094 02-29 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diamond-Obie, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0094,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Financial Company Executives Sentenced to Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Greenberg, graf 2; also moving on
general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two financial company executives were
sentenced to prison today for their roles in bilking mortgage
company investors of millions of dollars.
   Oakland County Circuit Judge Norman L. Lippitt sentenced Barton
Greenberg to the maximum six years, eight months to 10 years in
prison, and sentenced Gary L. Mitchell to 16 months to three years
in prison.
   Scattered applause broke out as the two former executives of
A.J. Obie & Associates and Diamond Mortgage Corp. were led away in
handcuffs.
   Lippitt gave the two 56 days to appeal.
   The pair were accused of defrauding 1,600 investors of about $47
million in what state Attorney General Frank Kelley has termed
Michigan's largest mortgage scam.
   Greenberg and Mitchell were charged last year with 18 counts of
securities fraud. Greenberg also was charged with two counts of
obtaining money under false pretenses.
   In a plea bargain arranged before trial, Greenberg pleaded no
contest to one count of obtaining money under false pretenses and
Mitchell no contest to a count of securities fraud. The other
counts were dropped.
   Kelley has said that Greenberg, former board chairman of Diamond
and former Obie president, used corporate accounts for personal
purposes while drawing a $1 million annual salary.
   Mitchell owned no stock in either company, had little control
over bank accounts and drew a $100,000 annual salary, Kelley wrote
Lippitt in a letter last week. Kelley said while Mitchell knew of
two of the fraud schemes, he was not the primary instigator and did
not benefit nearly as much as Greenberg.
   Diamond and Obie were charged with arranging high-risk mortgage
loans at above-market rates that Obie then resold to investors.
   Because they had more investors than borrowers, Obie frequently
gave individual mortgages to several investors. Diamond also was
accused of failing to account properly for escrow money to pay
taxes and insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-HuttonScam     02-29 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hutton Scam,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former E.F. Hutton President Agrees To Censure By Stock Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
has agreed to a censure by the New York Stock Exchange for failing
to oversee E.F. Hutton & Co. properly when he was president of that
firm during an illicit overdrafting scheme, sources familiar with
the settlement said Monday.
   The sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified, said
the exchange determined George L. Ball wasn't aware of the scheme,
which was conducted in the early 1980s and played a role in
Hutton's later demise. But the exchange felt Ball still bore some
responsibility, the sources said.
   Hutton's former chief financial officer Thomas Lynch also will
be censured, and Hutton must pay a $400,000 fine to the exchange,
among the largest ever levied, the sources said. Because Hutton was
acquired by Shearson Lehman Brothers Inc. late last year, Shearson
will pay the fine.
   Norman Epstein, a former Hutton executive responsible for
overseeing some of its operations, also faced discipline by the
exchange but reportedly has been resisting a settlement.
   Ball was away from his office and did not return telephone
messages for comment, but a Prudential-Bache official said the
chairman agreed to the settlement in order to put the matter behind
him.
   ``This is the mildest form of action available to the
exchange,'' said the official. ``There is no fine, no restrictions,
it's a censure.''
   The action by stock exchange investigators is regarded as
largely inconsequential. It isn't expected to have any effect on
Ball's position at Prudential Bache.
   ``What they're saying is, `We realize and acknowledge you
weren't aware of any of the improprieties,'' the Prudential Bache
official said.
   Stock exchange spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin declined comment in
accordance with its policy on investigations that haven't been
concluded.
   Shearson officials did not return calls for comment, and the
whereabouts of Lynch and Epstein weren't clear.
   Shearson has said previously that in acquiring Hutton, it
scrutinized the firm's legal history and potential liabilities.
   The exchange's investigation stemmed from a 1985
check-overdrafting scheme that Hutton orchestrated through its
retail brokerage network. The firm earned up to $8 million in
interest income at commercial banks by deliberately overdrawing
checking accounts and putting the money to use elsewhere.
   Hutton pleaded guilty to 2,000 federal fraud counts and paid a
$2 million fine in May 1985 because of the scheme, which exposed
serious management lapses at the firm and led to a chain of events
that forced Hutton to sell itself.
   Ball departed Hutton for Prudential-Bache in 1982, after a
federal probe of the overdrafting scheme had begun.
   The stock exchange routinely disciplines member firms for
violating its rules of conduct, with punitive actions ranging from
expulsions for severe infractions to fines or censure for less
serious offenses.
   Previous large fines levied by the stock exchange included
$400,000 against First Wall Street Settlement in 1981 and $400,000
against Bache Halsey Stuart Shields in 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
