<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Belgium-SocieteGenerale     02-29 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Belgium-Societe Generale,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>De Benedetti Announces Partnership with Two Belgian Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlo De Benedetti reached a
partnership agreement with two Belgian firms Monday, bringing the
Italian investor closer to gaining control of Societe Generale de
Belgique SA, Belgium's biggest holding company.
   De Benedetti, Belgian industrialist Andre Leysen of Gevaert NV
and Pierre Scohier of Cobepa SA, a Belgian investment firm, said
they agreed to form a new holding company with 4.5 million, or
about 16 percent, of Societe Generale shares.
   The group's aim is to control a stake of 20 to 25 percent of
Societe Generale shares, Scohier said.
   De Benedetti, together with allies, already claims to control 45
percent of Societe Generale's 28.2 million shares but it was
unclear Monday whether the new partnership could give him a
majority stake in the company at the expense of an alliance of
mainly French and Belgian companies that claims 52 percent of the
shares.
   The alliance, built around the French investment Cie Financiere
de Suez and Belgium's biggest insurer, Groupe AG, wants to keep
Societe Generale, which has a stake in a third of the Belgian
economy, anchored in Belgium.
   De Benedetti wants to use the 166-year-old firm as a platform
for a pan-European holding company.
   But in the deal with the two Belgian companies he seemed more
willing to let Societe Generale maintain its Belgian identity.
   De Benedetti's French investment firm Cerus SA will have a stake
of 55 percent in the new holding company and Gevaert and Cobepa
holdings of 22.5 percent each.
   Scohier said Copeba, the Belgian subsidiary of the French
investment group Paribas, currently did not own shares of Societe
Generale, but that it planned to buy about 1 million. He did not
elaborate.
   Paribas and Suez are fierce competitors on the French investment
market and are in opposing camps in the battle of Societe Generale.
   The three parties said in a statement the new holding company
will ensure that Societe Generale will have a Belgian base and
invited other Belgian as well as international investors to join
the holding company.
   Societe Generale has interests in some 1,400 companies
world-wide and in about half of Belgium's top 50 firms. It has such
pervasive influence in the national economy that it is sometimes
identified with Belgium itself.
   Leysen told the West German magazine Der Spiegel the importance
of Societe Generale was reflected in its stake in ``all vital
economic sectors of Belgium: the energy sector, gas, electricity,
petroleum and (Belgium's) largest bank.''
   The announcement further said that De Benedetti will be
president of the new holding company with Leysen and Scohier
vice-presidents.
   De Benedetti's insistence on having personal control over at
least day-to-day management of Societe Generale had been a
stumbling block when he failed to forge a partnership with Leysen
last month.
   But the statement released Monday said ``the decision-making
center of the company will remain in Belgium and the essential
interests of Belgium will be preserved,'' which had been a constant
demand by Leysen.
   De Benedetti said prior to Monday's agreement he controlled 45
percent while the alliance opposing him claims 52 percent.
   Maurice Lippens, managing director of Belgium's Groupe AG, said
on Belgian RTBf radio the shareholders meeting would not be called
to assess the size of the two factions trying to take control of
the company.
   Lippens further said he and officials of the Suez group, which
holds the largest single known bloc of shares within the coalition,
had met with Belgium's caretaker prime minister Wilfried Martens
over the weekend.
   No details of the meeting were available.
   The battle for control of Societe Generale started Jan. 18 when
De Benedetti announced he was seeking effective control of the
holding company in view of the completion of the European internal
market of 1992.
   By that date, the Common Market hopes to free all movement of
goods, services and people within the 12-nation European Economic
Community.
</TEXT>
