<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FarmlandValues     02-29 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmland Values,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Shows Continued Improvement In Farmland Values In Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of Midwestern farmland is up
about 7 percent from depressed 1986 levels, but still is little
more than half what it was seven years ago, the Federal Reserve
Bank of Chicago says.
   The bank says its survey of about 500 agricultural bankers in
five Midwestern states shows farmland values rose 3.2 percent
during the last three months of 1987 _ the fourth consecutive
quarterly increase.
   ``The reversal last year of the long downtrend in farmland
values stems largely from the improving income trend of the
sector,'' said Peter Heffernan, an analyst for the Chicago bank.
   Net farm income in 1987 rose 20 percent from the previous year's
level, said Heffernan.
   ``While much of the improvement in farm-sector earnings is
attributable to large government payments, strong livestock returns
over the past few years and sharply curtailed production expenses
have also contributed to the sector's improved income
performance,'' said Heffernan.
   The most substantial increases in farmland values during the
fourth quarter of 1987 were the 5.8 percent reported in Indiana and
4.9 percent in Iowa, the survey showed.
   Illinois bankers reported a 2.1 percent increase in farmland
values during October, November and December, and Wisconsin bankers
reported a 1 percent increase.
   Michigan bankers said there was virtually no change from
third-quarter values.
   Heffernan said the best annual increase in farmland values was
13 percent in Iowa. The others were 8.2 percent in Indiana, 7.2
percent in Illinois and 2 percent in Michigan, with no change
reported by bankers in Wisconsin.
   ``District bankers remain optimistic regarding the farmland
market in 1988,'' said Heffernan. ``The vast majority of surveyed
bankers _ almost 70 percent _ expect farmland values in their areas
to remain stable during the first quarter of this year.''
   He said 28 percent of the bankers expect farmland values to
continue to rise this quarter, while just 2 percent expect a
decline.
   Even with the latest increase in farmland values, the survey
showed that they are 45 percent below their 1981 peak.
</TEXT>
