<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Canada-Strike     02-29 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Strike,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 5,000 Workers Strike Northern Telecom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 Northern Telecom Ltd. production
and office workers went on strike in five Canadian cities Monday
after the union rejected a last-minute economic proposal from the
company.
   ``We are quite a ways apart on some very basic issues,'' said
Bob White, president of the Canadian Auto Workers union.
   White said the company wants to cut cost-of-living allowances by
35 percent and has failed to meet the union's proposal for indexed
pensions. The union is also seeking higher wages and a sweetened
benefit package. Wages now are $15 to $18 an hour.
   The contract expired Sunday at midnight and the strike began
after a deadline of Monday at 11 a.m. EST.
   Affected by the strike are a repair facility in Saint John, New
Brunswick, and manufacturing plants in Ontario at Bramalea,
Belleville, London and Kingston that make wire, cable, telephones
and office telecommunications equipment.
   The company is 52.3 per cent owned by conglomerate BCE, formerly
Bell Canada Enterprises, and has 24 plants and repair operations.
Fourteen of the company's plants are located in the United States.
</TEXT>
