<1ST_LINE>r f BC-RigCount     02-29 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Rig Count,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rig Count Rises By Five To Total 983</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of oil and gas rigs working in the
United States posted a small increase of five this week to total
983, Baker Hughes Inc. announced.
   The total reflects the number of rigs actively exploring for oil
as of last Friday, not the number rigs producing oil. The previous
week, the count had increased by 10 to total 978.
   A year ago, the rig count was 801, Baker Hughes announced Monday.
   Houston-based Baker Hughes, an oil toolmaker, tallies the number
of working rigs and the count is the widely-watched industry index
of drilling activity.
   Hughes Tool Co., which merged this year with Baker International
Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept track of the number of working
rigs since 1940.
   The rig count reached a peak of 4,500 active rigs in December
1981 _ the height of the oil boom. But as oil prices plunged to
less than $10 per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, the count
fell to 663, the lowest since Hughes began compiling figures.
   Among the major oil producing states, Oklahoma gained 12 rigs
this week, followed by Texas with 11, Wyoming with three and
Louisiana with one.
   Michigan's count dropped by seven and Ohio and Colorado each
lost three. Kansas and New Mexico were down by two each, while
Pennsylvania and California each lost one.
</TEXT>
