<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0192</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for corn and soybeans were higher
while wheat prices were mixed at the close Monday in moderate to
good volume on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean prices closed near 7 cents above Friday's prices.
   Lighter than expected delivery notices for soybeans helped
support higher soybeans prices, said Jerry Gidel, grains analyst
for G.H. Miller & Co.
   Wheat prices were supported by import interest from the
Phillippines, 175,000 tons worth, and talk that the Soviets may be
back in the market, Gidel said.
   Corn prices were restained somewhat by lower than expected
exports for that commodity, said Steve Freed, grains analyst with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   At the close, wheat was } cent lower to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.15} a bushel; corn was 2{
cents to 3{ cents higher with March at $2.03\ a bushel; oats were
1} cents to 3{ cents higher with March at $1.93} a bushel; and
soybeans were 4} cents to 7\ cents higher with March at $6.32 a
bushel.
