<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WeeklySteel     02-29 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Steel,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Output Rose 3.1 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production rose to 2.002 million tons in
the week ended Feb. 27, an increase of 3.1 percent from the
previous week's 1.942 million tons, the American Iron and Steel
Institute reported Monday.
   The industry's production amounted to 93.2 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 90.4 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
15.798 million net tons, an increase of 39.7 percent from the
11.308 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations
of USX Corp., the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down
by a strike during the first month of 1987.
   Production so far this year used 88.8 percent of capacity,
compared with 64.1 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended Feb. 27: Northeast
Coast, 285,000; Pittsburgh, 208,000; Youngstown, 125,000; Lake
Erie, 165,000; Detroit, 164,000; Chicago, 539,000; Midwest,
195,000; Southern, 223,000; and Western, 98,000.
</TEXT>
