<1ST_LINE>b b SecurityPacifictoPay$160MillionforHiberniaBonnel.     02-29
0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>Security Pacific to Pay $160 Million for Hibernia Bank</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security Pacific Corp., the nation's
seventh-largest bank holding concern, said Monday it has agreed to
acquire San Francisco-based Hibernia Bank for $160 million, or
about 1{ times its book value.
   Hibernia was put on the auction block by its parent, Hong
Kong-based First Pacific Holdings Ltd., last summer. But after
October's stock market crash, First Pacific said it was no longer
actively seeking a buyer.
   Acquisition of Hibernia will strengthen Los Angeles-based
Security Pacific in the northern part of the state.
   Hibernia, the 13th largest bank in California, has 35 branches
in Northern California, including 28 in the San Francisco Bay Area.
At year end, it had $1.2 billion in deposits and more than $1
billion in outstanding loans. It posted a profit of $11.2 million
last year.
   However, the sale of Hibernia doesn't mark a pullout from
California banking for First Pacific, which will continue to own
smaller United Savings Bank, with operations in the San Francisco
and Los Angeles regions.
   Tom Yasuda, one of First Pacific's directors, said the holding
company's plans call for it to expand United Savings.
   First Pacific also owns a bank in Hong Kong, an
investment-banking concern in the Philippines, and a
trade-confirming operation and minority interest in an
export-finance business in England.
   Security Pacific, whose chief subsidiary is Los Angeles-based
Security Pacific National Bank, the second largest in the state,
has assets of more than $72 billion.
</TEXT>
