<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SantaFe-Subsidiary     02-29 0131</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Fe-Subsidiary,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Santa Fee Closes on Sale of Timber Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Santa Fe Southern Pacific Corp. has completed the
sale of a timber subsidiary to Sierra Pacific Industries for $460
million, officials announced Monday.
   The two companies had announced their agreement Oct. 12 on the
sale of Santa Fe Pacific Timber Co., which owns and manages about
520,000 acres of timberland in northern California.
   Sierra Pacific is a privately-held company based in Redding,
Calif.
   Closing on the timber company sale nearly completes Santa Fe's
restructuring program, leaving only one non-core business for sale,
the Black Mesa Pipeline.
   Before taxes, the company has taken in $880 million from the
sales, which included Robert E. McKee, a general building
contractor, Bankers Leasing and Financial Corp. and two pipeline
systems.
