<DOCNO> AP880229-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1714EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-Economy     02-29 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Economy,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goverment Steps Up Inflation Fight: Freezes Prices, Grants Small
Pay Hike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has authorized a 3 percent
increase in the minimum wage in March and ordered a freeze in
official prices and the value of the peso.
   The new measures, announced late Sunday, marked the government's
most aggressive attempt yet to rid the nation of its No. 1 economic
problem, inflation.
   President Miguel de la Madrid told a meeting of labor, business
and campesino leaders, ``The national motto is no increase in
prices in the month of March.''
   Labor leader Fidel Velazquez worried, though, that merchants
would quickly mark up their prices before Tuesday, the first day of
the freeze.
   ``Prices in March are going to try to be checked ... but last
night and today they have been raising them,'' he contended late
Sunday.
   The small increase in the minimum daily wage to 8,000 pesos _
about $3.50 _ was a blow to Velazquez and his 3 million-member
Mexican Labor Federation, which had been pushing for a 10 percent
gain.
   Workers, he said, have agreed to ``put the interests of the
country ahead of their own interests.''
   About half the nation's 25 million workers are estimated to earn
the minimum wage.
   Analysts calculate that the purchasing power of workers' making
the minimum pay has deteriorated to about half of what it was in
1978.
   De la Madrid said he was quickening the pace of his
inflation-fighting program, unveiled in mid-December, because fresh
price figures showed ``an important de-acceleration'' in February.
   Consumer prices, the president predicted, would rise in February
at about half the record 15.5 percent of January. Last week, the
government announced a a gain of 8.7 percent in prices in the first
half of February.
   Jonathan Heath, senior economist at the forecasting firm of
Macro Asesoria Economica, predicted an inflation rate of about 8.5
percent in February and 5 percent to 5.5 percent in March.
   The new economic program, he said, appears to be successful so
far. But, he added, ``we can't look at short-run indicators.''
   ``We want to see if it is a permanent drop and the government is
not inducing a temporary, artificial drop. We want to make sure
it's a permanent, once-and-for-all drop in inflation,'' he said.
   The government had been expected to release a target level that
would be used, starting Tuesday, to index wages and prices. The
indexation plan was designed as the centerpiece of the
anti-inflation program, called the Economic Solidarity Pact.
   The government drew up the Solidarity Pact because of worries
the nation was on the verge of hyper-inflation. Consumer prices
skyrocketed a record 159.2 percent last year.
   But in a surprise move, the president's office authorized the
smaller-than-expected increase in the minimum wage and ordered a
freeze on the prices of government-regulated and -controlled itms.
Such products range from gasoline and electricity to tortillas and
milk.
   It also urged private companies to join in the freeze,
refraining from marking up prices to make up for higher wage costs.
   Moreover, officials said the exchange rate for the peso will be
held steady in March at Monday's level. The Bank of Mexico, the
nation's central bank, trimmed the currency's value against the
dollar by 3 units each trading day in February.
   At midday Monday, the peso in free-market trading ranged from
2,300 pesos to the dollar to 2,360 pesos at the private firms. It
was 2,237-2,267 on Friday. The free rate is used in tourism and
border transactions.
   A second rate regulated by the government was 2,281 pesos to the
dollar. This rate, used in about 75 percent of all commercial
transaction, stood at 2,270 on Friday.
</TEXT>
