<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Northwest-Strike Bjt   02-29 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest-Strike, Bjt,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Flight Attendants Play Waiting Game</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union flight attendants for Northwest
Airlines were told by Teamsters officials Monday that a company
proposal to delay the promotion of B-scale workers to the
higher-paid A-scale bracket is the only major issue separating the
two sides in contract talks.
   About 150 of the company's 6,700 flight attendants were informed
of the situation at a rally at a Teamsters office less that two
miles away from the corporation's headquarters.
   An 11 p.m. Friday strike deadline passed without a settlement in
talks aimed at bring former Republic Airlines employees and their
Northwest counterparts under one contract. The employees have been
working under separate contracts since Northwest acquired Republic
in the fall of 1986.
   Talks broke down Saturday at dawn after an all-night bargaining
session with a federal mediator. But flight attendants have not
been called on to strike and the company has not exercised its
right to impose a contract on the flight attendants.
   Jeff Musto, a spokesman for the Teamsters, said Monday that no
talks have been held since Saturday and none are scheduled.
   ``We're still on red alert to strike,'' Musto. ``We want to keep
the company guessing.''
   As Musto explained, the one major issue left unresolved in the
negotiations are wages, which are governed under a two-tiered scale.
   All Northwest flight attendant were paid under one scale before
a 1982 contract created the B scale. All new employees hired since
then have started as B-scale employees at rates of pay lower than
the old system, Musto said.
   But the 1982 contract called for B-scale employees to jump to
A-scale levels in their sixth year of employment. The company has
proposed extending that wait until the ninth year of employment,
Musto said.
   For the average flight attendant, that would mean a loss of
$16,776 over the three years, Musto said.
   The company said the hourly wages it has proposed for the flight
attendants would make them the second-highest paid in the industry.
Musto said he agrees with that assessment, but he added that the
union has a commitment to flight attendants hired under the B-scale
not to break ``our promise'' that they would be promoted to the
A-scale in their sixth year.
   ``They could see light at the end of the tunnel,'' Musto said.
``Now all of a sudden the company is dangling the carrot out in
front of them a little further.''
   About a third of the company's flight attendants are at the
B-scale level, Musto said. By delaying their promotion to A-scale,
the majority of flight attendants would be under the B-scale when
it is time to negotiate the next contract.
   Then the company could win support for cutting the wages of
A-scale flight attendants because A-scale employees would be in the
minority, Musto said.
   Under Northwest's latest contract offer, base pay for senior
flight attendants would be about $35.18 an hour based on a 78-hour
work month, about half of what most Americans work. That would
increase to $36.60 an hour by May 1, 1991, the company said.
   William Wren said a large number of senior flight attendants
make more than $40,000 a year, plus meal payments when they're
working.
   Most entry-level flight attendants are making about $15,000 a
year, Wren said.
   The chief negotiator for the flight attendants, William Genoese,
was denied a request Monday to meet with Steven Rothmeier, chairman
and chief executive officer of the airline, Musto said.
   There was no further word Monday on whether pilots and mechanics
at Northwest would honor picket lines by the flight attendants.
Officials from the unions representing pilots and mechanics have
said they will wait to make a decision.
   Wren has said the mechanics are barred from sympathy strikes
under their contract and pilots are barred from sympathy strikes
under the Railway Labor Act.
   Wren said the company was operating under its normal flight
schedule Monday. About 2,000 non-union flight attendants are on
call to fill in if a strike is called, he has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0307 </DOCNO>
