<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AT&T-Unix     02-29 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AT&T-Unix,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T To Make Its Unix Available Equally to All</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. said Monday
it will make sure that its widely used Unix operating system, the
internal traffic cop of computers, is readily available to all the
computer hardware companies that want to use it.
   Some major computer companies had charged that AT&T was playing
favorites by giving early information about future versions of Unix
to Sun Microsystems Inc., a Silicon Valley maker of engineering
workstations that is a close partner of AT&T.
   ``People have had a big misconception about what the nature of
the agreement has been,'' Bill Klinger, an AT&T executive in charge
of Unix product management, said in an interview.
   Klinger said it would be a mistake for AT&T to play favorites
because that would delay the spread of Unix, an operating system
that is used mainly for scientific and engineering work.
   Motorola Inc. said Monday that the London-based UniSoft Group,
working closely with AT&T, would work to make sure that Unix runs
on computers that contain microprocessors made by Motorola.
   ``Combined with AT&T's support, this will ensure Motorola's
customers the same full and timely access as early as any
competitive architecture,'' Gary Tooker, Motorola's chief operating
officer, said in a news release.
   Motorola claims that 80 percent of all Unix-based computer
programs run on computers containing its microprocessors.
   Motorola's goal is to have programs run without modification on
any computer that uses one of its microprocessors.
</TEXT>
