<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2008EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Henley     02-29 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Henley,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Henley Posts Losses, Cites Investment Losses, Santa Fe Stock Costs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investment losses and high interest
expenses for money it borrowed to buy Santa Fe Southern Pacific
Corp. stock gave Henley Group large deficits for the fourth quarter
and all of 1987.
   However, the losses were 44 percent less for the quarter and 35
percent less for the year compared with the year-earlier periods,
the investment company said Monday.
   For the three months ended Dec. 31, the company said it lost
$197 million on revenues of $863 million, compared with a $354
million lossk on revenues of $825 million in the final period of
1986.
   For the full year, the company said it lost $278 million on
revenues of $3.52 billion, compared with a loss of $426 million on
revenues of $3.17 billion in 1986.
   The 1987 results reflected investment losses of $112 million for
the fourth quarter and $102 million for the year, plus higher
interest expense for loans to acquire 15.1 million shares of Santa
Fe, the Chicago-based railroad and natural resources concern that
Henley has been seeking to take over.
   In all, Henley owns 24.6 million, or 15.7 percent, of Santa Fe's
157.3 million shares.
   The 1986 results included $286 million in pretax restructuring
charges related to writedowns and asset revaluations.
   For nearly a year, Henley has been courting Santa Fe, but the
Chicago company has repeatedly spurned its unsolicited overtures.
   The 1987 results represent Henley's first full year as an
independent company.
   Henley was formed in 1986 from 35 construction, environmental,
energy, chemical, manufacturing and finance businesses spun off 1{
years earlier by Allied-Signal Corp., which itself was formed by a
$5 billion merger in mid-1985.
   Henley has focused on paring costs and improving results of the
operations, then spinning them off at a profit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
