<DOCNO> AP880229-0312 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1736EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     02-29 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0659</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices for livestock plunged Monday on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, and analysts blamed it on a ``nervousness''
over slaughter house shutdowns.
   Prices fell as much as 127 points, or 1.27 cents, and only one
contract, live hogs for delivery in December, managed to finish
higher.
   Selling interest in cattle was heightened by inactive cash
markets, traders said.
   ``Packers, with squeezed margins, have reduced their slaughters.
They're closing some plants and there's nervousness in market,''
said Tom Morgan, head of Sterling Research Corp. of Arlington
Heights, Ill.
   Live hog prices followed a lower cash market, and prices for
frozen pork bellies followed the lead of traders in the live hog
pit, Morgan said.
   Live cattle settled .40 cent to 1.12 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in April at 71.50 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .45 cent higher to 1.27 cents lower with March at 79.75
cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent higher to 1.07 cents lower
with April at 43.25 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25
cent to .63 cent higher with March at 51.85 cents a pound.
   Futures prices for corn and soybeans were up sharply while wheat
prices were mixed on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Some soybean contracts closed more than 10 cents above Friday's
prices.
   Lighter-than-expected delivery notices for soybeans helped
support higher soybeans prices, said Jerry Gidel, a grains analyst
in Chicago for G.H. Miller & Co.
   Wheat prices were supported by import interest from the
Phillippines, 175,000 tons worth, and talk that the Soviets may be
back in the market, Gidel said.
   Corn prices were restained somewhat by lower-than-expected
exports for that commodity, said Steve Freed, a grains analyst in
Chicago with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents lower to 1\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.15{ a bushel; corn was 2\
cents to 3 cents higher with March at $2.03} a bushel; oats were 2\
cents to 4\ cents higher with March at $1.94{ a bushel; and
soybeans were 8{ cents to 10{ cents higher with March at $6.36 a
bushel.
   Energy prices finished higher in moderate volume on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   The heating oil contract for March rose 1.46 cents because it
had been oversold at the end of last week, said Peter Beutel, a
petroleum analyst in New York with Elders Future Inc.
   Crude oil prices were supported by a recently published report
that production by Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
was lower than expected, he said.
   Crude oil settled 12 cents to 23 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in February at $15.49 a barrel; heating oil was .38
cent to 1.46 cents higher with February at 45.85 cents a gallon;
and unleaded gasoline was .41 cent to .70 cent higher with March at
45.71 cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver prices climbed higher on the Commodity Exchange
in New York.
   A technical adjustment, known as a short-covering rally, in
platinum trading _ where futures prices rose $25 a troy ounce _
triggered the higher prices in precious metals, said Marty McNeill,
a metals analyst in New York with Dominick & Dominick.
   In a short sale, a trader sells borrowed contracts in hopes of
replacing them _ or ``covering'' the sale _ later with others
bought at a lower price.
   ``Grains were up sharply, that always helps,'' he said. ``Oil
prices were rising, and the dollar was mixed among foreign
currencies. That played a part in the market, too.''
   Gold settled 10 cents to 90 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in March at $430.50 a troy ounce; and silver was 8.4 cents
to 9.7 cents higher with March at $6.23 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
