<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MCorp-EDS     02-29 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-MCorp-EDS,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MCorp Reaches Pact with EDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp officials on Monday reached a definitive
agreement to sell the company's 80.1 percent interest in MTech to
Electronic Data Systems Corp. for about $281 million in cash and
securities.
   Gene H. Bishop, chairman and chief executive officer of MCorp,
and Les Alberthal, EDS president and chief executive officer, made
the joint announcement.
   The Dallas-based EDS is a wholly owned subsidiary of General
Motors Corp.
   ``We are particularly pleased to reach this agreement with
EDS,'' Bishop said in a prepared statement. ``The transaction will
allow MCorp to realize significant value which has been previouosly
unrecognized.''
   The agreement's terms call for MCorp to get about $30 in cash
and securities for each MTech common share. The transaction,
subject to GM approval and satisfaction of other conditions, was
expected to be completed by April 15.
   Holders of MTech common stock and convertible debentures would
be offered the same package of cash and securities as that received
by MCorp. Public holders of MTech common stock would also get a
``cash election'' for payment entirely in cash at the rate of $30
per MTech share.
   Holders of MTech convertible debentures will be offered the
opportunity to receive $1,000 plus accrued interest for each
debenture.
   MTech has been an EDS competitor for some time, said EDS
spokesman Roger Still. MTech does business in 18 states with 1,400
financial institutions.
   ``We have no intention of laying off anybody,'' Still said.
``There's a lot of good talent at MTech. It would be really
premature to talk about any changes in their assets or management
structure.''
   About 19.9 percent of MTech is owned by individual stockholders,
said Still.
   MCorp is a financial services company with assets of $20.2
billion as of Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
