<HEAD>Pillsbury's Stafford Quits, Spoor Succeeds Him</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be updated.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John M. Stafford resigned as head of
Pillsbury Co. Monday, and will be replaced by former chief
executive William H. Spoor, who will come out of retirement to
assume those duties, the company said.
   The announcement was made in a prepared statement, which did not
indicate why Stafford resigned as chairman, president and chief
executive officer, nor why Spoor was elected by the company's board
of directors to replace him.
   Spokesmen for the company did not immediately return a
reporter's phone call seeking comment beyond the statement.
   Spoor, 65, returned to the company last September as chairman of
the executive committee. He had retired in 1985 after spending his
entire career with the company, the last 12 years as chairman and
chief executive.
   Spoor said shareholders and employees will long remember the
many contributions made to the company by Stafford.
   ``Jack Stafford has been totally dedicated to the success of
Pillsbury and to the values that make it great. We deeply
appreciate everything that he has achieved for this company over
the past decade,'' Spoor said.
   In addition to the above action, the board of directors
appointed a search committee to seek a chief executive for the
company to succeed Spoor.
