<DOCNO> AP880229-0319 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1821EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-RemakingCities Bjt   02-29 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Remaking Cities, Bjt,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel's Dead, Move On, Planners Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pittsburgh-area residents should wake up if
they're still dreaming that empty steel plants will come back to
life, say city planners from an international architecture
conference.
   ``You've got to face reality. They're gone,'' said Tony McGann,
whose hometown of Liverpool, England, lived through the decline of
dockyard industries. ``If you wait for the steel industry to come
back, you'll wait forever.''
   The planning team, 12 Americans and five Britons, toured
Monongahela Valley communities whose economies have been gutted by
the decline of steelmaking. They addressed about 100 Mon Valley
residents Saturday in Homestead and released a report Monday
suggesting how the once-thriving steel centers of Homestead,
Duquesne and McKeesport could recover.
   The planners' effort was organized by the American Institute of
Architects, a sponsor of this week's Remaking Cities Conference in
Pittsburgh. Britain's Prince Charles, an advocate of better city
planning, is scheduled to address the conference Saturday.
   Plants last operated by USX Corp. in Homestead, a river gateway
to Pittsburgh, could be leveled and replaced by five-acre flower
plots like those featured in European garden festivals, the
planners recommended.
   ``We can't use all the land at once. But if it looked green it
would be easier to sell,'' said team leader John Clarke of Trenton,
N.J.
   The planners envision turning one old ironmaking blast furnace
into a museum, developing the riverbank as a yacht landing and
perhaps within a decade building luxury riverfront homes.
   ``It's the greening of industrial America,'' British architect
Richard Burton said.
   ``It sounds innovative, anyway. Most of us around here though
were looking for things that were going to create more jobs,'' said
Robert Anderson, a founder of Homestead's Rainbow Kitchen, which
feeds about 100 unemployed people per day and distributes groceries
as needed to about 600 households.
   At its peak, about 15,000 workers were employed at the Homestead
plant. The last steel was rolled in May 1986.
   ``Few white knights are likely to ride into the Mon Valley and
bring thousands of jobs at once,'' the report said.
   The report recommended that a former USX plant site at
McKeesport be used for sports events, a giant flea market, a
discount sales center and a factory outlet.
   ``It's better than using it for a warehouse. It would employ
people and bring activity to downtown McKeesport,'' Clarke said.
   Duquesne seems best suited as a center for recycling trash or
converting it to energy, the report said.
   Homestead Councilwoman Betty Esper and Mike Stout, a member of
the Steel Valley Authority and Tri-State Conference on Steel, were
among the town meeting speakers who said steel plants should not be
redeveloped so quickly because the industry might need them again.
   ``You have to move forward. This is like a lingering divorce
that, until it is finally settled, is very painful, and even after
it's settled will be painful,'' said architect Michael Swartler of
New York.
   Longstanding dependence on one industry has left Mon Valley
communities with little experience in developing their economies,
Clarke said.
   ``We have heard from mayors who don't know what role they play
in development of the sites,'' he said. ``Our work is an
illustration of how to embark on that process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880229-0320 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 2019EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Whirlpool-Roper     02-29 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whirlpool-Roper,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whirlpool Buys Ga.-Based Appliance-Maker for $350 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whirlpool Corp. said Monday it has
reached an agreement to buy Roper Corp., an Augusta, Ga.-based
manufacturer of appliances and lawn equipment, for $350 million.
   Whirlpool, one of the nation's leading appliance makers with
$4.2 billion in sales last year, will pay $37.50 a share for all
outstanding stock in Roper, Whirlpool said.
   ``Acquiring Roper is a major step in our strategic plans for
growth and is evidence of our commitment to the major home
appliance marketplace,'' said David R. Whitwam, chairman and
president of Whirlpool.
   Charles Ryan, an analyst for Merrill Lynch in New York, said the
two companies were a ``good fit'' and each offered something that
the other needed.
   ``Ranges has been one of the weak areas for Whirlpool,'' which
now will have an internal source for them, he said. Roper, on the
other hand, faced the threat of a hostile takeover and found a
friendly suitor in Whirlpool, he said.
   Whirlpool had net income of $191.9 million in 1987, down from
$199.7 million one year earlier. Earnings from the two years were
the company's best of the last decade.
   Under the agreement, Robert Cook will remain as president of
Roper and will become a vice president of Whirlpool, Whitwam said.
   ``This new relationship with Whirlpool is outstanding for the
future of both companies and is excellent for our stockholders,
employees and customers,'' Cook said.
   Roper employs about 4,750 people at plants and offices in
Lafayette, Dalton, McRae and Swainsboro, Ga.; Kankake, Ill.;
Orangeburg, S.C.; Chattanooga, Tenn., Mississauga, Ontario. It had
sales of $703 million in the 12 months ending July 31, 1987.
   Roper produces electric and gas ranges, tillers, lawn mowers and
lawn and garden tractors.
   Like Whirlpool, Roper is a major supplier to Sears Roebuck &
Co., the nation's leading retailer. The companies produce
appliances that are sold under the Sears brand name.
   ``Joining forces with another reliable supplier of quality goods
to Sears can only serve to enhance the Whirlpool-Sears
relationship,'' Whitwam said.
</TEXT>
