<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Unemployment     02-29 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Unemployment,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan's Unemployment Rate Rises To 2.7 Percent In January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unemployment in Japan fell to a seasonally-adjusted
2.7 percent in January from 3.0 percent a year earlier, but was up
0.1 percentage point from the previous month, the government
announced Tuesday.
   The number of job holders rose during the one-year period by
1.12 million to 58.28 million, an increase of 1.9 percent,
according to the Statistics Bureau of the Prime Minister's Office.
   Bureau officials said the number of people employed rose sharply
in the latter half of the year as the economy recovered from the
effects of the higher value of the Japanese yen. The strong yen
curbed overseas sales and earnings and forced Japanese
manufacturers, particularly shipbuilders and steelmakers, to slash
production and manpower.
   After hitting a record 3.2 percent last May, Japan's
unemployment rate has drifted lower as manufacturers adjusted to
the high yen.
   Japan's unemployment rate would be higher if calculated by U.S.
and European methods.
   In Japan, members of the armed forces and people who worked more
than one hour during the last week of the month are counted as
employed. In the United States, military personnel are not included
in the work force and those who work less than 15 hours a week are
considered unemployed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
